{"title_page": "National Union Party (United States)", "text_new": "{{short description|Political party}}\n{{distinguish|Constitutional Union Party (United States)}}\n\n{{Infobox political party\n| colorcode = {{National Union Party (United States)/meta/color}}\n| name = National Union Party\n| logo = Republican presidential ticket 1864b.jpg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| leader1_title = Leaders\n| leader1_name = {{ubl\n | [[Abraham Lincoln]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] President)\n | [[Andrew Johnson]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] Vice President)\n}}\n| foundation = {{start date|1864|5|21}}\n| dissolution = {{end date|1868|11|3}}\n| merger = {{\u2022}}[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]<br>{{\u2022}}[[Unionist Party (United States)|Unionist Party]]<br>{{\u2022}}[[War Democrats]]\n| merged = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]<br />[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]\n| headquarters = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| ideology = [[Abolitionism in the United States|Abolitionism]]<br>[[Reconstruction Era|Reconstructionism]]<br>[[Union (American Civil War)|Unionism]]\n| colors = {{color box|#CC0C2F|border=darkgray}} [[Red]], {{color box|#FFFFFF|border=darkgray}} [[white]] and {{color box|#002C77|border=darkgray}} [[blue]]<br>([[Flag of the United States|United States national colors]])\n| seats1_title = Senate (1864)\n| seats1 = {{composition bar|42|54|hex=#CC0C2F}}\n| seats2_title = House of<br>Representatives (1864)\n| seats2 = {{composition bar|149|193|hex=#CC0C2F}}\n| country = United States\n}}\n\nThe '''National Union Party''' was the temporary name used by the [[History of the United States Republican Party|Republican Party]] for the national ticket in the [[1864 United States presidential election|1864 presidential election]] that was held during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]]. For the most part, state Republican parties did not change their name.<ref>[[Arthur Schlesinger, Jr.]], ed. ''History of U.S. Political Parties: vol II: 1860\u20131910''  (1973) 2:1287.</ref> The temporary name was used to attract [[War Democrat]]s and [[Border states (American Civil War)|border states]], [[Unconditional Union Party|Unconditional Unionists]] and [[Unionist Party (United States)|Unionist Party]] members  who would not vote for the Republican Party. The party nominated incumbent Republican [[List of presidents of the United States |President]] [[Abraham Lincoln]] and for Democrat [[List of vice presidents of the United States |Vice President]] [[Andrew Johnson]], who were elected in an electoral [[Landslide victory|landslide]].\n\n== Establishment ==\nThe National Union Party was created prior to the General Election of November 1864, when the Civil War was still in progress. A faction of anti-Lincoln [[Radical Republican]]s held the belief that Lincoln was incompetent and therefore could not be reelected. A number of Radical Republicans formed a party called the [[Radical Democracy Party (United States)|Radical Democracy Party]] and a few hundred delegates met in [[Cleveland, Ohio|Cleveland]] starting on May 31, 1864, eventually nominating [[John C. Fr\u00e9mont]], who had also been the Republicans' first presidential standard-bearer during the [[1856 United States presidential election|1856 presidential election]].\n\n=== Baltimore Convention ===\nRepublicans loyal to Lincoln created a new name for their party in convention at [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]] during the first week in June 1864 in order to accommodate the [[War Democrat]]s who supported the war and wished to separate themselves from the [[Copperheads (politics)|Copperheads]]. This is the main reason why War Democrat [[Andrew Johnson]] was selected to be the vice presidential nominee as then-current Vice President [[Hannibal Hamlin]] was not nominated. The National Unionists supporting the Lincoln\u2013Johnson ticket also hoped that the new party would stress the national character of the war.\n\nThe convention's temporary chairman, [[Robert Jefferson Breckinridge]] of Kentucky, explained that he could support Lincoln on this new ticket for the following reason:<ref>[[John G. Nicolay]] and [[John Hay]], ''Abraham Lincoln: A History'' (1890) 9:66.</ref> {{cquote|As a Union party I will follow you to the ends of the earth, and to the gates of death. But as an Abolition party, as a Republican party, as a Whig party, as a Democratic party, as an American [Know-Nothing] party, I will not follow you one foot.}}\n\nThe National Union Party adopted the following goals as its platform: {{cquote|[P]ursuit of the war until the Confederacy surrendered unconditionally; a constitutional amendment for the abolition of slavery; aid to disabled Union veterans; continued European neutrality; enforcement of the [[Monroe Doctrine]]; encouragement of immigration; and construction of a transcontinental railroad. It also praised the use of black troops and Lincoln's management of the war.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.harpweek.com/1864/Overview-1864-2.htm#Convention|title=HarpWeek &#124; Elections &#124; 1864 Overview|publisher=Elections.harpweek.com|accessdate=October 12, 2013}}</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Abraham Lincoln head on shoulders photo portrait.jpg|thumb|1864 National Union Party presidential nominee, [[Abraham Lincoln]]]]\n[[File:Andrew Johnson photo portrait head and shoulders, c1870-1880-Edit1.jpg|thumb|1864 National Union Party vice presidential nominee, [[Andrew Johnson]]]]\nNews of his nomination at the [[1864 Republican National Convention|1864 National Union Convention]] elicited Lincoln's famous response on June 9, 1864: {{cquote|I am very grateful for the renewed confidence which has been accorded to me, both by the convention and by the National [Union] League. I am not insensible at all to the personal compliment there is in this; yet I do not allow myself to believe that any but a small portion of it is to be appropriated as a personal compliment. The convention and the nation, I am assured, are alike animated by a higher view of the interests of the country for the present and the great future, and that part I am entitled to appropriate as a compliment is only that part which I may lay hold of as being the opinion of the convention and of the League, that I am not entirely unworthy to be entrusted with the place I have occupied for the last three years. I have not permitted myself, gentlemen, to conclude that I am the best man in the country; but I am reminded, in this connection, of a story of an old Dutch farmer, who remarked to a companion once that 'it was not best to swap horses when crossing streams.'}}\n\nIn August 1864, Lincoln wrote and signed a pledge that should he lose the election, he would nonetheless defeat the Confederacy by an all-out military effort before turning over the White House:<ref>[[Mark Grimsley]] and [[Brooks D. Simpson]], eds. ''The Collapse of the Confederacy'' (2001) p. 80.</ref> {{cquote|This morning, as for some days past, it seems exceedingly probable that this Administration will not be re-elected. Then it will be my duty to so co-operate with the President elect, as to save the Union between the election and the [[inauguration]]; as he will have secured his election on such ground that he cannot possibly save it afterward.<ref>Lincoln, Memorandum concerning his probable failure of re-election, August 23, 1864. ''Collected Works of Abraham Lincoln'' (1953), vol. 7, p. 514.</ref>}}\n\nLincoln did not show the pledge to his cabinet, but asked them to sign the sealed envelope.\n\n== Changing mood ==\nThe complexion of the war changed as the election approached. [[Confederate States of America|Confederate Commander]] [[Robert E. Lee]]'s last victory in battle occurred June 3, 1864 at [[Cold Harbor]]. Union General [[Ulysses S. Grant]]'s aggressive tactics trapped Lee in the trenches defending Richmond. Admiral [[David Farragut]] successfully shut down Mobile Bay as a Confederate resource in the [[Battle of Mobile Bay]] on August 3\u201323, 1864. Most decisive of all, Union General [[William Tecumseh Sherman]] captured Atlanta on September 1, 1864, convincing even the pessimists that the Confederacy was collapsing.<ref>[[Allan Nevins]], ''War for the Union'' 4:97\u201398, 120\u2013122.</ref>\n\n== Fr\u00e9mont withdraws ==\nFr\u00e9mont and his fellow Republicans hated their former ally [[United States Postmaster General|Postmaster General]] [[Montgomery Blair]]. Fr\u00e9mont, aware that his candidacy could result in victory for the Democrats, made a deal to drop out of the presidential race in exchange for Blair's removal from office. On September 22, 1864, Fr\u00e9mont dropped out of the race. On September 23, Lincoln asked for and received Blair's resignation. The National Union ticket went on to win handily in the [[1864 United States presidential election|election of 1864]], defeating the [[History of the Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] ticket of General [[George B. McClellan]] (whom Lincoln had previously relieved of his command) and [[George H. Pendleton]].\n\n== Election ==\n[[File:AL1864A.JPG|thumb|The [[History of the United States Republican Party|Republican Party]] called itself the Union Party in 1864 and gave out this ballot for supporters to vote for Lincoln]]\nIn the [[United States House election, 1864|1864 congressional elections]], the party won 42 [[United States Senate|Senate]] seats (out of 54 senators seated, not including vacancies due to the secession of Confederate states) and 149 seats (out of 193) in the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.harpweek.com/1864/Overview-1864-2.htm#results|title=Elections: 1864 Overview|publisher=HarpWeek|accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref> These candidates ran under various party names, including National Union, Republican and Unconditional Union, but were part of the overall Republican/National Union effort.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The 39th Congress (1865\u20131867) and the 14th Amendment: Some Preliminary Perspectives|first=Richard L.|last=Aynes|work=Akron Law Review|volume=42|issue=4|year=2009|pages=1022|url=http://www.uakron.edu/law/lawreview/v42/docs/aynes.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404155652/http://www.uakron.edu/law/lawreview/v42/docs/aynes.pdf|archivedate=April 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Post-Lincoln: Andrew Johnson presidency (1865-69) ==\n{{see also|Andrew Johnson presidency}}\nUpon [[Assassination of Abraham Lincoln|Lincoln's death]] in 1865, [[Andrew Johnson]] became the only other National Union President.\n\nAfter the bitter break with the Republicans in Congress over [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]] policies, Johnson used federal [[patronage]] to build up a party of loyalists, but it proved to be unsuccessful.<ref>[[Hans Trefousse]], ''Andrew Johnson: A Biography'' (1998) ch. 11\u201312.</ref> Johnson's friends sponsored the [[1866 National Union Convention]] in August 1866 in Philadelphia as part of his attempt at maintaining a coalition of supporters. The convention sought to bring together moderate and conservative Republicans and defecting Democrats and forge an unbeatable coalition behind President Johnson and his Reconstruction policy.<ref>Thomas Wagstaff,  \"The Arm-In-Arm Convention,\" ''Civil War History''; 1968 14(2): 101\u2013119.</ref>\n\nIn the fall of 1866, Johnson embarked upon a speaking tour (known as the \"[[Swing Around the Circle]]\") before the 1866 Congressional elections to attempt to garner support for his policies. His swing was heavily ridiculed and proved ineffective as more of his opponents were elected. [[Republican National Committee]] chairman [[Henry Jarvis Raymond]] (1864\u20131866) lost the regard of the Republicans for his participation in the convention. The National Union movement became little more than the Democratic Party in a new form as Republicans left the movement and returned to the old party fold by the fall.<ref>Patrick W. Riddleberger, ''1866: The Critical Year Revisited'' (1979).</ref>\n\n[[File:Grant-Colfax.png|thumb|260px|[[Ulysses S. Grant]]/[[Schuyler Colfax]] 1868 National Union Republican campaign poster]]\nThe last congressman to represent the National Union Party ended his affiliation with the party in March 1867. Johnson was [[Impeachment of Andrew Johnson|impeached]] by the Republican-led House of Representatives in 1868 and was acquitted in the Senate by one vote. Upon the 1869 expiration of Johnson's only term as President, the National Union Party came to an end. The platform adopted at the [[1868 Republican National Convention]] strongly repudiated President Johnson<ref>[http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/index.php?pid=29622 \"Republican Party Platform of 1868\"].</ref> while the platform adopted by the [[1868 Democratic National Convention]] thanked Johnson.<ref>[http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/index.php?pid=29579 \"Democratic Party Platform of 1868\"].</ref> Johnson received dozens of votes on the first ballot of the Democratic convention, but the party ultimately nominated [[Horatio Seymour]]. Meanwhile, the mainline Republicans decided at their 1868 national convention to use the term the National Union Republican Convention. The 1868 National Union Republican delegates nominated [[Ulysses S. Grant]] for President and his running mate [[Schuyler Colfax]] for Vice President. In 1872, all reference to Union had disappeared.<ref>Schlesinger, 2:1287.</ref> Historians regard the initial National Union coalition assembled in 1864 as part of the Republican Party lineage and heritage.<ref>The standard multivolume history includes it with the Republican Party and does not give it a separate entry. Arthur Schlesinger, Jr. ed. ''History of U.S. Political Parties: vol II: 1860\u20131910'' (1973).</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the National Union Party would be revived, albeit in an unofficial way by [[state of Washington|Washington State]] [[perennial candidate]] [[Mike The Mover]] (born Michael Patrick Shanks). Mike is not a member of the Republicans [[Independent politician|or any other political party]]. Despite this, during the 2014 congressional election for [[Washington's 1st congressional district]], he ran as a candidate for the National Union Party, taking advantage of an election law in the state where candidates can declare themselves a member of any party, even if that party doesn't exist.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20140515070440/http://www.kingcounty.gov/elections/candidatefiling/whohasfiled.aspx</ref> Mike is a fan of Civil War history<ref>http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/congressional-district-no-1-representative/Content?oid=11929</ref> and this interest probably influenced his choice.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[1866 National Union Convention]]\n* [[History of the United States Democratic Party]]\n* [[History of the United States Republican Party]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* [[David Herbert Donald|Donald, David]] (1996). ''Lincoln''. [https://www.amazon.com/Lincoln-David-Herbert-Donald/dp/068482535X/ Excerpt and text search]. pp. 516\u2013544.\n* Johnson, David (2012). ''Decided on the Battlefield: Grant, Sherman, Lincoln and the Election of 1864''. \n* [[Allan Nevins|Nevins, Allan]] (1971). ''The War for the Union: The Organized war to Victory, 1864\u20131865''.  pp 97\u2013143.\n* [[John G. Nicolay|Nicolay, John G.]] and [[John Hay]] (1890). ''Abraham Lincoln: A History''. vol 9. ch 3, 15 and 16.\n* McSeveney, Samuel T. (1986). \"Re-Electing Lincoln: The Union Party Campaign and the Military Vote in Connecticut\". ''Civil War History''. 32(2). pp. 139\u2013158.\n* [[John C. Waugh|Waugh, John C.]] (2001). ''Reelecting Lincoln: The Battle For The 1864 Presidency''. [https://www.amazon.com/Reelecting-Lincoln-Battle-1864-Presidency/dp/0306810220/ Excerpt and text search].\n* Zornow, William Frank (1954). ''Lincoln and the Party Divided''.\n{{Authority control}}\n{{United States political parties}}\n{{Abraham Lincoln|state=expanded}}\n{{American Civil War}}{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:American Civil War political groups]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1864]]\n[[Category:1864 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Defunct political parties in the United States]]\n[[Category:Republican Party (United States)]]\n[[Category:1864 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct political party alliances]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Political party}}\n{{distinguish|Constitutional Union Party (United States)}}\n\n{{Infobox political party\n| colorcode = {{National Union Party (United States)/meta/color}}\n| name = National Union Party\n| logo = Republican presidential ticket 1864b.jpg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| leader1_title = Leaders\n| leader1_name = {{ubl\n | [[Abraham Lincoln]]\n | [[Andrew Johnson]]\n}}\n| foundation = {{start date|1864|5|21}}\n| dissolution = {{end date|1868|11|3}}\n| merger = {{\u2022}}[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]<br>{{\u2022}}[[Unionist Party (United States)|Unionist Party]]<br>{{\u2022}}[[War Democrats]]\n| merged = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]<br />[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]\n| headquarters = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| ideology = [[Abolitionism in the United States|Abolitionism]]<br>[[Reconstruction Era|Reconstructionism]]<br>[[Union (American Civil War)|Unionism]]\n| colors = {{color box|#CC0C2F|border=darkgray}} [[Red]], {{color box|#FFFFFF|border=darkgray}} [[white]] and {{color box|#002C77|border=darkgray}} [[blue]]<br>([[Flag of the United States|United States national colors]])\n| seats1_title = Senate (1864)\n| seats1 = {{composition bar|42|54|hex=#CC0C2F}}\n| seats2_title = House of<br>Representatives (1864)\n| seats2 = {{composition bar|149|193|hex=#CC0C2F}}\n| country = United States\n}}\n\nThe '''National Union Party''' was the temporary name used by the [[History of the United States Republican Party|Republican Party]] for the national ticket in the [[1864 United States presidential election|1864 presidential election]] that was held during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]]. For the most part, state Republican parties did not change their name.<ref>[[Arthur Schlesinger, Jr.]], ed. ''History of U.S. Political Parties: vol II: 1860\u20131910''  (1973) 2:1287.</ref> The temporary name was used to attract [[War Democrat]]s and [[Border states (American Civil War)|border states]], [[Unconditional Union Party|Unconditional Unionists]] and [[Unionist Party (United States)|Unionist Party]] members  who would not vote for the Republican Party. The party nominated incumbent Republican [[List of presidents of the United States |President]] [[Abraham Lincoln]] and for Democrat [[List of vice presidents of the United States |Vice President]] [[Andrew Johnson]], who were elected in an electoral [[Landslide victory|landslide]].\n\n== Establishment ==\nThe National Union Party was created prior to the General Election of November 1864, when the Civil War was still in progress. A faction of anti-Lincoln [[Radical Republican]]s held the belief that Lincoln was incompetent and therefore could not be reelected. A number of Radical Republicans formed a party called the [[Radical Democracy Party (United States)|Radical Democracy Party]] and a few hundred delegates met in [[Cleveland, Ohio|Cleveland]] starting on May 31, 1864, eventually nominating [[John C. Fr\u00e9mont]], who had also been the Republicans' first presidential standard-bearer during the [[1856 United States presidential election|1856 presidential election]].\n\n=== Baltimore Convention ===\nRepublicans loyal to Lincoln created a new name for their party in convention at [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]] during the first week in June 1864 in order to accommodate the [[War Democrat]]s who supported the war and wished to separate themselves from the [[Copperheads (politics)|Copperheads]]. This is the main reason why War Democrat [[Andrew Johnson]] was selected to be the vice presidential nominee as then-current Vice President [[Hannibal Hamlin]] was not nominated. The National Unionists supporting the Lincoln\u2013Johnson ticket also hoped that the new party would stress the national character of the war.\n\nThe convention's temporary chairman, [[Robert Jefferson Breckinridge]] of Kentucky, explained that he could support Lincoln on this new ticket for the following reason:<ref>[[John G. Nicolay]] and [[John Hay]], ''Abraham Lincoln: A History'' (1890) 9:66.</ref> {{cquote|As a Union party I will follow you to the ends of the earth, and to the gates of death. But as an Abolition party, as a Republican party, as a Whig party, as a Democratic party, as an American [Know-Nothing] party, I will not follow you one foot.}}\n\nThe National Union Party adopted the following goals as its platform: {{cquote|[P]ursuit of the war until the Confederacy surrendered unconditionally; a constitutional amendment for the abolition of slavery; aid to disabled Union veterans; continued European neutrality; enforcement of the [[Monroe Doctrine]]; encouragement of immigration; and construction of a transcontinental railroad. It also praised the use of black troops and Lincoln's management of the war.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.harpweek.com/1864/Overview-1864-2.htm#Convention|title=HarpWeek &#124; Elections &#124; 1864 Overview|publisher=Elections.harpweek.com|accessdate=October 12, 2013}}</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Abraham Lincoln head on shoulders photo portrait.jpg|thumb|1864 National Union Party presidential nominee, [[Abraham Lincoln]]]]\n[[File:Andrew Johnson photo portrait head and shoulders, c1870-1880-Edit1.jpg|thumb|1864 National Union Party vice presidential nominee, [[Andrew Johnson]]]]\nNews of his nomination at the [[1864 Republican National Convention|1864 National Union Convention]] elicited Lincoln's famous response on June 9, 1864: {{cquote|I am very grateful for the renewed confidence which has been accorded to me, both by the convention and by the National [Union] League. I am not insensible at all to the personal compliment there is in this; yet I do not allow myself to believe that any but a small portion of it is to be appropriated as a personal compliment. The convention and the nation, I am assured, are alike animated by a higher view of the interests of the country for the present and the great future, and that part I am entitled to appropriate as a compliment is only that part which I may lay hold of as being the opinion of the convention and of the League, that I am not entirely unworthy to be entrusted with the place I have occupied for the last three years. I have not permitted myself, gentlemen, to conclude that I am the best man in the country; but I am reminded, in this connection, of a story of an old Dutch farmer, who remarked to a companion once that 'it was not best to swap horses when crossing streams.'}}\n\nIn August 1864, Lincoln wrote and signed a pledge that should he lose the election, he would nonetheless defeat the Confederacy by an all-out military effort before turning over the White House:<ref>[[Mark Grimsley]] and [[Brooks D. Simpson]], eds. ''The Collapse of the Confederacy'' (2001) p. 80.</ref> {{cquote|This morning, as for some days past, it seems exceedingly probable that this Administration will not be re-elected. Then it will be my duty to so co-operate with the President elect, as to save the Union between the election and the [[inauguration]]; as he will have secured his election on such ground that he cannot possibly save it afterward.<ref>Lincoln, Memorandum concerning his probable failure of re-election, August 23, 1864. ''Collected Works of Abraham Lincoln'' (1953), vol. 7, p. 514.</ref>}}\n\nLincoln did not show the pledge to his cabinet, but asked them to sign the sealed envelope.\n\n== Changing mood ==\nThe complexion of the war changed as the election approached. [[Confederate States of America|Confederate Commander]] [[Robert E. Lee]]'s last victory in battle occurred June 3, 1864 at [[Cold Harbor]]. Union General [[Ulysses S. Grant]]'s aggressive tactics trapped Lee in the trenches defending Richmond. Admiral [[David Farragut]] successfully shut down Mobile Bay as a Confederate resource in the [[Battle of Mobile Bay]] on August 3\u201323, 1864. Most decisive of all, Union General [[William Tecumseh Sherman]] captured Atlanta on September 1, 1864, convincing even the pessimists that the Confederacy was collapsing.<ref>[[Allan Nevins]], ''War for the Union'' 4:97\u201398, 120\u2013122.</ref>\n\n== Fr\u00e9mont withdraws ==\nFr\u00e9mont and his fellow Republicans hated their former ally [[United States Postmaster General|Postmaster General]] [[Montgomery Blair]]. Fr\u00e9mont, aware that his candidacy could result in victory for the Democrats, made a deal to drop out of the presidential race in exchange for Blair's removal from office. On September 22, 1864, Fr\u00e9mont dropped out of the race. On September 23, Lincoln asked for and received Blair's resignation. The National Union ticket went on to win handily in the [[1864 United States presidential election|election of 1864]], defeating the [[History of the Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] ticket of General [[George B. McClellan]] (whom Lincoln had previously relieved of his command) and [[George H. Pendleton]].\n\n== Election ==\n[[File:AL1864A.JPG|thumb|The [[History of the United States Republican Party|Republican Party]] called itself the Union Party in 1864 and gave out this ballot for supporters to vote for Lincoln]]\nIn the [[United States House election, 1864|1864 congressional elections]], the party won 42 [[United States Senate|Senate]] seats (out of 54 senators seated, not including vacancies due to the secession of Confederate states) and 149 seats (out of 193) in the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.harpweek.com/1864/Overview-1864-2.htm#results|title=Elections: 1864 Overview|publisher=HarpWeek|accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref> These candidates ran under various party names, including National Union, Republican and Unconditional Union, but were part of the overall Republican/National Union effort.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The 39th Congress (1865\u20131867) and the 14th Amendment: Some Preliminary Perspectives|first=Richard L.|last=Aynes|work=Akron Law Review|volume=42|issue=4|year=2009|pages=1022|url=http://www.uakron.edu/law/lawreview/v42/docs/aynes.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404155652/http://www.uakron.edu/law/lawreview/v42/docs/aynes.pdf|archivedate=April 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Post-Lincoln: Andrew Johnson presidency (1865-69) ==\n{{see also|Andrew Johnson presidency}}\nUpon [[Assassination of Abraham Lincoln|Lincoln's death]] in 1865, [[Andrew Johnson]] became the only other National Union President.\n\nAfter the bitter break with the Republicans in Congress over [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]] policies, Johnson used federal [[patronage]] to build up a party of loyalists, but it proved to be unsuccessful.<ref>[[Hans Trefousse]], ''Andrew Johnson: A Biography'' (1998) ch. 11\u201312.</ref> Johnson's friends sponsored the [[1866 National Union Convention]] in August 1866 in Philadelphia as part of his attempt at maintaining a coalition of supporters. The convention sought to bring together moderate and conservative Republicans and defecting Democrats and forge an unbeatable coalition behind President Johnson and his Reconstruction policy.<ref>Thomas Wagstaff,  \"The Arm-In-Arm Convention,\" ''Civil War History''; 1968 14(2): 101\u2013119.</ref>\n\nIn the fall of 1866, Johnson embarked upon a speaking tour (known as the \"[[Swing Around the Circle]]\") before the 1866 Congressional elections to attempt to garner support for his policies. His swing was heavily ridiculed and proved ineffective as more of his opponents were elected. [[Republican National Committee]] chairman [[Henry Jarvis Raymond]] (1864\u20131866) lost the regard of the Republicans for his participation in the convention. The National Union movement became little more than the Democratic Party in a new form as Republicans left the movement and returned to the old party fold by the fall.<ref>Patrick W. Riddleberger, ''1866: The Critical Year Revisited'' (1979).</ref>\n\n[[File:Grant-Colfax.png|thumb|260px|[[Ulysses S. Grant]]/[[Schuyler Colfax]] 1868 National Union Republican campaign poster]]\nThe last congressman to represent the National Union Party ended his affiliation with the party in March 1867. Johnson was [[Impeachment of Andrew Johnson|impeached]] by the Republican-led House of Representatives in 1868 and was acquitted in the Senate by one vote. Upon the 1869 expiration of Johnson's only term as President, the National Union Party came to an end. The platform adopted at the [[1868 Republican National Convention]] strongly repudiated President Johnson<ref>[http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/index.php?pid=29622 \"Republican Party Platform of 1868\"].</ref> while the platform adopted by the [[1868 Democratic National Convention]] thanked Johnson.<ref>[http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/index.php?pid=29579 \"Democratic Party Platform of 1868\"].</ref> Johnson received dozens of votes on the first ballot of the Democratic convention, but the party ultimately nominated [[Horatio Seymour]]. Meanwhile, the mainline Republicans decided at their 1868 national convention to use the term the National Union Republican Convention. The 1868 National Union Republican delegates nominated [[Ulysses S. Grant]] for President and his running mate [[Schuyler Colfax]] for Vice President. In 1872, all reference to Union had disappeared.<ref>Schlesinger, 2:1287.</ref> Historians regard the initial National Union coalition assembled in 1864 as part of the Republican Party lineage and heritage.<ref>The standard multivolume history includes it with the Republican Party and does not give it a separate entry. Arthur Schlesinger, Jr. ed. ''History of U.S. Political Parties: vol II: 1860\u20131910'' (1973).</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the National Union Party would be revived, albeit in an unofficial way by [[state of Washington|Washington State]] [[perennial candidate]] [[Mike The Mover]] (born Michael Patrick Shanks). Mike is not a member of the Republicans [[Independent politician|or any other political party]]. Despite this, during the 2014 congressional election for [[Washington's 1st congressional district]], he ran as a candidate for the National Union Party, taking advantage of an election law in the state where candidates can declare themselves a member of any party, even if that party doesn't exist.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20140515070440/http://www.kingcounty.gov/elections/candidatefiling/whohasfiled.aspx</ref> Mike is a fan of Civil War history<ref>http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/congressional-district-no-1-representative/Content?oid=11929</ref> and this interest probably influenced his choice.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[1866 National Union Convention]]\n* [[History of the United States Democratic Party]]\n* [[History of the United States Republican Party]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* [[David Herbert Donald|Donald, David]] (1996). ''Lincoln''. [https://www.amazon.com/Lincoln-David-Herbert-Donald/dp/068482535X/ Excerpt and text search]. pp. 516\u2013544.\n* Johnson, David (2012). ''Decided on the Battlefield: Grant, Sherman, Lincoln and the Election of 1864''. \n* [[Allan Nevins|Nevins, Allan]] (1971). ''The War for the Union: The Organized war to Victory, 1864\u20131865''.  pp 97\u2013143.\n* [[John G. Nicolay|Nicolay, John G.]] and [[John Hay]] (1890). ''Abraham Lincoln: A History''. vol 9. ch 3, 15 and 16.\n* McSeveney, Samuel T. (1986). \"Re-Electing Lincoln: The Union Party Campaign and the Military Vote in Connecticut\". ''Civil War History''. 32(2). pp. 139\u2013158.\n* [[John C. Waugh|Waugh, John C.]] (2001). ''Reelecting Lincoln: The Battle For The 1864 Presidency''. [https://www.amazon.com/Reelecting-Lincoln-Battle-1864-Presidency/dp/0306810220/ Excerpt and text search].\n* Zornow, William Frank (1954). ''Lincoln and the Party Divided''.\n{{Authority control}}\n{{United States political parties}}\n{{Abraham Lincoln|state=expanded}}\n{{American Civil War}}{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:American Civil War political groups]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1864]]\n[[Category:1864 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Defunct political parties in the United States]]\n[[Category:Republican Party (United States)]]\n[[Category:1864 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct political party alliances]]\n", "name_user": "Marxistfounder", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Union_Party_(United_States)"}
{"title_page": "Sathi Leelavathi (1936 film)", "text_new": "{{About|the 1936 film|the 1995 film|Sathi Leelavathi (1995 film)}}\n{{short description|1936 film by Ellis R. Dungan}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Sathi Leelavathi\n| image          = Sathi Leelavathi (1936 film).jpg\n| alt            = Landscape black-and-white poster with the film's title in English\n| caption        = Theatrical poster\n| director       = [[Ellis R. Dungan]]\n| producer       = A. N. Marudachalam Chettiar\n| screenplay     = Madras Kandaswamy Mudaliar\n| based_on       = {{based on|''Sathi Leelavathi''|[[S. S. Vasan]]}}\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[M. K. Radha]]|M. R. Gnanambal}}\n| cinematography = {{ubl|D. T. Telang|V. J. Shave}}\n| editing        = {{ubl|Sircar|Ellis R. Dungan}}\n| studio         = Manorama Films\n| released       = {{film date|1936|3|28|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 200 minutes<!-- 18,000 feet -->\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n}}\n\n'''''Sathi Leelavathi''''' ({{IPA-ta|sat\u032ai l\u032ai\u02d0l\u032aa\u02d0\u028bat\u032ai|pron}}, {{trans|''Leelavathi, the Chaste Wife''}}) is a 1936 [[Tamil language|Tamil-language]] Indian [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[Ellis R. Dungan]] and written by Madras Kandaswamy Mudaliar. It is based on [[S. S. Vasan]]'s novel of the same name, which had been [[Serial (literature)|serialised]] in 1934. [[M. K. Radha]] stars as Krishnamurthy, a man from [[Chennai|Madras]], who is lured into drinking alcohol by an acquaintance. Believing he murdered his friend in a drunken stupor, Krishnamurthy flees to [[Sri Lanka|Ceylon]] while his wife and daughter, played by M. R. Gnanambal and M. K. Mani respectively, are reduced to poverty. [[T. S. Balaiah]], [[M. G. Ramachandran]], [[M. V. Mani]] and P. Nammalvar appear in supporting roles.\n\nA. N. Marudachalam Chettiar initially wanted to produce a film version of the Madurai Original Boys Company (MOBC) play ''Pathi Bhakthi'', but realised [[Pathi Bhakthi|an adaptation]] was already being made. Chettiar then learnt about Vasan's novel, which had a similar plot and obtained the rights to make a film version. ''Sathi Leelavathi'' was Dungan's directorial debut and the film-acting debuts of Radha, Balaiah, Ramachandran and [[K. A. Thangavelu]]. It was [[N. S. Krishnan]]'s first film appearance, but his second release. The film was mostly shot at Vel Pictures Studio in Madras. D. T. Telang and V. J. Shave were the cinematographers, and the film was co-edited by Dungan and Sircar.\n\n''Sathi Leelavathi'' explores themes of [[Temperance movement in India|temperance]], social reform, the [[Gandhism|Gandhian]] concept of selfless service and the plight of labourers. It was one of the earliest Tamil films to be involved in a plagiarism controversy; the MOBC accused Chettiar and Mudaliar of plagiarising their play. The case was resolved after Vasan testified that both the play and the novel were based on ''Danesbury House'', an 1860 novel written by [[Ellen Wood (author)|Ellen Wood]], so neither party could claim originality. The film premiered on 1 February 1936 in Madras and was released theatrically on 28 March. It was a commercial success and made Dungan a sought-after director. Several features of his direction, including shooting by schedule, camera mobility, cabaret dances and less-theatrical acting, became staples of [[Tamil cinema]]. No complete print of the film is known to survive, making it a [[List of incomplete or partially lost films|partially lost film]].\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Plot ==\nKrishnamurthy is a wealthy man who lives in [[Chennai|Madras]] with his wife Leelavathi and their daughter Lakshmi. At a mock tea party, Krishnamurthy's acquaintance Ramanathan persuades him to drink alcohol. Ramanathan's collaborator is Rangiah Naidu, a corrupt police inspector. Krishnamurthy becomes infatuated by Mohanangi, a promiscuous woman, and promises to pay her {{INR}}50,000 (about US$18,700 in 1936).{{efn|name=exchange1936}}\n\nParasuraman, Krishnamurthy's friend, tries but fails to reform him. A [[Marwari people|Marvadi]] man who lent money to Krishnamurthy obtains a [[Warrant of payment|repayment warrant]], sinking Krishnamurthy deeper in debt. Krishnamurthy drunkenly accuses Leelavathi of having an affair with Parasuraman. When Parasuraman arrives at Krishnamurthy's house while he is absent, Leelavathi warns him to leave. Parasuram leaves but forgets his umbrella. Krishnamurthy comes home drunk, sees the umbrella, assaults Leelavathi and goes out to shoot Parasuraman. Meanwhile, Ramanathan sends his servant disguised as Parasuraman to steal the treasuries of the [[Ekambareswarar Temple, Chennai|Ekambareswarar Temple]].\n\nKrishnamurthy chases Ramanathan's servant, whom he thinks is Parasuraman; a shot is heard, and the servant is killed. After coming to his senses, Krishnamurthy thinks he has murdered Parasuraman and decides to escape, leaving Leelavathi and Lakshmi in the custody of his servant Govindan. Krishnamurthy flees to [[Sri Lanka|Ceylon]], where he leads a wretched life as a labourer on a [[Tea processing|tea estate]]. Ramanathan makes advances to Leelavathi, who spurns him. Penniless, she goes with Govindan and Lakshmi, and works as a ''[[Spinning wheel#Charkha|charkha]]'' spinner. Krishnamurthy finds treasure and gives it to his master, who is pleased and adopts him as his son.\n\nKrishnamurthy returns to his family in Madras but is arrested for Parasuraman's murder. Detective Sreenivasan's investigation reveals the malicious intent of Ramanathan and Rangiah, and he produces the real Parasuraman in court. Parasuraman reveals himself, proving Krishnamurthy's innocence. Ramanathan had been secretly following the drunken Krishnamurthy, who passed out and dropped his gun. When the servant came out, Ramanathan picked up the gun, shot the servant and placed it in Krishnamurthy's hand. Krishnamurthy is acquitted, Ramanathan is sentenced to death, and Rangiah receives seven years' imprisonment. Lakshmi and Parasuraman's son Chandrakanthan marry.<ref name=\"pressbook\" />\n\n== Cast ==\n<!-- Credits adapted from the pressbook: http://tamildigitallibrary.in/admin/assets/book/TVA_BOK_0008620_%E0%AE%9A%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF-%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%80%E0%AE%B2%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF.pdf -->\n{{Col-begin|width=80%}}\n{{col-break|width=20%}}\n;Male cast<ref name=\"pressbook\" />\n* [[M. K. Radha]] as Krishnamurthy\n* [[T. S. Balaiah|T. S. Baliah]] as Ramanathan\n* [[M. G. Ramachandran]] as Inspector Rangiah\n* [[M. V. Mani]] as Sreenivasan\n* M. K. Mani as Lakshmi\n* P. Nammalvar as Parasuraman\n* T. N. Lakshmana Rao as Govindan\n* P. N. Ramakrishnan as Devotee\n{{col-break|width=20%}}\n;Female cast<ref name=\"pressbook\" />\n* M. R. Gnanambal as Leelavathi\n* Dhanalakshmi as Bama\n* Santhakumari as Mohanangi\n* M. Chandra Bai as Shanbagavalli<!--This name only follows the Tamil credits the spelling is wrong in the English credits.-->\n;Comedians<ref name=\"pressbook\" />\n* M. S. Murugesan as Marvadi\n* [[N. S. Krishnan]] as Balu\n* S. Sundaram as Sesha Iyengar\n{{Col-end}}\nAdditionally, J. Susheela Devi appears uncredited as a cabaret dancer,{{sfn|Guy|2016|p=72}} and [[K. A. Thangavelu]] plays a minor role, also uncredited.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Rajanayaham |first=R. P. |url=https://www.hindutamil.in/news/supplements/hindu-talkies/63625-.html |title=\u0ba8\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bc8\u0bb5\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b9a\u0bbf\u0bb1\u0b95\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd: \u0b95\u0bc7.\u0b8f. \u0ba4\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb5\u0bc7\u0bb2\u0bc1&nbsp;\u2013 \u0b85\u0ba3\u0bcd\u0ba3\u0bc7 \u0b8e\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0ba9\u0bc8\u0b9a\u0bcd \u0b9a\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bcb\u0bb1\u0bbe\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95! |date=13 November 2015 |work=[[The Hindu (Tamil)]] |access-date=12 November 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112040430/https://www.hindutamil.in/news/supplements/hindu-talkies/63625-.html |archive-date=12 November 2019 |trans-title=Wings of memories: K. A. Thangavelu&nbsp;\u2013 My big brother is going to shoot me!}}</ref> Parasuraman's son Chandrakanthan, Ramanathan's servant and Krishnamurthy's master in Ceylon were played by uncredited actors.<ref name=\"pressbook\" /><ref name=\"ohiocountylibrary\" />\n\n== Production ==\n=== Development ===\n''Pathi Bhakthi'', a [[Tamil language|Tamil]] play dealing with alcohol abuse and its effects on family life, was written by Te. Po. Krishnaswamy Pavalar during the early 1930s<ref name=\"started\" /> and was successful throughout the [[Madras Presidency]]. Pavalar's play was rewritten for the Madurai Original Boy's Company (MOBC) theatre troupe by playwright Madras Kandaswamy Mudaliar, and this production was also successful.{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=173}}<ref>{{Cite news |last=Raman |first=Mohan |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/100th-birthday-of-one-of-actor-t-s-balaiah/article6345220.ece |title=100 years of laughter |date=23 August 2014 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=14 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181014070941/https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/100th-birthday-of-one-of-actor-t-s-balaiah/article6345220.ece |archive-date=14 October 2018 |author-link=Mohan Raman}}</ref> A. N. Marudachalam Chettiar of Manorama Films wanted to produce ''Pathi Bhakthi'' as a film, but a [[Pathi Bhakthi|film version]] was already being made.{{efn|While historian [[Randor Guy]]'s 1997 book ''Starlight, Starbright'' says MOBC themselves decided to produce a film version of their play,{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=174}} his 2016 book ''Memories of Madras'' and historian [[Vamanan]] say that Chidambaram Chettiar of National Movietone had acquired the film rights for the play.{{sfn|Guy|2016|p=69}}<ref name=\"VamananDinamalarNellai\" />|name=|group=}}\n\nMudaliar, still keen on working with Chettiar, told him about [[S. S. Vasan]]'s 1934 novel ''Sathi Leelavathi''.{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=174}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tamilelibrary.org/biblio/list_novels.php |title=List of Novels in Tamil Books Bibliography |website=Tamil Electronic Library |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014042257/http://tamilelibrary.org/biblio/list_novels.php |archive-date=14 October 2018 |access-date=14 October 2018}}</ref> First [[Serial (literature)|serialised]] in the weekly magazine ''[[Ananda Vikatan]]'', the novel had the same storyline as ''Pathi Bhakthi''. Chettiar and Mudaliar approached Vasan, who sold the film rights for {{INR}}200 (about $75 in 1936).<ref name=\"SPAN\" />{{efn|name=exchange1936}} Mudaliar was then signed on as the screenwriter and soon began developing the screenplay.{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=174}} Vasan, who had never previously been involved with a film project, was credited in ''Sathi Leelavathi''{{'}}s opening titles for the original story.{{sfn|Pillai|2015|pp=151\u2013152}}{{sfn|Baskaran|1996|p=203}}\n\nChettiar wanted Manik Lal Tandon to direct the film but he declined;{{efn|Although Randor Guy has said that Tandon was reluctant to accept ''Sathi Leelavathi'' because he was directing ''[[Bhakta Nandanar]]'' (1935),{{sfn|Guy|1997|pp=174\u2013175}} [[Ellis R. Dungan]] said after ''Bhakta Nandanar''{{'s}} release, Tandon asked him if he would direct ''Sathi Leelavathi'' since he (Tandon) had an offer to direct the [[Hindi]] film ''Shame of the Nation''.<ref name=\"MGR Remembered Part 7\" />|name=|group=}} Tandon instead suggested his American friend [[Ellis R. Dungan]].{{sfn|Guy|1997|pp=174\u2013175}} Chettiar was hesitant because Dungan was new to India and did not know Tamil or much about Indian culture, but was persuaded to hire him because he had worked as a technician in Hollywood.<ref name=\"SPAN\" />{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=175}} The film was Dungan's directorial debut,{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=166}}{{efn|Dungan previously filmed scenes in ''Bhakta Nandanar'' in Tandon's absence.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Guy |first=Randor |url=https://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/fr/2002/02/01/stories/2002020100850300.htm |title=He transcended barriers with aplomb |date=1 February 2002 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=29 May 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529064253/https://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/fr/2002/02/01/stories/2002020100850300.htm |archive-date=29 May 2019 |author-link=Randor Guy}}</ref>}} and later listed in the [[Limca Book of Records]] as the first Indian film to be \"directed by a foreigner\".<ref name=\"Limca\" /> Because Dungan did not know Tamil, Chettiar hired C. K. Sathasivan as associate director.{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=176}}<ref>{{Cite news |last=Guy |first=Randor |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/Rajamrsquos-romance-with-cinema/article16812622.ece |title=Rajam's romance with cinema |date=5 February 2010 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=14 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181014071749/https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/Rajamrsquos-romance-with-cinema/article16812622.ece |archive-date=14 October 2018 |author-link=Randor Guy}}</ref> S. Panju, who would later go on to become a part of the [[Krishnan\u2013Panju]] directorial duo, was an assistant director.{{sfn|Rajadhyaksha|Willemen|1998|p=129}}\n\n''Sathi Leelavathi'' was one of the earliest Tamil films to be involved in a plagiarism controversy.<ref name=\"VamananDinamalarNellai\" /> When it was still in the pre-production stage, MOBC sued Chettiar and Mudaliar for plagiarising ''Pathi Bhakthi''.{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=175}} Many similarities between the two stories, including the female leads having the name Leelavathi, were noted.{{sfn|Guy|2016|p=82}} The case was resolved when Vasan testified both ''Pathi Bhakthi'' and the novel ''Sathi Leelavathi'' were in turn based on [[Ellen Wood (author)|Ellen Wood]]'s 1860 novel ''Danesbury House'',<ref name=\"started\" /><ref name=\"IE SathiLeelavathi\" /> therefore neither party could claim originality.{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=175}} The film explores themes of [[Temperance movement in India|temperance]],<ref name=\"MGR Remembered Part 8\" /> social reform, the [[Gandhism|Gandhian]] concept of selfless service,<ref>{{Cite book |title=Beyond Bollywood: The Cinemas of South India |publisher=[[HarperCollins]] |year=2017 |editor-last=Raghavendra |editor-first=M. K. |editor-link=M. K. Raghavendra |quote=Other films of the period that invoked nationalist symbols and the themes of temperance, social reform and the Gandhian concept of selfless service included ''Sathi Leelavathi'' (1936), ''Pathi Bhakti'' (1936) and ''Chandra Mohan Alladhu Samooga Thondu'' (1936).}}</ref> and labour\u2014in particular the plight of [[Tamil Nadu]] labourers in Ceylon's tea estates.{{sfnm |1a1=Baskaran |1y=1981 |1p=109 |2a1=Muthiah |2y=2004 |2p=404}}<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Laul |first=Brian |date=16 January 1983 |title=Where Cinema Is Politics and Politics Is Cinema |url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.101041/page/n287 |magazine=[[The Illustrated Weekly of India]] |pages=16\u201319}}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\nMudaliar had initially intented ''Pathi Bhakthi'' to be a [[star vehicle]] for his son [[M. K. Radha]], but thespian K. P. Kesavan was selected for the lead role instead.{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=174}}<ref name=\"VamananDinamalarNellai\" /> Radha, an MOBC actor, was eventually cast as the protagonist Krishnamurthy of ''Sathi Leelavathi''.<ref name=\"toast\" /> Other MOBC actors who made their screen debuts with the film were [[N. S. Krishnan]],{{efn|Although ''Sathi Leelavathi'' was Krishnan's first film project,<ref name=\"Americans\" /> because of production delays caused by the lawsuit, it became his second release.{{sfn|Kannan|2017|pp=30, 84}}<ref name=\"poppies\" />}} [[T. S. Balaiah]], and [[M. G. Ramachandran]], appearing as comedic character Balu, antagonist Ramanathan, and a police officer respectively.<ref name=\"pressbook\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/MGRs-first-film-steps/article14695764.ece |title=MGR's first film steps |date=25 April 2011 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=5 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005060725/https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/MGRs-first-film-steps/article14695764.ece |archive-date=5 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Guy |first=Randor |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/t-s-balaiah-endeared-himself-to-millions-of-fans-with-a-career-spanning-nearly-four-decades-says-randor-guy/article6324279.ece |title=Darling of the masses |date=16 August 2014 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=14 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181014064409/https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/t-s-balaiah-endeared-himself-to-millions-of-fans-with-a-career-spanning-nearly-four-decades-says-randor-guy/article6324279.ece |archive-date=14 October 2018 |author-link=Randor Guy}}</ref> Krishnan wrote the screenplay for his scenes and put on weight for the role.<ref>{{Cite news |last=\u0b9a\u0bb0\u0bb5\u0ba3\u0ba9\u0bcd |first=\u0baa\u0bc2.\u0b95\u0bca. |url=https://www.vikatan.com/news/coverstory/21760.html |title=\u0b95\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0bb5\u0bbe\u0ba3\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0b8e\u0ba9\u0bcd.\u0b8e\u0bb8\u0bcd.\u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0bb7\u0bcd\u0ba3\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b85\u0bb5\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bbf\u0bb1\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0ba8\u0bbe\u0bb3\u0bcd&nbsp;\u2013 \u0b9a\u0bbf\u0bb1\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1 \u0baa\u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc1 |date=29 November 2013 |work=[[Ananda Vikatan]] |access-date=9 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181009093037/https://www.vikatan.com/news/coverstory/21760.html |archive-date=9 October 2018 |language=ta |trans-title=The art lover N. S. Krishnan's birthday&nbsp;\u2013 Special Edition}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=\u0ba8\u0bbe\u0b95\u0bb0\u0bbe\u0b9c\u0ba9\u0bcd |first=\u0b9a\u0bcb\u0bb4 |url=https://www.hindutamil.in/news/supplements/hindu-talkies/63330-.html |title=\u0ba8\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bc8\u0bb5\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b9a\u0bbf\u0bb1\u0b95\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd: \u0b8e\u0ba9\u0bcd.\u0b8e\u0bb8\u0bcd.\u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0bb7\u0bcd\u0ba3\u0ba9\u0bcd \u2013 \u0b95\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0bb5\u0bbe\u0ba3\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0ba4\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0baf \u0b95\u0bca\u0bb2\u0bc8 \u0bb5\u0bb4\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1! |date=27 November 2015 |work=[[The Hindu (Tamil)]] |access-date=18 December 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828113000/https://www.hindutamil.in/news/supplements/hindu-talkies/63330-.html |archive-date=18 December 2019 |trans-title=Wings of Memories: N. S. Krishnan&nbsp;\u2013 A murder case against the lover of arts}}</ref>{{sfn|Kannan|2017|p=36}}\n\nRamachandran appeared in ''Pathi Bhakthi'' as the antagonist's henchman Veeramuthu,{{sfn|Kannan|2017|p=17}}{{sfn|Kannan|2017|p=28}} but MOBC owner Sachidanandam Pillai did not offer him a role in the film adaptation.{{sfn|Kannan|2010|p=85}} He later approached Mudaliar for a role in ''Sathi Leelavathi'' because he felt his role in ''Pathi Bhakthi'' offered him \"no room to shine\".{{sfn|Kannan|2017|pp=28\u201329}} According to Ramachandran, he was told he would play Detective Sreenivasan and later Krishnamurthy's friend Parasuraman,<ref>{{Cite book |last=Jayababu |first=S. V. |url=http://tamildigitallibrary.in/admin/assets/book/TVA_BOK_0010363_%E0%AE%AA%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A9%E0%AE%95%E0%AF%88_%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%B3%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%B3%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%8D_%E0%AE%8E%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%9C%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%86%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%8D_%E0%AE%A8%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%88%E0%AE%B5%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%95%E0%AE%B3%E0%AF%8D_2000.pdf |title=\u0baa\u0bc1\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0ba9\u0b95\u0bc8 \u0bb5\u0bb3\u0bcd\u0bb3\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b8e\u0bae\u0bcd.\u0b9c\u0bbf.\u0b86\u0bb0\u0bcd. \u0ba8\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bc8\u0bb5\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd 2000 |publisher=Jayababu |year=2000 |location=Chennai |pages=9 |language=ta |trans-title=Memories of the philanthropist of smiles MGR 2000 |access-date=17 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218021300/http://tamildigitallibrary.in/admin/assets/book/TVA_BOK_0010363_%E0%AE%AA%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A9%E0%AE%95%E0%AF%88_%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%B3%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%B3%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%8D_%E0%AE%8E%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%9C%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%86%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%8D_%E0%AE%A8%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%88%E0%AE%B5%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%95%E0%AE%B3%E0%AF%8D_2000.pdf |archive-date=18 February 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"MGR Filmfare\" /> but he was cast as Inspector Rangiah Naidu\u2014a role he disliked.{{sfn|Kannan|2017|pp=28\u201329}}<ref name=\"Tunes and trivia\" /> Ramachandran was paid an advance of {{INR}}100 (about $37.50 in 1936);{{sfn|Kannan|2017|p=29}}{{efn|name=exchange1936}} it was the first time he had seen a [[Indian 100-rupee note|100-rupee note]].<ref name=\"MGR Filmfare\" /> Chettiar gave the role of Sreenivasan to [[M. V. Mani]] without Mudaliar's knowledge,<ref name=\"pressbook\" />{{sfn|Kannan|2017|pp=29\u201330}} and P. Nammalvar was cast as Pasaruraman.<ref name=\"pressbook\" /> Despite Ramachandran's reluctance to play Rangiah, his mother was happy he got a \"respectable\" role and advised him to perform it responsibly.{{sfn|Kannan|2017|p=37}}\n\nThe casting of Krishnamurthy's wife Leelavathi was difficult; no actress was willing to play the character because the script required her to be physically abused and mistreated by her inebriated husband. In desperation, the producer asked Mudaliar and Radha to cast M. R. Gnanambal, Radha's wife, in the role.{{sfn|Guy|2016|p=83}} Gnanambal, who had retired from acting after her marriage, was initially reluctant to accept the role and came out of retirement to play it because no other actress would do so.<ref name=\"toast\" /><ref name=\"poppies\" /> Leelavathi's daughter Lakshmi was played by M. K. Mani, a boy. T. N. Lakshmana Rao, P. N. Ramakrishnan, Dhanalakshmi, Santhakumari, M. Chandra Bai, M. S. Murugesan and S. Sundaram were cast in supporting roles.<ref name=\"pressbook\" /> The film was also the feature debut of [[K. A. Thangavelu]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Raman |first=Mohan V. |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/King-of-comedy/article14995630.ece |title=King of comedy |date=24 September 2016 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=12 December 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181212085703/https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/King-of-comedy/article14995630.ece |archive-date=12 December 2018 |author-link=Mohan Raman}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Venkatraman |first=Karthikeyan |url=https://www.dinamani.com/specials/cinemaexpress/2017/mar/03/%E0%AE%8E%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%8E%E0%AE%99%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%95-%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%AA%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%95%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%95%E0%AF%81-%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%B1%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%88-2658937.html |title=\u0b8e\u0bb5\u0ba9\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd \u0b8e\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95 \u0bb5\u0bae\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1 \u0bb5\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb1\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bc8. |date=3 March 2017 |work=[[Dinamani]] |access-date=12 December 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181212073538/http://www.dinamani.com/specials/cinemaexpress/2017/mar/03/%E0%AE%8E%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%8E%E0%AE%99%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%95-%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%AA%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%95%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%95%E0%AF%81-%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%B1%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%88-2658937.html |archive-date=12 December 2018 |language=ta |trans-title=No-one dares to mess with us.}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\nPrincipal photography for ''Sathi Leelavathi'' began in 1935.<ref name=\"MGR Remembered Part 7\" />{{sfn|Rajadhyaksha|Willemen|1998|p=92}} Although Manorama Films was based in [[Coimbatore]],<ref name=\"Tunes and trivia\" /> the film was shot primarily at Vel Pictures Studio, Madras.{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=176}} Dungan wrote in his autobiography ''A Guide to Adventure'' (2001) that most of the cast were theatre actors and he was tasked with \"subduing [their] voices and facial expressions\".<ref name=\"MGR Remembered Part 8\" />{{sfn|Dungan|Smik|2001|pp=61\u201362}} According to him, when the actors faced the camera, they often froze and did not speak because it frightened them.<ref name=\"MGR Remembered Part 7\" /> In 1994, he recalled in an interview with ''Ananda Vikatan'', that Ramachandran initially did not understand the nuances of film acting and performed aggressively as though he was on stage. Dungan later advised and corrected Ramachandran to deliver his lines naturally.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vikatan.com/arts/nostalgia/40396--2 |title=\u0b8e\u0bae\u0bcd.\u0b9c\u0bbf.\u0b86\u0bb0\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b87\u0baf\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1\u0ba8\u0bb0\u0bcd! |date=30 January 1994 |website=[[Ananda Vikatan]] |language=ta |trans-title=MGR's first director! |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |archive-url=http://archive.today/FWJaN |archive-date=12 February 2020 |access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOne scene required Ramachandran to ride a bicycle but he did not know how to ride one. The sequence was thus filmed with him sitting on the bicycle with two people balancing it. They gave the bicycle a push as the camera rolled.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Vamanan |url=http://www.dinamalarnellai.com/web/news/24179 |title=\u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bc1\u0bb2\u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b90\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bae\u0bbe\u0ba9 \u0b85\u0bae\u0bc6\u0bb0\u0bbf\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0b9f\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b95\u0ba4\u0bc8! |date=13 March 2017 |work=[[Dinamalar]] |access-date=28 December 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228161112/http://www.dinamalarnellai.com/web/news/24179 |archive-date=28 December 2018 |location=Nellai |language=ta |trans-title=The story of the American Dungan who was totally involved in Tamil cinema |author-link=Vamanan}}</ref> According to film historian [[Film News Anandan]], filming was also done in Ceylon<ref name=\"anandan\" /> but [[Randor Guy]] wrote in the fortnightly ''[[Madras Musings]]'' that a large plot of land behind Vel Pictures Studio was used for the Ceylon tea plantation.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Guy |first=Randor |url=http://madrasmusings.com/older-archives/Vol%2018/Vol%20XVIII%20-%20No%2002.pdf |title=Vel's where MGR made his film debut |date=1-15 May 2008 |work=[[Madras Musings]] |access-date=8 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008060545/http://madrasmusings.com/older-archives/Vol%2018/Vol%20XVIII%20-%20No%2002.pdf |archive-date=8 October 2018 |author-link=Randor Guy}}</ref> With this film, Dungan introduced many features to Tamil cinema such as a lack of on-screen stage influences,<ref name=\"Americans\" />{{sfn|Guy|2016|p=79}} the \"cabaret dance\" or the \"club dance\",<ref name=\"IE SathiLeelavathi\" /> strict discipline, filming by schedule and camera mobility.<ref name=\"George\" />\n\nThere was no facility to pre-record songs in Madras at the time so performers had to sing on set. The accompanying musicians sat on a trolley and played the background musical score; this often restricted camera movement. In one scene, the orchestra sat under a nearby tree playing the [[harmonium]], [[tabla]] and other instruments while Radha's character sang at a tea plantation {{sfnm|1a1=Guy |1y=1997|1p=177 |2a1=Guy |2y=2016 |2pp=72\u201373}} The film's cinematographers were D. T. Telang and V. J. Shave,<ref name=\"ohiocountylibrary\" /> and Sircar and Dungan were the editors. Ramamurthi, the manager of Vel Pictures Studio, cleaned the exposed negatives by hand.<ref name=\"MGR Remembered Part 7\" /> The completed film was {{convert|18000|feet|metres|abbr=on}} in length and ran for 200 minutes.<ref name=\"MGR Remembered Part 8\" /><ref name=\"anandan\" />\n\n== Music ==\nThe music composer of ''Sathi Leelavathi'' is not credited in the film's [[song book]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Guy |first=Randor |url=http://mambalamtimes.in/admin/pdf/1397830127.MT%20Pages.pdf |title=Tamil Cinema 75&nbsp;\u2013 A Look Back {{!}} G. Ramanathan&nbsp;\u2013 3 |date=19\u201325 April 2014 |work=Mambalam Times |access-date=18 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181018113207/http://mambalamtimes.in/admin/pdf/1397830127.MT%20Pages.pdf |archive-date=18 October 2018 |page=4 |author-link=Randor Guy}}</ref> G. Sundhara Bhagavathar (also known as Sundhara Vadhiyar) was the lyricist in his cinematic debut.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cinemaexpress.com/cinemaexpress/story.aspx?Title=&artid=112692&SectionID=141&MainSectionID=141&SectionName=Interviews&SEO= |title=\u0b85\u0baa\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb5 \u0ba4\u0b95\u0bb5\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd-17: \u0b87\u0baf\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1\u0ba8\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0b8e\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bc0\u0bb8\u0bcd \u0b86\u0bb0\u0bcd. \u0b9f\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0ba9\u0bcd |work=[[Cinema Express]] |access-date=28 December 2018 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20161028053340/http://www.cinemaexpress.com/cinemaexpress/story.aspx?Title=&artid=112692&SectionID=141&MainSectionID=141&SectionName=Interviews&SEO= |archive-date=28 October 2016 |language=ta |trans-title=Rare information-17: Director Ellis R. Dungan}}</ref>\n\nThe melody of \"Theyila Thottathle\" (also spelt \"Theyilai Thottatile\") is based on [[Subramania Bharati]]'s poem \"Karumbu Thottathile\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Vamanan |url=http://www.dinamalarnellai.com/web/news/5426 |title=\u0ba4\u0b9f\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bc8\u0ba4\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bbe\u0ba3\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bbe\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bc7\u0bb0\u0bcb\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bae\u0bcd! |date=28 March 2016 |work=[[Dinamalar]] |access-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181006173908/http://www.dinamalarnellai.com/web/news/5426 |archive-date=6 October 2018 |location=Nellai |language=ta |trans-title=Bharati's gallop in his chariot crossing all barriers in film songs! |author-link=Vamanan}}</ref> The poem is about the plight of [[Debt bondage|bonded Indian labourers]] in [[Fiji]], while the song explores the problems of tea-plantation workers in Ceylon.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Venkatakrishnan |first=Sriram |url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/Memorial-to-Bharati/article15399096.ece |title=Memorial to Bharati |date=27 June 2008 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181006103021/https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/Memorial-to-Bharati/article15399096.ece |archive-date=6 October 2018 |author-link=V. Sriram}}</ref> The song, which is set in the [[Carnatic raga]] Chenchurutti, became popular and was frequently performed in concerts by [[Carnatic music]]ians. It was re-used in the [[Malayalam]] film ''[[Balan (film)|Balan]]'' (1938), as \"Jaathaka Doshathale\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Vijayakumar |first=B. |url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/Balan-1938/article15921329.ece |title=''Balan'' 1938 |date=7 September 2009 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181005190459/https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/Balan-1938/article15921329.ece |archive-date=5 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe other songs featured in the film were \"Thaayadhu Vayatrile Maayamai\", \"Thodudaiya Seviyan Vidai\", \"Hello Yennudaiya Dear\", \"Adhigha Sinamaen\", \"Paadhai Theriyamale\", \"Ini Yenna Seighuvaen Dhaeviyae\", \"Sadhikaaramaaranovubaanam\", \"Kaami Satthiyamaa Kannatthaik\", \"Pudhu Nilaa Mughap Poomaan Punniya\", \"Kallae Kadavuladaa Thambi\", \"Vaazhvinilae Maghaa Thaazvadaindhaenaiyo\", \"Undheepara Adhi Unnadha Thakkaliyae\" and \"Raattinamae Kadhar Poottinamae Kai\".<ref name=\"pressbook\" /><!--<ref>https://archive.today/20181014162827/http://songlyrics.lakshmansruthi.com/movie_song_list.php?id=Sathi%20Leelavathi</ref><ref>https://archive.today/20181014170731/http://www.mayyam.com/talk/showthread.php?10240-Ponmanachemmal-m-g-r-Filmography-news-amp-events/page3</ref> -->\n\n== Release and reception ==\n''Sathi Leelavathi'' had a \"[[Trade fair|trade show]]\" debut in Madras on 1 February 1936,<ref name=\"tradeshow\" /> and was theatrically released on 28 March that year. It was a major commercial success; according to film historian Aranthai Narayanan, this was due to Radha, Balaiah's and Krishnan's performances, Vasan's publicity, and support by [[British Raj|independence-era]] politicians of the anti-alcohol movement.<ref name=\"MGR Remembered Part 7\" /> The film ran for over 100 days in theatres.<ref>{{Cite book |url=http://tamildigitallibrary.in/book-detail.php?id=jZY9lup2kZl6TuXGlZQdjZt8l0U3&tag=%E0%AE%9A%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%88%20%E0%AE%A8%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%AF%E0%AE%95%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%8D%20%E0%AE%8E%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D.%E0%AE%9C%E0%AE%BF.%E0%AE%86%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%8D. |title=\u0b9a\u0bbe\u0ba4\u0ba9\u0bc8 \u0ba8\u0bbe\u0baf\u0b95\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b8e\u0bae\u0bcd.\u0b9c\u0bbf.\u0b86\u0bb0\u0bcd. |publisher=Arulmozhi Publications |year=1997 |page=28 |language=ta |trans-title=MGR, the man of achievements}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of its initial release, critics praised most aspects of the production, including the direction, photography, sound design, and writing.<ref name=\"pressbook\" /><ref name=\"tradeshow\" /> A few commentators including a reviewer for ''[[The Illustrated Weekly of India]]'' even saw the writing as an improvement on the novel. Praising the plot's continuity and climax, the reviewer called the film more \"interesting, natural and convincing\" than its source material.<ref name=\"pressbook\" /> The art magazine ''Aadal Paadal'' praised the social setting of ''Sathi Lellavathi'' in its January 1937 issue.{{sfn|Baskaran|2004|p=47}}. Politician [[C. Rajagopalachari]], a frequent critic of cinema, also appreciated the film's Gandhian ideals and pro-prohibition stance{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=177}} but said \"the main artiste in a [''charkha'']-spinning sequence did not know how to handle it\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Guy |first=Randor |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/chen-columns/sampoorna-ramayanam-1956/article3588925.ece |title=''Sampoorna Ramayanam'' 1956 |date=30 June 2012 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=4 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171123083806/http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/chen-columns/sampoorna-ramayanam-1956/article3588925.ece |archive-date=23 November 2017 |author-link=Randor Guy}}</ref> A writer for ''The Indian Review'' wrote that the film \"appeals to all classes and masses of the Tamil province\".<ref>{{Cite magazine |year=1936 |editor-last=Natesan |editor-first=G. A. |editor-link=G. A. Natesan |title=Sati Leelavati |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b_JVhvcfSkcC&dq=The+Indian+Review+%22Sati+Leelavati%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=LEELAVATI |magazine=The Indian Review |publisher=G. A. Natesan & Company |volume=37 |page=205}}</ref>\n\nThe acting performances also received generally positive response from critics.<ref name=\"tradeshow\" /> In a 14 February 1936 review, ''[[The Hindu]]'' praised Radha's performance for its \"naturalness and ease\", Balaiah's villainy and Gnanambal's performance in the \"difficult role\" of Leelavathi.<ref name=\"pressbook\" /> Playwright and retired [[Subordinate judge|sub-judge]] [[Pammal Sambandha Mudaliar]] echoed the sentiment, praising Radha for performing a \"difficult part very creditably\".<ref name=\"pressbook\" /> A ''Cine Art Review'' writer was also appreciative of the [[cross-gender acting]] of M. K. Mani, who played Lakshmi in the film. The writer was particularly impressed by the opening scene in which Lakshmi hums a tune while going downstairs.<ref name=\"pressbook\" />\n\nSeveral new filmmaking techniques introduced by Dungan were unappreciated at the time. In ''Silver Screen'' magazine on 1 August 1936, Pe. Ko. Sundararajan (journalist and writer for ''[[Manikkodi|Manikodi]]'') said the new methods of depicting emotions were not understood by the audience; in one scene, Dungan showed the dancing girl as seen by the inebriated protagonist, and in another he indicated his fear by depicting his twitching fingers and feet. According to Sundararajan, the techniques helped the actors to emote and showcased Dungan's talent; however, the audience thought the lighting in the first scene was poor and that the film was stuck in the second. He opined that this reflected their ignorance.{{sfn|Baskaran|2004|p=39}}\n\n== Legacy ==\n''Sathi Leelavathi'' attained cult status in Tamil cinema<ref>{{Cite news |last=Guy |first=Randor |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-columns/punjab-kesari-1938/article5973131.ece |title=''Punjab Kesari'' 1938 |date=3 May 2014 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=16 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016102149/https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-columns/punjab-kesari-1938/article5973131.ece |archive-date=16 October 2018 |author-link=Randor Guy}}</ref> and made Dungan an in-demand director.<ref name=\"IE SathiLeelavathi\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.frontline.in/arts-and-culture/dungan-the-director/article5492566.ece |title=Dungan the director |date=10 January 2014 |work=[[Frontline (magazine)|Frontline]] |access-date=8 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20141126025215/http://www.frontline.in/arts-and-culture/dungan-the-director/article5492566.ece |archive-date=26 November 2014}}</ref> The techniques introduced by Dungan in the film became staples of Tamil cinema.<ref name=\"George\" />{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=177}} Footage about the making of ''Sathi Leelavathi'' was later included in ''[[An American in Madras]]'', a documentary about Dungan's career in India.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Chatterji |first=Shoma A. |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2014/20140126/spectrum/entertainment1.htm |title=A fascinating documentary |date=26 January 2014 |work=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)]] |access-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181024114955/https://www.tribuneindia.com/2014/20140126/spectrum/entertainment1.htm |archive-date=24 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Vijayan |first=Naveena |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2014/aug/16/American-Touch-to-Tamil-Cinema-648420.html |title=American Touch to Tamil Cinema |date=16 August 2014 |work=[[The New Indian Express]] |access-date=17 November 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117132408/https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2014/aug/16/American-Touch-to-Tamil-Cinema-648420.html |archive-date=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Sathi Leelavathi'' was the first Tamil film to be successful in overseas markets.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Venkateswaran |first=N. |url=http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Repository/getFiles.asp?Style=OliveXLib:LowLevelEntityToPrintGifMSIE_PASTISSUES2&Type=text/html&Locale=english-skin-custom&Path=TOICH/2011/03/20&ChunkNum=0&ID=Ar00200 |title=The chronicler of Kollywood |date=20 March 2011 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=14 October 2018 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181014031543/http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Repository/getFiles.asp?Style=OliveXLib:LowLevelEntityToPrintGifMSIE_PASTISSUES2&Type=text/html&Locale=english-skin-custom&Path=TOICH/2011/03/20&ChunkNum=0&ID=Ar00200 |archive-date=14 October 2018}}</ref> According to film historian Swarnavel Eswaran Pillai, despite Vasan's initial aversion to films,{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=241}} ''Sathi Leelavathi''{{'}}s success encouraged him to enter the industry as a distributor.{{sfn|Pillai|2015|p=152}} Ramachandran avoided playing roles similar to Rangiah Naidu in his later films, preferring to play a \"good Samaritan\" in ''[[Marmayogi]]'' (1951), ''[[Malaikkallan]]'' (1954), ''[[Nadodi Mannan]]'' (1958) and ''[[Enga Veettu Pillai]]'' (1965).<ref>{{Cite news |last=Venkatramani |first=S. H. |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/cover-story/story/19880115-mgr-a-genius-with-an-uncanny-ability-to-think-up-populist-schemes-796840-1988-01-15 |title=MGR: A genius with an uncanny ability to think up populist schemes |date=15 January 1988 |work=[[India Today]] |access-date=15 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181015112743/https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/cover-story/story/19880115-mgr-a-genius-with-an-uncanny-ability-to-think-up-populist-schemes-796840-1988-01-15 |archive-date=15 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nNo complete print of ''Sathi Leelavathi'' is known to survive, making it a [[List of incomplete or partially lost films|partially lost film]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |url=https://www.thehindu.com/books/books-authors/another-anandan-in-the-making/article19593507.ece |title=Another Anandan in the making |date=31 August 2017 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=8 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20170918071320/http://www.thehindu.com/books/books-authors/another-anandan-in-the-making/article19593507.ece |archive-date=18 September 2017}}</ref> What remains of the film is preserved in the West Virginia State Archives.<ref name=\"ohiocountylibrary\" />\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notes\n| colwidth =\n| notes =\n{{efn\n| name = exchange1936\n| The exchange rate in 1936 was 2.67 Indian rupees ({{INR}}) per 1 US dollar (US$).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.measuringworth.com/datasets/exchangeglobal/result.php?year_source=1920&year_result=1945&countryE%5B%5D=India |title=Exchange Rates Between the United States Dollar and Forty-one Currencies |last=Officer |first=Lawrence H. |date=2015 |website=MeasuringWorth |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181014130029/https://www.measuringworth.com/datasets/exchangeglobal/result.php?year_source=1920&year_result=1945&countryE%5B%5D=India |archive-date=14 October 2018 |access-date=14 October 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"George\">{{Cite book |last=George |first=T. J. S. |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=eWO2AQAACAAJ |title=M.S. Subbulakshmi: The Definitive Biography |publisher=[[Aleph Book Company]] |year=2016 |isbn=9789384067601 |pages=101 |author-link=T. J. S. George}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MGR Remembered Part 7\">{{Cite web |url=http://sangam.org/mgr-remembered-part-7/ |title=MGR Remembered&nbsp;\u2013 Part 7 |last=Kantha |first=Sachi Sri |authorlink=Sachi Sri Kantha |date=2 April 2013 |website=[[Ilankai Tamil Sangam]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426063242/http://sangam.org/mgr-remembered-part-7/ |archive-date=26 April 2017 |access-date=25 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"pressbook\">{{Cite book |url=http://tamildigitallibrary.in/admin/assets/book/TVA_BOK_0008620_%E0%AE%9A%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF-%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%80%E0%AE%B2%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF.pdf |title=Sathi Leelavathi |publisher=Manorama Films |year=1936 |location=[[Coimbatore]] |type=[[pressbook]] |access-date=5 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005194851/http://tamildigitallibrary.in/admin/assets/book/TVA_BOK_0008620_%E0%AE%9A%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF-%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%80%E0%AE%B2%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF.pdf |archive-date=5 October 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"anandan\">{{Cite book |last=Film News Anandan |url=http://www.lakshmansruthi.com/cineprofiles/1936-cinedetails10.asp |title=Sadhanaigal padaitha Tamil Thiraipada Varalaaru |publisher=Sivagami Publications |year=2004 |location=Chennai |language=Tamil |trans-title=History of Landmark Tamil films |author-link=Film News Anandan |access-date=5 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005051333/http://www.lakshmansruthi.com/cineprofiles/1936-cinedetails10.asp |archive-date=5 October 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Americans\">{{Cite news |last=Muthiah |first=S. |url=https://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/mp/2004/09/06/stories/2004090600190300.htm |title=Americans in Tamil cinema |date=6 September 2004 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=5 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005044125/https://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/mp/2004/09/06/stories/2004090600190300.htm |archive-date=5 October 2018 |author-link=S. Muthiah}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"IE SathiLeelavathi\">{{Cite news |last=Guy |first=Randor |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=s4ZlAAAAIBAJ&sjid=sJ4NAAAAIBAJ&pg=1511%2C1703991 |title=''Sathi Leelavathi'', made after a legal battle |date=2 February 1991 |work=[[The Indian Express]] |page=19 |author-link=Randor Guy}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"SPAN\">{{Cite magazine |last=Guy |first=Randor |author-link=Randor Guy |date=August 1994 |title=Ellis R. Dungan&nbsp;\u2013 A Legend of Tamil Cinema |url=https://issuu.com/spanmagazine/docs/1994-08-cr |magazine=[[SPAN (magazine)|SPAN]] |volume=XXXV |issue=8 |page=35}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"started\">{{Cite news |last=Muthiah |first=S. |url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/The-film-that-got-MGR-started/article17199879.ece |title=The film that got MGR started |date=6 February 2017 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=4 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005045137/https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/The-film-that-got-MGR-started/article17199879.ece |archive-date=5 October 2018 |author-link=S. Muthiah}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Limca\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IP1tAAAAMAAJ |title=Limca Book of Records |publisher=Bisleri Beverages Limited |year=1999 |quote=First directed by a foreigner ''Sathi Leelavathi'' (1936) highlighting the evils of alcoholism was directed by Ellis R. {{sic|Duncan}}}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"toast\">{{Cite news |last=Guy |first=Randor |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/mk-radha-the-toast-of-theatre-and-cinema/article8446757.ece |title=M. K. Radha, the toast of theatre and cinema |date=7 April 2016 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181005190714/https://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/mk-radha-the-toast-of-theatre-and-cinema/article8446757.ece |archive-date=5 October 2018 |author-link=Randor Guy}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Tunes and trivia\">{{Cite news |last=Jeshi |first=K. |url=https://www.thehindu.com/books/tunes-and-trivia/article3931963.ece |title=Tunes and trivia |date=7 December 2004 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=5 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005060914/https://www.thehindu.com/books/tunes-and-trivia/article3931963.ece |archive-date=5 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MGR Remembered Part 8\">{{Cite web |url=https://sangam.org/mgr-remembered-part-8/ |title=MGR Remembered&nbsp;\u2013 Part 8 |last=Kantha |first=Sachi Sri |authorlink=Sachi Sri Kantha |date=7 May 2013 |website=[[Ilankai Tamil Sangam]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181017184304/http://sangam.org/mgr-remembered-part-8/ |archive-date=17 October 2018 |access-date=17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MGR Filmfare\">{{Cite magazine |last=Ramachandran |first=M. G. |author-link=M. G. Ramachandran |date=1-15 February 1988 |orig-year=1964 |title=My Memorable Roles |url=https://mgrroop.blogspot.com/2013/01/memorable-roles.html |magazine=[[Filmfare]] |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181018075244/https://mgrroop.blogspot.com/2013/01/memorable-roles.html |archive-date=18 October 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"VamananDinamalarNellai\">{{Cite news |last=Vamanan |url=http://www.dinamalarnellai.com/web/news/1896 |title=''\u0baa\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0baa\u0b95\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf''\u0baf\u0bc8\u0ba4\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bb4\u0bc1\u0bb5\u0bbf \u0b85\u0ba4\u0bc8 \u0bae\u0bc1\u0bb1\u0bbf\u0baf\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4 ''\u0b9a\u0ba4\u0bbf \u0bb2\u0bc0\u0bb2\u0bbe\u0bb5\u0ba4\u0bbf''!&nbsp;\u2013 \u0bb5\u0bbe\u0bae\u0ba9\u0ba9\u0bcd&nbsp;\u2013 \u0ba4\u0bca\u0b9f\u0bb0\u0bcd&nbsp;\u20135 |date=4 January 2016 |work=[[Dinamalar]] |access-date=4 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181004101727/http://www.dinamalarnellai.com/web/news/1896 |archive-date=4 October 2018 |location=Nellai |language=ta |trans-title=''Sathi Leelavathi'', the film that embraced ''Pathi Bhakthi'' and won over it |author-link=Vamanan}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ohiocountylibrary\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ohiocountylibrary.org/wheeling-history/5111 |title=Biography: Ellis Dungan |website=Ohio County Public Library |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181018180733/http://www.ohiocountylibrary.org/wheeling-history/5111 |archive-date=18 October 2018 |access-date=18 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"poppies\">{{Cite news |last=Muthiah |first=S. |url=https://www.thehindu.com/society/Indian-contribution-in-the-Great-War/article17334284.ece |title=Where poppies blow |date=20 February 2017 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=24 December 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181224060541/https://www.thehindu.com/society/Indian-contribution-in-the-Great-War/article17334284.ece |archive-date=24 December 2018 |author-link=S. Muthiah}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"tradeshow\">{{Cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zb8-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=XkwMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1930%2C1508286 |title=Sati Leelavathi |date=1 February 1936 |work=[[The Indian Express]] |url-status=live |page=2}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Baskaran |first=S. Theodore |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tOEDAAAAMAAJ |title=The Message Bearers: The Nationalist Politics and the Entertainment Media in South India, 1880\u20131945 |publisher=Cre-A |year=1981 |location=Chennai |oclc=9441794 |ref=harv |author-link=S. Theodore Baskaran}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Baskaran |first=S. Theodore |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PhFlAAAAMAAJ |title=The Eye of the Serpent: An introduction to Tamil cinema |publisher=East West Books |year=1996 |oclc=243920437 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Baskaran |first=S. Theodore |title=Chithiram Pesuthadi |publisher=Kalachuvadu |year=2004 |isbn=81-87477-75-X |location=Chennai |language=Tamil |trans-title=The Picture Speaks, Dear |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Dungan |first=Ellis R. |title=A Guide to Adventure: An Autobiography |last2=Smik |first2=Barbara |publisher=[[Dorrance Publishing Company]] |year=2001 |location=Pittsburgh |oclc=50318101 |ref=harv |author-link=Ellis R. Dungan}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Guy |first=Randor |title=Starlight, Starbright: The Early Tamil Cinema |publisher=Amra Publishers |year=1997 |location=Chennai |oclc=52794531 |ref=harv |author-link=Randor Guy}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Guy |first=Randor |title=Memories of Madras: Its Movies, Musicians & Men of Letters |publisher=Creative Workshop |year=2016 |isbn=978-81-928961-7-5 |editor-last=Gopal |editor-first=T. S. |location=Chennai |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Kannan |first=R. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aQc_Xi0J8M0C |title=Anna: The Life and Times of C. N. Annadurai |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-670-08328-2 |location=New Delhi |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Kannan |first=R. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2mclDwAAQBAJ |title=MGR: A Life |date=28 June 2017 |publisher=[[Penguin Random House]] |isbn=978-93-86495-88-4 |location=India |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Muthiah |first=S. |title=Madras Rediscovered: A Historical Guide to Looking Around |title-link=Madras Rediscovered |publisher=East West Books |year=2004 |isbn=81-88661-24-4 |edition=5th |location=Chennai |ref=harv |author-link=S. Muthiah |orig-year=1981}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Pillai |first=Swarnavel Eswaran |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HreICwAAQBAJ |title=Madras Studios: Narrative, Genre, and Ideology in Tamil Cinema |publisher=[[SAGE Publishing|SAGE Publications]] |year=2015 |isbn=978-93-5150-212-8 |location=New Delhi |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://indiancine.ma/texts/indiancine.ma%3AEncyclopedia_of_Indian_Cinema/text.pdf |title=Encyclopaedia of Indian Cinema |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |year=1998 |isbn=0-19-563579-5 |editor-last=Rajadhyaksha |editor-first=Ashish |ref=harv |orig-year=1994 |editor-last2=Willemen |editor-first2=Paul}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0215150}}\n* {{CITWF title|306281}}\n{{Ellis R. Dungan}}\n\n[[Category:1930s lost films]]\n[[Category:1930s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:1936 films]]\n[[Category:Directorial debut films]]\n[[Category:Films about alcoholism]]\n[[Category:Films based on adaptations]]\n[[Category:Films based on British novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on Indian novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ellis R. Dungan]]\n[[Category:Films involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:Indian black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Indian drama films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Lost drama films]]\n[[Category:Lost Indian films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 1936 film|the 1995 film|Sathi Leelavathi (1995 film)}}\n{{short description|1936 film by Ellis R. Dungan}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Sathi Leelavathi\n| image          = Sathi Leelavathi (1936 film).jpg\n| alt            = Landscape black-and-white poster with the film's title in English\n| caption        = Theatrical poster\n| director       = [[Ellis R. Dungan]]\n| producer       = A. N. Marudachalam Chettiar\n| screenplay     = Madras Kandaswamy Mudaliar\n| based_on       = {{based on|''Sathi Leelavathi''|[[S. S. Vasan]]}}\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[M. K. Radha]]|M. R. Gnanambal}}\n| cinematography = {{ubl|D. T. Telang|V. J. Shave}}\n| editing        = {{ubl|Sircar|Ellis R. Dungan}}\n| studio         = Manorama Films\n| released       = {{film date|1936|3|28|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 200 minutes<!-- 18,000 feet -->\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n}}\n\n'''''Sathi Leelavathi''''' ({{IPA-ta|sat\u032ai l\u032ai\u02d0l\u032aa\u02d0\u028bat\u032ai|pron}}, {{trans|''Leelavathi, the Chaste Wife''}}) is a 1936 [[Tamil language|Tamil-language]] Indian [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[Ellis R. Dungan]] and written by Madras Kandaswamy Mudaliar. It is based on [[S. S. Vasan]]'s novel of the same name, which had been [[Serial (literature)|serialised]] in 1934. [[M. K. Radha]] stars as Krishnamurthy, a man from [[Chennai|Madras]], who is lured into drinking alcohol by an acquaintance. Believing he murdered his friend in a drunken stupor, Krishnamurthy flees to [[Sri Lanka|Ceylon]] while his wife and daughter, played by M. R. Gnanambal and M. K. Mani respectively, are reduced to poverty. [[T. S. Balaiah]], [[M. G. Ramachandran]], [[M. V. Mani]] and P. Nammalvar appear in supporting roles.\n\nA. N. Marudachalam Chettiar initially wanted to produce a film version of the Madurai Original Boys Company (MOBC) play ''Pathi Bhakthi'', but realised [[Pathi Bhakthi|an adaptation]] was already being made. Chettiar then learnt about Vasan's novel, which had a similar plot and obtained the rights to make a film version. ''Sathi Leelavathi'' was Dungan's directorial debut and the film-acting debuts of Radha, Balaiah, Ramachandran and [[K. A. Thangavelu]]. It was [[N. S. Krishnan]]'s first film appearance, but his second release. The film was mostly shot at Vel Pictures Studio in Madras. D. T. Telang and V. J. Shave were the cinematographers, and the film was co-edited by Dungan and Sircar.\n\n''Sathi Leelavathi'' explores themes of [[Temperance movement in India|temperance]], social reform, the [[Gandhism|Gandhian]] concept of selfless service and the plight of labourers. It was one of the earliest Tamil films to be involved in a plagiarism controversy; the MOBC accused Chettiar and Mudaliar of plagiarising their play. The case was resolved after Vasan testified that both the play and the novel were based on ''Danesbury House'', an 1860 novel written by [[Ellen Wood (author)|Ellen Wood]], so neither party could claim originality. The film premiered on 1 February 1936 in Madras and was released theatrically on 28 March. It was a commercial success and made Dungan a sought-after director. Several features of his direction, including shooting by schedule, camera mobility, cabaret dances and less-theatrical acting, became staples of [[Tamil cinema]]. No complete print of the film is known to survive, making it a [[List of incomplete or partially lost films|partially lost film]].\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Plot ==\nKrishnamurthy is a wealthy man who lives in [[Chennai|Madras]] with his wife Leelavathi and their daughter Lakshmi. At a mock tea party, Krishnamurthy's acquaintance Ramanathan persuades him to drink alcohol. Ramanathan's collaborator is Rangiah Naidu, a corrupt police inspector. Krishnamurthy becomes infatuated by Mohanangi, a promiscuous woman, and promises to pay her {{INR}}50,000 (about US$18,700 in 1936).{{efn|name=exchange1936}}\n\nParasuraman, Krishnamurthy's friend, tries but fails to reform him. A [[Marwari people|Marvadi]] man who lent money to Krishnamurthy obtains a [[Warrant of payment|repayment warrant]], sinking Krishnamurthy deeper in debt. Krishnamurthy drunkenly accuses Leelavathi of having an affair with Parasuraman. When Parasuraman arrives at Krishnamurthy's house while he is absent, Leelavathi warns him to leave. Parasuram leaves but forgets his umbrella. Krishnamurthy comes home drunk, sees the umbrella, assaults Leelavathi and goes out to shoot Parasuraman. Meanwhile, Ramanathan sends his servant disguised as Parasuraman to steal the treasuries of the [[Ekambareswarar Temple, Chennai|Ekambareswarar Temple]].\n\nKrishnamurthy chases Ramanathan's servant, whom he thinks is Parasuraman; a shot is heard, and the servant is killed. After coming to his senses, Krishnamurthy thinks he has murdered Parasuraman and decides to escape, leaving Leelavathi and Lakshmi in the custody of his servant Govindan. Krishnamurthy flees to [[Sri Lanka|Ceylon]], where he leads a wretched life as a labourer on a [[Tea processing|tea estate]]. Ramanathan makes advances to Leelavathi, who spurns him. Penniless, she goes with Govindan and Lakshmi, and works as a ''[[Spinning wheel#Charkha|charkha]]'' spinner. Krishnamurthy finds treasure and gives it to his master, who is pleased and adopts him as his son.\n\nKrishnamurthy returns to his family in Madras but is arrested for Parasuraman's murder. Detective Sreenivasan's investigation reveals the malicious intent of Ramanathan and Rangiah, and he produces the real Parasuraman in court. Parasuraman reveals himself, proving Krishnamurthy's innocence. Ramanathan had been secretly following the drunken Krishnamurthy, who passed out and dropped his gun. When the servant came out, Ramanathan picked up the gun, shot the servant and placed it in Krishnamurthy's hand. Krishnamurthy is acquitted, Ramanathan is sentenced to death, and Rangiah receives seven years' imprisonment. Lakshmi and Parasuraman's son Chandrakanthan marry.<ref name=\"pressbook\" />\n\n== Cast ==\n<!-- Credits adapted from the pressbook: http://tamildigitallibrary.in/admin/assets/book/TVA_BOK_0008620_%E0%AE%9A%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF-%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%80%E0%AE%B2%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF.pdf -->\n{{Col-begin|width=80%}}\n{{col-break|width=20%}}\n;Male cast<ref name=\"pressbook\" />\n* [[M. K. Radha]] as Krishnamurthy\n* [[T. S. Balaiah|T. S. Baliah]] as Ramanathan\n* [[M. G. Ramachandran]] as Inspector Rangiah\n* [[M. V. Mani]] as Sreenivasan\n* M. K. Mani as Lakshmi\n* P. Nammalvar as Parasuraman\n* T. N. Lakshmana Rao as Govindan\n* P. N. Ramakrishnan as Devotee\n{{col-break|width=20%}}\n;Female cast<ref name=\"pressbook\" />\n* M. R. Gnanambal as Leelavathi\n* Dhanalakshmi as Bama\n* Santhakumari as Mohanangi\n* M. Chandra Bai as Shanbagavalli<!--This name only follows the Tamil credits the spelling is wrong in the English credits.-->\n;Comedians<ref name=\"pressbook\" />\n* M. S. Murugesan as Marvadi\n* [[N. S. Krishnan]] as Balu\n* S. Sundaram as Sesha Iyengar\n{{Col-end}}\nAdditionally, J. Susheela Devi appears uncredited as a cabaret dancer,{{sfn|Guy|2016|p=72}} and [[K. A. Thangavelu]] plays a minor role, also uncredited.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Rajanayaham |first=R. P. |url=https://www.hindutamil.in/news/supplements/hindu-talkies/63625-.html |title=\u0ba8\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bc8\u0bb5\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b9a\u0bbf\u0bb1\u0b95\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd: \u0b95\u0bc7.\u0b8f. \u0ba4\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb5\u0bc7\u0bb2\u0bc1&nbsp;\u2013 \u0b85\u0ba3\u0bcd\u0ba3\u0bc7 \u0b8e\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0ba9\u0bc8\u0b9a\u0bcd \u0b9a\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bcb\u0bb1\u0bbe\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95! |date=13 November 2015 |work=[[The Hindu (Tamil)]] |access-date=12 November 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112040430/https://www.hindutamil.in/news/supplements/hindu-talkies/63625-.html |archive-date=12 November 2019 |trans-title=Wings of memories: K. A. Thangavelu&nbsp;\u2013 My big brother is going to shoot me!}}</ref> Parasuraman's son Chandrakanthan, Ramanathan's servant and Krishnamurthy's master in Ceylon were played by uncredited actors.<ref name=\"pressbook\" /><ref name=\"ohiocountylibrary\" />\n\n== Production ==\n=== Development ===\n''Pathi Bhakthi'', a [[Tamil language|Tamil]] play dealing with alcohol abuse and its effects on family life, was written by Te. Po. Krishnaswamy Pavalar during the early 1930s<ref name=\"started\" /> and was successful throughout the [[Madras Presidency]]. Pavalar's play was rewritten for the Madurai Original Boy's Company (MOBC) theatre troupe by playwright Madras Kandaswamy Mudaliar, and this production was also successful.{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=173}}<ref>{{Cite news |last=Raman |first=Mohan |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/100th-birthday-of-one-of-actor-t-s-balaiah/article6345220.ece |title=100 years of laughter |date=23 August 2014 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=14 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181014070941/https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/100th-birthday-of-one-of-actor-t-s-balaiah/article6345220.ece |archive-date=14 October 2018 |author-link=Mohan Raman}}</ref> A. N. Marudachalam Chettiar of Manorama Films wanted to produce ''Pathi Bhakthi'' as a film, but a [[Pathi Bhakthi|film version]] was already being made.{{efn|While historian [[Randor Guy]]'s 1997 book ''Starlight, Starbright'' says MOBC themselves decided to produce a film version of their play,{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=174}} his 2016 book ''Memories of Madras'' and historian [[Vamanan]] say that Chidambaram Chettiar of National Movietone had acquired the film rights for the play.{{sfn|Guy|2016|p=69}}<ref name=\"VamananDinamalarNellai\" />|name=|group=}}\n\nMudaliar, still keen on working with Chettiar, told him about [[S. S. Vasan]]'s 1934 novel ''Sathi Leelavathi''.{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=174}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tamilelibrary.org/biblio/list_novels.php |title=List of Novels in Tamil Books Bibliography |website=Tamil Electronic Library |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014042257/http://tamilelibrary.org/biblio/list_novels.php |archive-date=14 October 2018 |access-date=14 October 2018}}</ref> First [[Serial (literature)|serialised]] in the weekly magazine ''[[Ananda Vikatan]]'', the novel had the same storyline as ''Pathi Bhakthi''. Chettiar and Mudaliar approached Vasan, who sold the film rights for {{INR}}200 (about $75 in 1936).<ref name=\"SPAN\">{{Cite magazine |last=Guy |first=Randor |author-link=Randor Guy |date=August 1994 |title=Ellis R. Dungan&nbsp;\u2013 A Legend of Tamil Cinema |url=https://issuu.com/spanmagazine/docs/1994-08-cr |magazine=[[SPAN (magazine)|SPAN]] |volume=XXXV |issue=8 |page=35}}</ref>{{efn|name=exchange1936}} Mudaliar was then signed on as the screenwriter and soon began developing the screenplay.{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=174}} Vasan, who had never previously been involved with a film project, was credited in ''Sathi Leelavathi''{{'}}s opening titles for the original story.{{sfn|Pillai|2015|pp=151\u2013152}}{{sfn|Baskaran|1996|p=203}}\n\nChettiar wanted Manik Lal Tandon to direct the film but he declined;{{efn|Although Randor Guy has said that Tandon was reluctant to accept ''Sathi Leelavathi'' because he was directing ''[[Bhakta Nandanar]]'' (1935),{{sfn|Guy|1997|pp=174\u2013175}} [[Ellis R. Dungan]] said after ''Bhakta Nandanar''{{'s}} release, Tandon asked him if he would direct ''Sathi Leelavathi'' since he (Tandon) had an offer to direct the [[Hindi]] film ''Shame of the Nation''.<ref name=\"MGR Remembered Part 7\" />|name=|group=}} Tandon instead suggested his American friend [[Ellis R. Dungan]].{{sfn|Guy|1997|pp=174\u2013175}} Chettiar was hesitant because Dungan was new to India and did not know Tamil or much about Indian culture, but was persuaded to hire him because he had worked as a technician in Hollywood.<ref name=\"SPAN\" />{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=175}} The film was Dungan's directorial debut,{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=166}}{{efn|Dungan previously filmed scenes in ''Bhakta Nandanar'' in Tandon's absence.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Guy |first=Randor |url=https://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/fr/2002/02/01/stories/2002020100850300.htm |title=He transcended barriers with aplomb |date=1 February 2002 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=29 May 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529064253/https://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/fr/2002/02/01/stories/2002020100850300.htm |archive-date=29 May 2019 |author-link=Randor Guy}}</ref>}} and later listed in the [[Limca Book of Records]] as the first Indian film to be \"directed by a foreigner\".<ref name=\"Limca\" /> Because Dungan did not know Tamil, Chettiar hired C. K. Sathasivan as associate director.{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=176}}<ref>{{Cite news |last=Guy |first=Randor |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/Rajamrsquos-romance-with-cinema/article16812622.ece |title=Rajam's romance with cinema |date=5 February 2010 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=14 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181014071749/https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/Rajamrsquos-romance-with-cinema/article16812622.ece |archive-date=14 October 2018 |author-link=Randor Guy}}</ref> S. Panju, who would later go on to become a part of the [[Krishnan\u2013Panju]] directorial duo, was an assistant director.{{sfn|Rajadhyaksha|Willemen|1998|p=129}}\n\n''Sathi Leelavathi'' was one of the earliest Tamil films to be involved in a plagiarism controversy.<ref name=\"VamananDinamalarNellai\" /> When it was still in the pre-production stage, MOBC sued Chettiar and Mudaliar for plagiarising ''Pathi Bhakthi''.{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=175}} Many similarities between the two stories, including the female leads having the name Leelavathi, were noted.{{sfn|Guy|2016|p=82}} The case was resolved when Vasan testified both ''Pathi Bhakthi'' and the novel ''Sathi Leelavathi'' were in turn based on [[Ellen Wood (author)|Ellen Wood]]'s 1860 novel ''Danesbury House'',<ref name=\"started\" /><ref name=\"IE SathiLeelavathi\" /> therefore neither party could claim originality.{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=175}} The film explores themes of [[Temperance movement in India|temperance]],<ref name=\"MGR Remembered Part 8\" /> social reform, the [[Gandhism|Gandhian]] concept of selfless service,<ref>{{Cite book |title=Beyond Bollywood: The Cinemas of South India |publisher=[[HarperCollins]] |year=2017 |editor-last=Raghavendra |editor-first=M. K. |editor-link=M. K. Raghavendra |quote=Other films of the period that invoked nationalist symbols and the themes of temperance, social reform and the Gandhian concept of selfless service included ''Sathi Leelavathi'' (1936), ''Pathi Bhakti'' (1936) and ''Chandra Mohan Alladhu Samooga Thondu'' (1936).}}</ref> and labour\u2014in particular the plight of [[Tamil Nadu]] labourers in Ceylon's tea estates.{{sfnm |1a1=Baskaran |1y=1981 |1p=109 |2a1=Muthiah |2y=2004 |2p=404}}<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Laul |first=Brian |date=16 January 1983 |title=Where Cinema Is Politics and Politics Is Cinema |url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.101041/page/n287 |magazine=[[The Illustrated Weekly of India]] |pages=16\u201319}}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\nMudaliar had initially intented ''Pathi Bhakthi'' to be a [[star vehicle]] for his son [[M. K. Radha]], but thespian K. P. Kesavan was selected for the lead role instead.{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=174}}<ref name=\"VamananDinamalarNellai\" /> Radha, an MOBC actor, was eventually cast as the protagonist Krishnamurthy of ''Sathi Leelavathi''.<ref name=\"toast\" /> Other MOBC actors who made their screen debuts with the film were [[N. S. Krishnan]],{{efn|Although ''Sathi Leelavathi'' was Krishnan's first film project,<ref name=\"Americans\" /> because of production delays caused by the lawsuit, it became his second release.{{sfn|Kannan|2017|pp=30, 84}}<ref name=\"poppies\" />}} [[T. S. Balaiah]], and [[M. G. Ramachandran]], appearing as comedic character Balu, antagonist Ramanathan, and a police officer respectively.<ref name=\"pressbook\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/MGRs-first-film-steps/article14695764.ece |title=MGR's first film steps |date=25 April 2011 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=5 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005060725/https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/MGRs-first-film-steps/article14695764.ece |archive-date=5 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Guy |first=Randor |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/t-s-balaiah-endeared-himself-to-millions-of-fans-with-a-career-spanning-nearly-four-decades-says-randor-guy/article6324279.ece |title=Darling of the masses |date=16 August 2014 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=14 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181014064409/https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/t-s-balaiah-endeared-himself-to-millions-of-fans-with-a-career-spanning-nearly-four-decades-says-randor-guy/article6324279.ece |archive-date=14 October 2018 |author-link=Randor Guy}}</ref> Krishnan wrote the screenplay for his scenes and put on weight for the role.<ref>{{Cite news |last=\u0b9a\u0bb0\u0bb5\u0ba3\u0ba9\u0bcd |first=\u0baa\u0bc2.\u0b95\u0bca. |url=https://www.vikatan.com/news/coverstory/21760.html |title=\u0b95\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0bb5\u0bbe\u0ba3\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0b8e\u0ba9\u0bcd.\u0b8e\u0bb8\u0bcd.\u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0bb7\u0bcd\u0ba3\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b85\u0bb5\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bbf\u0bb1\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0ba8\u0bbe\u0bb3\u0bcd&nbsp;\u2013 \u0b9a\u0bbf\u0bb1\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1 \u0baa\u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc1 |date=29 November 2013 |work=[[Ananda Vikatan]] |access-date=9 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181009093037/https://www.vikatan.com/news/coverstory/21760.html |archive-date=9 October 2018 |language=ta |trans-title=The art lover N. S. Krishnan's birthday&nbsp;\u2013 Special Edition}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=\u0ba8\u0bbe\u0b95\u0bb0\u0bbe\u0b9c\u0ba9\u0bcd |first=\u0b9a\u0bcb\u0bb4 |url=https://www.hindutamil.in/news/supplements/hindu-talkies/63330-.html |title=\u0ba8\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bc8\u0bb5\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b9a\u0bbf\u0bb1\u0b95\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd: \u0b8e\u0ba9\u0bcd.\u0b8e\u0bb8\u0bcd.\u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0bb7\u0bcd\u0ba3\u0ba9\u0bcd - \u0b95\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0bb5\u0bbe\u0ba3\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0ba4\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0baf \u0b95\u0bca\u0bb2\u0bc8 \u0bb5\u0bb4\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1! |date=27 November 2015 |work=[[The Hindu (Tamil)]] |access-date=18 December 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828113000/https://www.hindutamil.in/news/supplements/hindu-talkies/63330-.html |archive-date=18 December 2019 |trans-title=Wings of Memories: N. S. Krishnan&nbsp;\u2013 A murder case against the lover of arts}}</ref>{{sfn|Kannan|2017|p=36}}\n\nRamachandran appeared in ''Pathi Bhakthi'' as the antagonist's henchman Veeramuthu,{{sfn|Kannan|2017|p=17}}{{sfn|Kannan|2017|p=28}} but MOBC owner Sachidanandam Pillai did not offer him a role in the film adaptation.{{sfn|Kannan|2010|p=85}} He later approached Mudaliar for a role in ''Sathi Leelavathi'' because he felt his role in ''Pathi Bhakthi'' offered him \"no room to shine\".{{sfn|Kannan|2017|pp=28\u201329}} According to Ramachandran, he was told he would play Detective Sreenivasan and later Krishnamurthy's friend Parasuraman,<ref>{{Cite book |last=Jayababu |first=S. V. |url=http://tamildigitallibrary.in/admin/assets/book/TVA_BOK_0010363_%E0%AE%AA%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A9%E0%AE%95%E0%AF%88_%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%B3%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%B3%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%8D_%E0%AE%8E%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%9C%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%86%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%8D_%E0%AE%A8%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%88%E0%AE%B5%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%95%E0%AE%B3%E0%AF%8D_2000.pdf |title=\u0baa\u0bc1\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0ba9\u0b95\u0bc8 \u0bb5\u0bb3\u0bcd\u0bb3\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b8e\u0bae\u0bcd.\u0b9c\u0bbf.\u0b86\u0bb0\u0bcd. \u0ba8\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bc8\u0bb5\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd 2000 |publisher=Jayababu |year=2000 |location=Chennai |pages=9 |language=ta |trans-title=Memories of the philanthropist of smiles MGR 2000 |access-date=17 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218021300/http://tamildigitallibrary.in/admin/assets/book/TVA_BOK_0010363_%E0%AE%AA%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A9%E0%AE%95%E0%AF%88_%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%B3%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%B3%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%8D_%E0%AE%8E%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%9C%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%86%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%8D_%E0%AE%A8%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%88%E0%AE%B5%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%95%E0%AE%B3%E0%AF%8D_2000.pdf |archive-date=18 February 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"MGR Filmfare\" /> but he was cast as Inspector Rangiah Naidu\u2014a role he disliked.{{sfn|Kannan|2017|pp=28\u201329}}<ref name=\"Tunes and trivia\" /> Ramachandran was paid an advance of {{INR}}100 (about $37.50 in 1936);{{sfn|Kannan|2017|p=29}}{{efn|name=exchange1936}} it was the first time he had seen a [[Indian 100-rupee note|100-rupee note]].<ref name=\"MGR Filmfare\" /> Chettiar gave the role of Sreenivasan to [[M. V. Mani]] without Mudaliar's knowledge,<ref name=\"pressbook\" />{{sfn|Kannan|2017|pp=29\u201330}} and P. Nammalvar was cast as Pasaruraman.<ref name=\"pressbook\" /> Despite Ramachandran's reluctance to play Rangiah, his mother was happy he got a \"respectable\" role and advised him to perform it responsibly.{{sfn|Kannan|2017|p=37}}\n\nThe casting of Krishnamurthy's wife Leelavathi was difficult; no actress was willing to play the character because the script required her to be physically abused and mistreated by her inebriated husband. In desperation, the producer asked Mudaliar and Radha to cast M. R. Gnanambal, Radha's wife, in the role.{{sfn|Guy|2016|p=83}} Gnanambal, who had retired from acting after her marriage, was initially reluctant to accept the role and came out of retirement to play it because no other actress would do so.<ref name=\"toast\" /><ref name=\"poppies\" /> Leelavathi's daughter Lakshmi was played by M. K. Mani, a boy. T. N. Lakshmana Rao, P. N. Ramakrishnan, Dhanalakshmi, Santhakumari, M. Chandra Bai, M. S. Murugesan and S. Sundaram were cast in supporting roles.<ref name=\"pressbook\" /> The film was also the feature debut of [[K. A. Thangavelu]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Raman |first=Mohan V. |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/King-of-comedy/article14995630.ece |title=King of comedy |date=24 September 2016 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=12 December 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181212085703/https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/King-of-comedy/article14995630.ece |archive-date=12 December 2018 |author-link=Mohan Raman}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Venkatraman |first=Karthikeyan |url=https://www.dinamani.com/specials/cinemaexpress/2017/mar/03/%E0%AE%8E%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%8E%E0%AE%99%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%95-%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%AA%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%95%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%95%E0%AF%81-%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%B1%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%88-2658937.html |title=\u0b8e\u0bb5\u0ba9\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd \u0b8e\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95 \u0bb5\u0bae\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1 \u0bb5\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb1\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bc8. |date=3 March 2017 |work=[[Dinamani]] |access-date=12 December 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181212073538/http://www.dinamani.com/specials/cinemaexpress/2017/mar/03/%E0%AE%8E%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%8E%E0%AE%99%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%95-%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%AA%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%95%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%95%E0%AF%81-%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%B1%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%88-2658937.html |archive-date=12 December 2018 |language=ta |trans-title=No-one dares to mess with us.}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\nPrincipal photography for ''Sathi Leelavathi'' began in 1935.<ref name=\"MGR Remembered Part 7\" />{{sfn|Rajadhyaksha|Willemen|1998|p=92}} Although Manorama Films was based in [[Coimbatore]],<ref name=\"Tunes and trivia\" /> the film was shot primarily at Vel Pictures Studio, Madras.{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=176}} Dungan wrote in his autobiography ''A Guide to Adventure'' (2001) that most of the cast were theatre actors and he was tasked with \"subduing [their] voices and facial expressions\".<ref name=\"MGR Remembered Part 8\" />{{sfn|Dungan|Smik|2001|pp=61\u201362}} According to him, when the actors faced the camera, they often froze and did not speak because it frightened them.<ref name=\"MGR Remembered Part 7\" /> In 1994, he recalled in an interview with ''Ananda Vikatan'', that Ramachandran initially did not understand the nuances of film acting and performed aggressively as though he was on stage. Dungan later advised and corrected Ramachandran to deliver his lines naturally.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vikatan.com/arts/nostalgia/40396--2 |title=\u0b8e\u0bae\u0bcd.\u0b9c\u0bbf.\u0b86\u0bb0\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b87\u0baf\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1\u0ba8\u0bb0\u0bcd! |date=30 January 1994 |website=[[Ananda Vikatan]] |language=ta |trans-title=MGR's first director! |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |archive-url=http://archive.today/FWJaN |archive-date=12 February 2020 |access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOne scene required Ramachandran to ride a bicycle but he did not know how to ride one. The sequence was thus filmed with him sitting on the bicycle with two people balancing it. They gave the bicycle a push as the camera rolled.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Vamanan |url=http://www.dinamalarnellai.com/web/news/24179 |title=\u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bc1\u0bb2\u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b90\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bae\u0bbe\u0ba9 \u0b85\u0bae\u0bc6\u0bb0\u0bbf\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0b9f\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b95\u0ba4\u0bc8! |date=13 March 2017 |work=[[Dinamalar]] |access-date=28 December 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228161112/http://www.dinamalarnellai.com/web/news/24179 |archive-date=28 December 2018 |location=Nellai |language=ta |trans-title=The story of the American Dungan who was totally involved in Tamil cinema |author-link=Vamanan}}</ref> According to film historian [[Film News Anandan]], filming was also done in Ceylon<ref name=\"anandan\" /> but [[Randor Guy]] wrote in the fortnightly ''[[Madras Musings]]'' that a large plot of land behind Vel Pictures Studio was used for the Ceylon tea plantation.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Guy |first=Randor |url=http://madrasmusings.com/older-archives/Vol%2018/Vol%20XVIII%20-%20No%2002.pdf |title=Vel's where MGR made his film debut |date=1-15 May 2008 |work=[[Madras Musings]] |access-date=8 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008060545/http://madrasmusings.com/older-archives/Vol%2018/Vol%20XVIII%20-%20No%2002.pdf |archive-date=8 October 2018 |author-link=Randor Guy}}</ref> With this film, Dungan introduced many features to Tamil cinema such as a lack of on-screen stage influences,<ref name=\"Americans\" />{{sfn|Guy|2016|p=79}} the \"cabaret dance\" or the \"club dance\",<ref name=\"IE SathiLeelavathi\" /> strict discipline, filming by schedule and camera mobility.<ref name=\"George\" />\n\nThere was no facility to pre-record songs in Madras at the time so performers had to sing on set. The accompanying musicians sat on a trolley and played the background musical score; this often restricted camera movement. In one scene, the orchestra sat under a nearby tree playing the [[harmonium]], [[tabla]] and other instruments while Radha's character sang at a tea plantation {{sfnm|1a1=Guy |1y=1997|1p=177 |2a1=Guy |2y=2016 |2pp=72\u201373}} The film's cinematographers were D. T. Telang and V. J. Shave,<ref name=\"ohiocountylibrary\" /> and Sircar and Dungan were the editors. Ramamurthi, the manager of Vel Pictures Studio, cleaned the exposed negatives by hand.<ref name=\"MGR Remembered Part 7\" /> The completed film was {{convert|18000|feet|metres|abbr=on}} in length and ran for 200 minutes.<ref name=\"MGR Remembered Part 8\" /><ref name=\"anandan\" />\n\n== Music ==\nThe music composer of ''Sathi Leelavathi'' is not credited in the film's [[song book]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Guy |first=Randor |url=http://mambalamtimes.in/admin/pdf/1397830127.MT%20Pages.pdf |title=Tamil Cinema 75&nbsp;\u2013 A Look Back {{!}} G. Ramanathan&nbsp;\u2013 3 |date=19\u201325 April 2014 |work=Mambalam Times |access-date=18 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181018113207/http://mambalamtimes.in/admin/pdf/1397830127.MT%20Pages.pdf |archive-date=18 October 2018 |page=4 |author-link=Randor Guy}}</ref> G. Sundhara Bhagavathar (also known as Sundhara Vadhiyar) was the lyricist in his cinematic debut.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cinemaexpress.com/cinemaexpress/story.aspx?Title=&artid=112692&SectionID=141&MainSectionID=141&SectionName=Interviews&SEO= |title=\u0b85\u0baa\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb5 \u0ba4\u0b95\u0bb5\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd-17: \u0b87\u0baf\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1\u0ba8\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0b8e\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bc0\u0bb8\u0bcd \u0b86\u0bb0\u0bcd. \u0b9f\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0ba9\u0bcd |work=[[Cinema Express]] |access-date=28 December 2018 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20161028053340/http://www.cinemaexpress.com/cinemaexpress/story.aspx?Title=&artid=112692&SectionID=141&MainSectionID=141&SectionName=Interviews&SEO= |archive-date=28 October 2016 |language=ta |trans-title=Rare information-17: Director Ellis R. Dungan}}</ref>\n\nThe melody of \"Theyila Thottathle\" (also spelt \"Theyilai Thottatile\") is based on [[Subramania Bharati]]'s poem \"Karumbu Thottathile\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Vamanan |url=http://www.dinamalarnellai.com/web/news/5426 |title=\u0ba4\u0b9f\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bc8\u0ba4\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bbe\u0ba3\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bbe\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bc7\u0bb0\u0bcb\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bae\u0bcd! |date=28 March 2016 |work=[[Dinamalar]] |access-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181006173908/http://www.dinamalarnellai.com/web/news/5426 |archive-date=6 October 2018 |location=Nellai |language=ta |trans-title=Bharati's gallop in his chariot crossing all barriers in film songs! |author-link=Vamanan}}</ref> The poem is about the plight of [[Debt bondage|bonded Indian labourers]] in [[Fiji]], while the song explores the problems of tea-plantation workers in Ceylon.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Venkatakrishnan |first=Sriram |url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/Memorial-to-Bharati/article15399096.ece |title=Memorial to Bharati |date=27 June 2008 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181006103021/https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/Memorial-to-Bharati/article15399096.ece |archive-date=6 October 2018 |author-link=V. Sriram}}</ref> The song, which is set in the [[Carnatic raga]] Chenchurutti, became popular and was frequently performed in concerts by [[Carnatic music]]ians. It was re-used in the [[Malayalam]] film ''[[Balan (film)|Balan]]'' (1938), as \"Jaathaka Doshathale\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Vijayakumar |first=B. |url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/Balan-1938/article15921329.ece |title=''Balan'' 1938 |date=7 September 2009 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181005190459/https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/Balan-1938/article15921329.ece |archive-date=5 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe other songs featured in the film were \"Thaayadhu Vayatrile Maayamai\", \"Thodudaiya Seviyan Vidai\", \"Hello Yennudaiya Dear\", \"Adhigha Sinamaen\", \"Paadhai Theriyamale\", \"Ini Yenna Seighuvaen Dhaeviyae\", \"Sadhikaaramaaranovubaanam\", \"Kaami Satthiyamaa Kannatthaik\", \"Pudhu Nilaa Mughap Poomaan Punniya\", \"Kallae Kadavuladaa Thambi\", \"Vaazhvinilae Maghaa Thaazvadaindhaenaiyo\", \"Undheepara Adhi Unnadha Thakkaliyae\" and \"Raattinamae Kadhar Poottinamae Kai\".<ref name=\"pressbook\" /><!--<ref>https://archive.today/20181014162827/http://songlyrics.lakshmansruthi.com/movie_song_list.php?id=Sathi%20Leelavathi</ref><ref>https://archive.today/20181014170731/http://www.mayyam.com/talk/showthread.php?10240-Ponmanachemmal-m-g-r-Filmography-news-amp-events/page3</ref> -->\n\n== Release and reception ==\n''Sathi Leelavathi'' had a \"[[Trade fair|trade show]]\" debut in Madras on 1 February 1936,<ref name=\"tradeshow\" /> and was theatrically released on 28 March that year. It was a major commercial success; according to film historian Aranthai Narayanan, this was due to Radha, Balaiah's and Krishnan's performances, Vasan's publicity, and support by [[British Raj|independence-era]] politicians of the anti-alcohol movement.<ref name=\"MGR Remembered Part 7\" /> The film ran for over 100 days in theatres.<ref>{{Cite book |url=http://tamildigitallibrary.in/book-detail.php?id=jZY9lup2kZl6TuXGlZQdjZt8l0U3&tag=%E0%AE%9A%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%88%20%E0%AE%A8%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%AF%E0%AE%95%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%8D%20%E0%AE%8E%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D.%E0%AE%9C%E0%AE%BF.%E0%AE%86%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%8D. |title=\u0b9a\u0bbe\u0ba4\u0ba9\u0bc8 \u0ba8\u0bbe\u0baf\u0b95\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b8e\u0bae\u0bcd.\u0b9c\u0bbf.\u0b86\u0bb0\u0bcd. |publisher=Arulmozhi Publications |year=1997 |page=28 |language=ta |trans-title=MGR, the man of achievements}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of its initial release, critics praised most aspects of the production, including the direction, photography, sound design, and writing.<ref name=\"pressbook\" /><ref name=\"tradeshow\" /> A few commentators including a reviewer for ''[[The Illustrated Weekly of India]]'' even saw the writing as an improvement on the novel. Praising the plot's continuity and climax, the reviewer called the film more \"interesting, natural and convincing\" than its source material.<ref name=\"pressbook\" /> The art magazine ''Aadal Paadal'' praised the social setting of ''Sathi Lellavathi'' in its January 1937 issue.{{sfn|Baskaran|2004|p=47}}. Politician [[C. Rajagopalachari]], a frequent critic of cinema, also appreciated the film's Gandhian ideals and pro-prohibition stance{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=177}} but said \"the main artiste in a [''charkha'']-spinning sequence did not know how to handle it\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Guy |first=Randor |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/chen-columns/sampoorna-ramayanam-1956/article3588925.ece |title=''Sampoorna Ramayanam'' 1956 |date=30 June 2012 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=4 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171123083806/http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/chen-columns/sampoorna-ramayanam-1956/article3588925.ece |archive-date=23 November 2017 |author-link=Randor Guy}}</ref> A writer for ''The Indian Review'' wrote that the film \"appeals to all classes and masses of the Tamil province\".<ref>{{Cite magazine |year=1936 |editor-last=Natesan |editor-first=G. A. |editor-link=G. A. Natesan |title=Sati Leelavati |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b_JVhvcfSkcC&dq=The+Indian+Review+%22Sati+Leelavati%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=LEELAVATI |magazine=The Indian Review |publisher=G. A. Natesan & Company |volume=37 |page=205}}</ref>\n\nThe acting performances also received generally positive response from critics.<ref name=\"tradeshow\" /> In a 14 February 1936 review, ''[[The Hindu]]'' praised Radha's performance for its \"naturalness and ease\", Balaiah's villainy and Gnanambal's performance in the \"difficult role\" of Leelavathi.<ref name=\"pressbook\" /> Playwright and retired [[Subordinate judge|sub-judge]] [[Pammal Sambandha Mudaliar]] echoed the sentiment, praising Radha for performing a \"difficult part very creditably\".<ref name=\"pressbook\" /> A ''Cine Art Review'' writer was also appreciative of the [[cross-gender acting]] of M. K. Mani, who played Lakshmi in the film. The writer was particularly impressed by the opening scene in which Lakshmi hums a tune while going downstairs.<ref name=\"pressbook\" />\n\nSeveral new filmmaking techniques introduced by Dungan were unappreciated at the time. In ''Silver Screen'' magazine on 1 August 1936, Pe. Ko. Sundararajan (journalist and writer for ''[[Manikkodi|Manikodi]]'') said the new methods of depicting emotions were not understood by the audience; in one scene, Dungan showed the dancing girl as seen by the inebriated protagonist, and in another he indicated his fear by depicting his twitching fingers and feet. According to Sundararajan, the techniques helped the actors to emote and showcased Dungan's talent; however, the audience thought the lighting in the first scene was poor and that the film was stuck in the second. He opined that this reflected their ignorance.{{sfn|Baskaran|2004|p=39}}\n\n== Legacy ==\n''Sathi Leelavathi'' attained cult status in Tamil cinema<ref>{{Cite news |last=Guy |first=Randor |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-columns/punjab-kesari-1938/article5973131.ece |title=''Punjab Kesari'' 1938 |date=3 May 2014 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=16 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016102149/https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-columns/punjab-kesari-1938/article5973131.ece |archive-date=16 October 2018 |author-link=Randor Guy}}</ref> and made Dungan an in-demand director.<ref name=\"IE SathiLeelavathi\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.frontline.in/arts-and-culture/dungan-the-director/article5492566.ece |title=Dungan the director |date=10 January 2014 |work=[[Frontline (magazine)|Frontline]] |access-date=8 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20141126025215/http://www.frontline.in/arts-and-culture/dungan-the-director/article5492566.ece |archive-date=26 November 2014}}</ref> The techniques introduced by Dungan in the film became staples of Tamil cinema.<ref name=\"George\" />{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=177}} Footage about the making of ''Sathi Leelavathi'' was later included in ''[[An American in Madras]]'', a documentary about Dungan's career in India.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Chatterji |first=Shoma A. |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2014/20140126/spectrum/entertainment1.htm |title=A fascinating documentary |date=26 January 2014 |work=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)]] |access-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181024114955/https://www.tribuneindia.com/2014/20140126/spectrum/entertainment1.htm |archive-date=24 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Vijayan |first=Naveena |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2014/aug/16/American-Touch-to-Tamil-Cinema-648420.html |title=American Touch to Tamil Cinema |date=16 August 2014 |work=[[The New Indian Express]] |access-date=17 November 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117132408/https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2014/aug/16/American-Touch-to-Tamil-Cinema-648420.html |archive-date=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Sathi Leelavathi'' was the first Tamil film to be successful in overseas markets.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Venkateswaran |first=N. |url=http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Repository/getFiles.asp?Style=OliveXLib:LowLevelEntityToPrintGifMSIE_PASTISSUES2&Type=text/html&Locale=english-skin-custom&Path=TOICH/2011/03/20&ChunkNum=0&ID=Ar00200 |title=The chronicler of Kollywood |date=20 March 2011 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=14 October 2018 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181014031543/http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Repository/getFiles.asp?Style=OliveXLib:LowLevelEntityToPrintGifMSIE_PASTISSUES2&Type=text/html&Locale=english-skin-custom&Path=TOICH/2011/03/20&ChunkNum=0&ID=Ar00200 |archive-date=14 October 2018}}</ref> According to film historian Swarnavel Eswaran Pillai, despite Vasan's initial aversion to films,{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=241}} ''Sathi Leelavathi''{{'}}s success encouraged him to enter the industry as a distributor.{{sfn|Pillai|2015|p=152}} Ramachandran avoided playing roles similar to Rangiah Naidu in his later films, preferring to play a \"good Samaritan\" in ''[[Marmayogi]]'' (1951), ''[[Malaikkallan]]'' (1954), ''[[Nadodi Mannan]]'' (1958) and ''[[Enga Veettu Pillai]]'' (1965).<ref>{{Cite news |last=Venkatramani |first=S. H. |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/cover-story/story/19880115-mgr-a-genius-with-an-uncanny-ability-to-think-up-populist-schemes-796840-1988-01-15 |title=MGR: A genius with an uncanny ability to think up populist schemes |date=15 January 1988 |work=[[India Today]] |access-date=15 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181015112743/https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/cover-story/story/19880115-mgr-a-genius-with-an-uncanny-ability-to-think-up-populist-schemes-796840-1988-01-15 |archive-date=15 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nNo complete print of ''Sathi Leelavathi'' is known to survive, making it a [[List of incomplete or partially lost films|partially lost film]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |url=https://www.thehindu.com/books/books-authors/another-anandan-in-the-making/article19593507.ece |title=Another Anandan in the making |date=31 August 2017 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=8 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20170918071320/http://www.thehindu.com/books/books-authors/another-anandan-in-the-making/article19593507.ece |archive-date=18 September 2017}}</ref> What remains of the film is preserved in the West Virginia State Archives.<ref name=\"ohiocountylibrary\" />\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notes\n| colwidth =\n| notes =\n{{efn\n| name = exchange1936\n| The exchange rate in 1936 was 2.67 Indian rupees ({{INR}}) per 1 US dollar (US$).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.measuringworth.com/datasets/exchangeglobal/result.php?year_source=1920&year_result=1945&countryE%5B%5D=India |title=Exchange Rates Between the United States Dollar and Forty-one Currencies |last=Officer |first=Lawrence H. |date=2015 |website=MeasuringWorth |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181014130029/https://www.measuringworth.com/datasets/exchangeglobal/result.php?year_source=1920&year_result=1945&countryE%5B%5D=India |archive-date=14 October 2018 |access-date=14 October 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"George\">{{Cite book |last=George |first=T. J. S. |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=eWO2AQAACAAJ |title=M.S. Subbulakshmi: The Definitive Biography |publisher=[[Aleph Book Company]] |year=2016 |isbn=9789384067601 |pages=101 |author-link=T. J. S. George}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MGR Remembered Part 7\">{{Cite web |url=http://sangam.org/mgr-remembered-part-7/ |title=MGR Remembered&nbsp;\u2013 Part 7 |last=Kantha |first=Sachi Sri |authorlink=Sachi Sri Kantha |date=2 April 2013 |website=[[Ilankai Tamil Sangam]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426063242/http://sangam.org/mgr-remembered-part-7/ |archive-date=26 April 2017 |access-date=25 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"pressbook\">{{Cite book |url=http://tamildigitallibrary.in/admin/assets/book/TVA_BOK_0008620_%E0%AE%9A%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF-%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%80%E0%AE%B2%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF.pdf |title=Sathi Leelavathi |publisher=Manorama Films |year=1936 |location=[[Coimbatore]] |type=[[pressbook]] |access-date=5 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005194851/http://tamildigitallibrary.in/admin/assets/book/TVA_BOK_0008620_%E0%AE%9A%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF-%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%80%E0%AE%B2%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF.pdf |archive-date=5 October 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"anandan\">{{Cite book |last=Film News Anandan |url=http://www.lakshmansruthi.com/cineprofiles/1936-cinedetails10.asp |title=Sadhanaigal padaitha Tamil Thiraipada Varalaaru |publisher=Sivagami Publications |year=2004 |location=Chennai |language=Tamil |trans-title=History of Landmark Tamil films |author-link=Film News Anandan |access-date=5 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005051333/http://www.lakshmansruthi.com/cineprofiles/1936-cinedetails10.asp |archive-date=5 October 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Americans\">{{Cite news |last=Muthiah |first=S. |url=https://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/mp/2004/09/06/stories/2004090600190300.htm |title=Americans in Tamil cinema |date=6 September 2004 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=5 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005044125/https://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/mp/2004/09/06/stories/2004090600190300.htm |archive-date=5 October 2018 |author-link=S. Muthiah}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"IE SathiLeelavathi\">{{Cite news |last=Guy |first=Randor |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=s4ZlAAAAIBAJ&sjid=sJ4NAAAAIBAJ&pg=1511%2C1703991 |title=''Sathi Leelavathi'', made after a legal battle |date=2 February 1991 |work=[[The Indian Express]] |page=19 |author-link=Randor Guy}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"started\">{{Cite news |last=Muthiah |first=S. |url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/The-film-that-got-MGR-started/article17199879.ece |title=The film that got MGR started |date=6 February 2017 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=4 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005045137/https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/The-film-that-got-MGR-started/article17199879.ece |archive-date=5 October 2018 |author-link=S. Muthiah}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Limca\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IP1tAAAAMAAJ |title=Limca Book of Records |publisher=Bisleri Beverages Limited |year=1999 |quote=First directed by a foreigner ''Sathi Leelavathi'' (1936) highlighting the evils of alcoholism was directed by Ellis R. {{sic|Duncan}}}}</ref