llain films]]\n[[Category:2010s action adventure films]]\n[[Category:2010s superhero films]]\n[[Category:American action adventure films]]\n[[Category:American superhero films]]\n[[Category:DC Extended Universe films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American vigilante films]]\n[[Category:American prison films]]\n[[Category:Fantasy action films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by David Ayer]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2016]]\n[[Category:Films set in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Films set in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Films set in the White House]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Atlas Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by David Ayer]]\n[[Category:Films about witchcraft]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n[[Category:Familicide in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Steven Price]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Academy Award for Best Makeup]]\n[[Category:Superhero films featuring female antagonists]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Paul Dini]]\n[[Category:Harley Quinn in other media]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the 2021 sequel|The Suicide Squad (film)}}\n{{short description|2016 American superhero film written and directed by David Ayer}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Suicide Squad\n| image          = Suicide Squad (film) Poster.png\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[David Ayer]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Charles Roven]]\n* [[Richard Suckle]]\n}}\n| writer         = David Ayer\n| based on       = {{Based on|[[Suicide Squad]]|[[John Ostrander]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Will Smith]]\n* [[Margot Robbie]]\n* [[Jared Leto]]\n* [[Joel Kinnaman]]\n* [[Viola Davis]]\n* [[Jai Courtney]]\n* [[Jay Hernandez]]\n* [[Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje]]\n* [[Karen Fukuhara]]\n* [[Ike Barinholtz]]\n* [[Scott Eastwood]]\n* [[Cara Delevingne]]<!--PER POSTER/TRAILER BILLING; DO NOT REMOVE/ADD NAMES-->\n}}\n| music          = [[Steven Price (composer)|Steven Price]]\n| cinematography = [[Roman Vasyanov]]\n| editing        = [[John Gilroy (film editor)|John Gilroy]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[DC Films]]\n* [[RatPac Entertainment]]\n* [[Atlas Entertainment]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2016|8|1|[[Beacon Theatre (New York City)|Beacon Theatre]]|2016|8|5|United States}}\n| runtime        = 123 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 122:55--><ref name=\"Runtime\"/>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $175 million<ref name=\"LATimes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-ca-mn-suicide-squad-comic-con-feature-20160719-snap-story.html |title=The pressures behind 'Suicide Squad,' the DC Comics movie that Warner Bros. needs to work, and work big |first=Josh |last=Rottenberg |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=August 1, 2016 |accessdate=August 1, 2016}}</ref>\n| gross          = $746.8 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=dc2016.htm |title=Suicide Squad (2016) |accessdate=December 20, 2017 |website=Box Office Mojo}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Suicide Squad''''' is a 2016 American [[superhero film]] based on the [[DC Comics]] [[Suicide Squad|supervillain team of the same name]]. The third installment in the [[DC Extended Universe]], it was written and directed by [[David Ayer]] and stars an [[ensemble cast]] including [[Will Smith]], [[Margot Robbie]], [[Jared Leto]], [[Joel Kinnaman]], [[Viola Davis]], [[Jai Courtney]], [[Jay Hernandez]], [[Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje]], [[Scott Eastwood]], [[Karen Fukuhara]], [[Ike Barinholtz]], and [[Cara Delevingne]]. In the film, a secret government agency led by [[Amanda Waller]] recruits imprisoned [[supervillain]]s to execute dangerous black ops missions and save the world from a powerful threat in exchange for reduced sentences.\n\nBy February 2009, a Suicide Squad film was in development at [[Warner Bros.]] Ayer signed on to write and direct in September 2014, and by October, the casting process had begun. [[Principal photography]] began in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]] on April 13, 2015, with additional filming in [[Chicago]], and ended in August that year.\n\n''Suicide Squad'' premiered in [[New York City]] on August 1, 2016, and was released in the [[United States]] in 2D, [[Real D 3D]], [[IMAX]], and [[IMAX 3D]] on August 5, 2016. Following a strong debut that set new box office records, the film grossed over $746 million worldwide, making it the [[2016 in film|tenth highest-grossing film of 2016]]. It received generally negative<!--- as sourced in Critical reviews section.---> reviews from critics, who criticized its perceived thin plot, direction, editing, and characterization,<!--DO NOT PUT OTHER ACTORS AS IT IS NOT SUPPORTED BY CONSENSUS IN THE PRESS. ALREADY DISCUSSED IN TALK.--> though Robbie's performance and the makeup was praised. The film was nominated for and won multiple awards across various categories, including an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] for [[Academy Award for Best Makeup and Hairstyling|Best Makeup and Hairstyling]] at the [[89th Academy Awards]], making it the first film in the DCEU to win an Academy Award. It was followed by the [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] film ''[[Birds of Prey (2020 film)|Birds of Prey]]'', starring Robbie, in 2020, and will be followed by the [[standalone sequel]] ''[[The Suicide Squad (film)|The Suicide Squad]]'' in 2021, with Robbie, Kinnaman, Davis, and Courtney returning.\n\n==Plot==\nIn the [[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice|one-year aftermath]] of <!-- do not link this to Batman v Superman because it's an easter egg link-->[[Superman]]'s death,{{refn|name=Timeline|group=N|As depicted in the 2016 film ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]''.}}<!--be explicit, see WP:EASTEREGG--> intelligence officer [[Amanda Waller]] convinces [[Washington, D.C.|Washington D.C.]] officials to allow her to assemble [[Suicide Squad|Task Force X]], a team of dangerous criminals imprisoned at Belle Reve Special Security Barracks. The team consists of elite hitman [[Deadshot]], former [[psychiatrist]] [[Harley Quinn]], pyrokinetic ex-gangster [[El Diablo (comics)#Chato Santana|El Diablo]], opportunistic thief [[Captain Boomerang]], genetic mutant [[Killer Croc]], and specialized assassin [[Slipknot (comics)|Slipknot]]. They are placed under command of Colonel [[Rick Flag]] to be used as disposable assets in high-risk missions for the United States government. A nanite bomb is implanted in the neck of each team member, designed to detonate should the member rebel or try to escape.\n\nOne of Waller's intended recruits is Flag's girlfriend [[Enchantress (DC Comics)|Dr. June Moone]], an archaeologist possessed by a demonic witch known as the \"Enchantress\". She quickly turns on Waller for imprisoning her, deciding to eradicate humankind with a mystical weapon. She besieges Midway City by transforming its populace into a horde of monsters, and summons her brother Incubus to assist her. Waller then deploys the squad to extract a high-profile mark from Midway, which is reported to be under a terrorist attack. Joining them is [[Katana (comics)|Katana]], a Japanese swordswoman.\n\nHarley's homicidal lover [[Joker (character)|Joker]] finds out about her predicament and tortures Belle Reve security officer Griggs into leading him to the facility where the nanite bombs are made. There, he blackmails Dr. Van Criss into disabling Harley's bomb. Upon arrival, the squad's helicopter is shot down, forcing them to proceed on foot to their target. Boomerang convinces Slipknot that he believes the bombs are a ruse to keep them in check: the latter attempts to escape and is killed. Meanwhile, the squad is ambushed by Enchantress' minions. They eventually fight their way through to a safe house, where they learn that their mark is Waller herself, who is attempting to cover up her involvement in Enchantress' siege.\n\nThe squad escorts Waller to the rooftop for extraction, but the arriving helicopter has been hijacked by the Joker and his men, who open fire on the squad. Harley's bomb is disarmed by Dr. Van Criss, leaving Flag unable to execute her and allowing her to climb aboard the helicopter. Waller's men subsequently shoot down the helicopter, and Harley falls out while the Joker is presumed dead, after which Harley rejoins the squad. Alerted to Waller's whereabouts, Enchantress' minions arrive and kidnap her. Deadshot finds Waller's confidential files, from which he learns the truth about Enchantress, which Flag then is forced to confirm. This causes the squad members to abandon him. With Waller compromised, Flag relieves the squad of the mission but chooses to continue. Realizing they have an opportunity to prove themselves, they soon rejoin him and locate Enchantress at a partially-flooded subway station. Killer Croc and a group of [[Navy SEAL]]s, led by Lieutenant GQ Edwards, go underwater to plant a bomb underneath Incubus. El Diablo embraces his abilities and distracts Incubus long enough for the bomb to detonate underneath, killing them both as well as Edwards.\n\nThe remaining squad members battle Enchantress together but are ultimately defeated. Enchantress offers to fulfill their deepest desires in exchange for their allegiance, and Harley feigns interest in order to get close enough to cut out Enchantress' heart. Killer Croc then throws explosives into Enchantress' weapon and Deadshot shoots them, destroying the device. Flag takes Enchantress' heart and crushes it, finally freeing June from the curse. Waller, still alive, emerges, and the squad members are returned to Belle Reve with ten years off their sentences. All but Captain Boomerang are allowed special privileges. The Joker, alive and unscathed, breaks into the penitentiary and rescues Harley.\n\nIn a [[mid-credits scene]], Waller meets with [[Batman|Bruce Wayne]], who agrees to protect her from the backlash against her role in Enchantress' rampage in exchange for access to the government's files on the expanding [[metahuman]] community and a document on both [[Flash (Barry Allen)|Barry Allen]] and [[Aquaman|Arthur Curry]]. Waller then advises him to stop working late nights, to which Bruce answers her to shut down Task Force X or else he and his \"[[Justice League (film)|friends]]\" will do it.\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Suicide Squad by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|Cast of ''Suicide Squad'' at the 2016 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]. From left to right: Will Smith, Margot Robbie, Jared Leto, Viola Davis, Joel Kinnaman, Scott Eastwood, Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje, Jai Courtney, Jay Hernandez, Cara Delevingne, and Adam Beach]]\n* [[Will Smith]] as [[Deadshot|Floyd Lawton / Deadshot]]:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cinemablend.com/news/1536049/new-suicide-squad-video-shines-the-spotlight-on-will-smiths-deadshot |title=New Suicide Squad Video Shines The Spotlight On Will Smith's Deadshot |first=Adam |last=Holmes |publisher=CinemaBlend|date=July 19, 2016 }}</ref>\n: An expert marksman and assassin.<ref name=\"CastVariety\"/><ref name=\"CastTelegraph\"/> A mercenary by day and a concerned father by night, Deadshot is a conflicted criminal who enjoys the hunt, but still tries to do right by his young daughter.<ref name=\"EWProfiles\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/gallery/suicide-squad-character-photos |title='Suicide Squad': Meet the Roster of Rogues |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=July 8, 2016 |accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref> Smith was simultaneously offered to appear in ''Suicide Squad'' and ''[[Independence Day: Resurgence]]'', the sequel to ''[[Independence Day (1996 film)|Independence Day]]'' which he starred in. Smith opted to portray Deadshot, saying that the choice was \"nothing about the qualities of the movie - but the choice of trying to go forward versus clinging and clawing backwards.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stolworthy |first1=Jacob |title=Will Smith explains why he chose Suicide Squad over Independence Day 2 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/will-smith-explains-why-he-chose-suicide-squad-over-independence-day-2-a7471771.html |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=December 13, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Jared Leto]] as [[Joker (character)|The Joker]]:\n: A psychopathic crime boss and the nemesis of [[Batman]]. Leto described his role as \"nearly [[William Shakespeare|Shakespearean]]\" and a \"beautiful disaster of a character;\" about portraying the villain, he stated, \"I took a pretty deep dive. But this was a unique opportunity and I couldn't imagine doing it another way. It was fun, playing these [[Mind games|psychological games]]. But at the same time it was very painful.\" Leto [[Breaking character|never broke character]] throughout filming, with Smith going as far as stating he never met him. In preparation for the role, Leto spent his time alone, listened to [[gospel music]] from the 1920s \u2014commenting he senses \"Joker may be much older than people think\" \u2014 and read literature on [[shamanism]]. Influences for the character's appearance include the work of [[Alejandro Jodorowsky]].<ref name=\"Empire20152\">{{cite news |title=Superbad |last=de Semlyen |first=Nick |date=December 2015 |work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] |pages=64\u201373 }}</ref> The Joker's tattoos were added by Ayer, who believed it gave the character a modernized gangster look.<ref name=\"JokerEWMental\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/04/15/jared-leto-joker-suicide-squad |title=Jared Leto dives deep to play The Joker in Suicide Squad |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=April 15, 2016 |accessdate=April 17, 2016 |last=Sperling |first=Nicole |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417113453/http://www.ew.com/article/2016/04/15/jared-leto-joker-suicide-squad |url-status=live |archivedate=April 17, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Margot Robbie]] as [[Harley Quinn|Dr. Harleen Quinzel / Harley Quinn]]:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.superherohype.com/news/378543-harley-quinn-suicide-squad-promo-gives-you-the-giggles#/slide/1 |title=Harley Quinn Suicide Squad Promo Gives You the Giggles |first=Max |last=Evry |date=July 20, 2016 |publisher=superherohype.com}}</ref>\n: A former [[psychiatrist]] at [[Arkham Asylum]] seduced by the Joker into becoming his crazed partner-in-crime.<ref name=\"CastVariety\"/><ref name=\"CastTelegraph\"/> Producer [[Richard Suckle]] described the character as, \"a fan fave. Funny, crazy, scary. ... You can't come up with enough adjectives to describe all the different things you see her do.\"<ref name=\"EmpireNewImages\">{{cite web |url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/new-suicide-squad-images-killer-croc-amanda-waller/ |title=New Suicide Squad Images: Killer Croc And Amanda Waller |last=De Semlyen |first=Phil |date=October 29, 2015 |id=Accessed October 30, 2015 |work=Empire}}</ref> Robbie described Quinn as one of the Squad's most manipulative members, and her relationship with Joker as \"incredibly dysfunctional,\" adding that Quinn is, \"mad about him\u2014like, literally, mad. She's crazy. But she loves him. And it's a really unhealthy, dysfunctional relationship. But an addictive one.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/herocomplex/la-et-hc-margot-robbie-on-harley-quinn-20160412-story.html |title=Margot Robbie explains why Harley Quinn is the most manipulative member of the 'Suicide Squad' |work=Los Angeles Times |date=April 13, 2016 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Joel Kinnaman]] as [[Rick Flag|Colonel Rick Flag]]:<ref name=\"FlagSpelling\" />\n: A [[United States Military Academy|West Point]] graduate and [[Special Forces (United States Army)|Army Special Forces]] colonel who leads the Suicide Squad in the field. He is all business and executes Amanda Waller's orders but does not always agree with her goals or methods.<ref name=\"EWProfiles\"/> [[Tom Hardy]] was previously cast in the role but was forced to drop out because of scheduling conflicts.<ref name=\"CastTelegraph\"/><ref name=\"CastCollider\"/>\n* [[Viola Davis]] as [[Amanda Waller]]:<ref name=\"CastWaller\"/>\n: The government official who gives out the Squad's orders.<ref name=\"EmpireNewImages\"/> Ambitious and devious, she has big plans and intends to let no [[metahuman]] or military protocol get in her way.<ref name=\"EWProfiles\"/> Davis stated she is fascinated by the character, singling out her psychology and strength and describing her as a \"powerful black woman, hard, ready to pick up a gun and shoot anyone at will.\"<ref name=\"CastWaller2\"/> She described Waller as \"relentless in her villainy\" and noted that her powers are \"her intelligence and her complete lack of guilt.\"<ref name=\"EmpireNewImages\"/><ref name=\"Empire2015\"/>\n* [[Jai Courtney]] as [[Captain Boomerang|George \"Digger\" Harkness / Captain Boomerang]]:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qqwsRrEf4O8 |title=Suicide Squad - Boomerang Promo Clip |publisher=YouTube |date=July 16, 2016 |accessdate=August 4, 2016}}</ref>\n: A thief who uses deadly boomerangs,<ref name=\"CastVariety\"/><ref name=\"CastTelegraph\"/> described as rugged, unpredictable and mouthy.<ref name=\"EWProfiles\"/> About his role, Courtney stated, \"he is an absolute [[bogan]], in the purest sense. [[David Ayer]]'s first instruction was, 'find your inner dirtbag'.\"<ref name=\"Empire2015\"/>\n* [[Jay Hernandez]] as [[El Diablo (comics)#Chato Santana|Chato Santana / El Diablo]]:<ref name=\"CastCollider\"/><ref name=\"Empire2015\"/>\n: A former [[Los Angeles]] gang member who has [[metahuman]] powers that allow him to summon flames, and transform himself into a monstrous fire demon-like entity.<ref name=\"Empire2015\"/> He has squelched his fire-conjuring powers to a solitary flame as penance for the horrors he inflicted on those he loved.<ref name=\"EWProfiles\"/> Hernandez set his character apart from his teammates as he \"just wants to stay out of the fight,\" while \"most of [the Squad members] are happy to get out there and kill people.\"<ref name=\"Empire2015\"/>\n* [[Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje]] as [[Killer Croc|Waylon Jones / Killer Croc]]:\n: A cannibalistic metahuman criminal who suffers from a regressive [[atavism]] which caused him to develop reptilian features.<ref name=\"CastTelegraph\"/><ref name=\"CastCroc\" /> Being a meta-human, he possesses near superhuman strength, high endurance, and the capacity to breathe underwater. His skin allows him to withstand high caliber weapons and skin abrasion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.argus-gov.com/ |title=A.R.G.U.S. |publisher=[[Warner Bros.]] |accessdate=January 5, 2018}}</ref> Akinnuoye-Agbaje described the character as \"a cannibal with rage issues.\"<ref name=\"EmpireNewImages\"/>\n* [[Cara Delevingne]] as [[Enchantress (DC Comics)|Dr. June Moone / Enchantress]]:\n: An archaeologist who is possessed by an ancient evil force that transforms her into a host of a powerful sorceress, when summoned.<ref name=\"CastVariety\"/><ref name=\"EmpireNewImages\"/><ref name=\"Empire2015\"/> Unleashed after a long period of imprisonment, the entity draws the attention of Waller.<ref name=\"Empire2015\"/> Delevingne described Moone as \"an adventure-seeker who\u2019s always wanted some excitement\" and Enchantress as \"a feral being.\"<ref name=\"Empire2015\"/> Intended to be a recruit for the squad, Enchantress instead seeks revenge against mankind for imprisoning her and her brother's souls in artifacts after years of worshipping them.\n* [[Ike Barinholtz]] as Capt. Hunter Griggs:<ref name=\"CastVarietyMisc\" /> \n: An officer at Belle Reve's Special Security Barracks, the black site where the government imprisons the squad.\n* [[Scott Eastwood]] as \"GQ\" Edwards:<ref name=\"CastVarietyMisc\" /> \n: A [[United States Navy SEALs|Navy SEAL]] Lieutenant who assists Flag during the squad's mission. After working with actor [[Shia LaBeouf]] on ''[[Fury (2014 film)|Fury]]'', Ayer originally sought him out for the role, but the studio was not interested in the actor.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/shia-labeouf-drinking-steven-spielberg-american-honey-1201851776/ |title=How Shia LaBeouf Stopped Drinking and Found the Career He Wanted |work=Variety |last=Setoodeh |first=Ramin |date=September 6, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Adam Beach]] as [[Slipknot (comics)|Christopher Weiss / Slipknot]]:\n: A mercenary, specializing in tactical grappling and scaling.<ref name=\"CastSlipKnot\"/>\n* [[Karen Fukuhara]] as [[Katana (comics)|Tatsu Yamashiro / Katana]]:\n: A widowed expert martial artist and swordswoman who mourns her husband's death.<ref name=\"CastTelegraph\"/><ref name=\"EWProfiles\"/><ref name=\"CastCollider\"/> She serves as Rick Flag's bodyguard and wields the mystical Soultaker blade, capable of trapping the souls of its victims. As she is a volunteer, not a criminal, she does not have a micro-bomb implant. Fukuhara stated that Katana \"has morals and codes. She can also slice through hundreds of people without taking a breath.\"<ref name=\"Empire2015\">{{cite news |first=Nick |last=de Semlyen |title=Superbad |work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] |pages=64\u201373 |date=December 2015 }}</ref>\n\n[[Ben Affleck]] appears as [[Batman|Bruce Wayne / Batman]], and [[Ezra Miller]] appears as [[Flash (Barry Allen)|Barry Allen / The Flash]], both reprising their roles from ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]'' with Miller's being a [[cameo role]]; while [[Jason Momoa]] makes a brief photographic appearance as [[Aquaman|Arthur Curry / Aquaman]].<ref name=\"Batman-Suicide-Squad-confirmed\">{{cite news |first1=Brian |last1=Truitt |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2016/01/10/batman-v-superman-suicide-squad-2016-superhero-movies/78249180/ |title=2016 brings Batman, Superman and the 'Dawn' of a new superhero universe |work=[[USA Today]] |date=January 10, 2016 |accessdate=January 10, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Ezra-The-Flash-Confirmed\">{{cite news |last1=Kit |first1=Borys |title='Suicide Squad' Adds Key DC Character Weeks Before Release |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/suicide-squad-key-dc-character-914995 |accessdate=July 28, 2016 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=July 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/07/29/another-major-dc-character-to-appear-in-suicide-squad |title=Another Major DC Character to Appear in 'Suicide Squad' |website=IGN.com |last1=Reilly |first1=Luke}}</ref> Alain Chanoine portrays Incubus, the brother of Enchantress, who possesses the body of a businessman in Midway City in order to have a physical form.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/08/05/suicide-squads-second-mystery-villain-incubus-revealed |title=Suicide Squad's Mysterious Second Villain, Incubus, Revealed |website=IGN |last=Vejvoda |first=Jim |date=August 5, 2016 |accessdate=August 8, 2016}}</ref> [[Jim Parrack]] and [[Common (rapper)|Common]] appear as the Joker's henchmen, [[Jonny Frost]] and Monster T, respectively.<ref name=\"Empire2015\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/common-joins-suicide-squad-790824 |title=Common Joins 'Suicide Squad' (Exclusive) |last=Kit |first=Borys |work=The Wrap |date=April 22, 2015 |accessdate=April 27, 2015}}</ref> [[David Harbour]] portrays government official Dexter Tolliver, [[Alex Meraz]] portrays Navy SEAL Gomez, and Matt Baram portrays Dr. Van Criss, a scientist at Wayne Enterprises' branch Van Criss Laboratories.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://comicbook.com/2015/04/29/alex-meraz-david-harbour-join-suicide-squad-viola-davis-amanda-w/ |title=Alex Meraz & David Harbour Join Suicide Squad; Viola Davis' Amanda Waller Haircut |last=Jayson |first=Jay |publisher=ComicBook.com |accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/suicide-squad-alex-meraz-twilight-1201482900/# |title='Twilight' Actor Joins 'Suicide Squad' |last=Kroll |first=Justin |work=Variety |accessdate=April 27, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"CastVarietyMisc\" /> [[Shailyn Pierre-Dixon]] plays Zoe Lawton, Deadshot's daughter, and Corina Calderon plays Grace Santana, Diablo's wife.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://comicbook.com/2015/08/07/suicide-squads-jim-parrack-seemingly-confirmed-as-johnny-frost/ |title=Suicide Squad's Jim Parrack Seemingly Confirmed As Johnny Frost |first=Russ |last=Burlingame |publisher=Comicbook.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/arts-and-life/entertainment/movies/canadian-shailyn-pierre-dixon-on-playing-deadshots-daughter-in-suicide-squad-388915841.html |title=Canadian Shailyn Pierre-Dixon on playing Deadshot's daughter in 'Suicide Squad' |work=Winnipeg Free Press |last=Ahearn |first=Victoria |date=August 2, 2016 |accessdate=August 2, 2016}}</ref> [[David Ayer]], writer and director of the film, makes a cameo appearance as a Belle Reve officer.\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nThe film was announced in 2009 with [[Dan Lin]] as producer, Stephen Gilchrist as co-producer and Justin Marks as the screenwriter.<ref name=\"Suicideannounced\">{{cite web |last1=Mcnary |first1=Dave |title=Warner Bros. sets up 'Suicide Squad' |url=https://variety.com/2009/film/features/warner-bros-sets-up-suicide-squad-1118000590/ |website=Variety |accessdate=September 18, 2016|date=February 26, 2009 }}</ref> [[David Ayer]] signed on to direct and write the film in September 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=Warner Bros. Circling David Ayer for DC Comics' 'Suicide Squad' (Exclusive) |url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/warner-bros-circling-david-ayer-for-adaptation-of-dc-comics-suicide-squad-1201308883/ |accessdate=September 19, 2014 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=September 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>Kit, Borys. [http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/scribe-suicide-squad-pact-79891 \"Scribe In for 'Suicide Squad' Pact\"]. ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''. February 25, 2009.</ref> He later described the film to ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire Online]]'' as \"[[The Dirty Dozen|''Dirty Dozen'']] with supervillains\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=de Semlyen |first1=Phil |title=David Ayer Talks DC's Suicide Squad |url=http://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=42521 |accessdate=October 21, 2014 |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |date=October 20, 2014}}</ref> Ayer had six weeks to write the screenplay, given the release date was already set.<ref name=thr>{{cite news |newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/suicide-squads-secret-drama-rushed-916693 |title='Suicide Squad's' Secret Drama: Rushed Production, Competing Cuts, High Anxiety |date=August 3, 2016 |first=Kim |last=Masters |accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nIn October 2014, Warner Bros. had initially offered [[Ryan Gosling]], [[Tom Hardy]], [[Margot Robbie]], and [[Will Smith]] roles in the film.<ref>{{cite news |title=Suicide Squad Targets Ryan Gosling, Will Smith, Margot Robbie and Tom Hardy! |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=124067 |last=Lesnick |first=Silas |accessdate=October 16, 2014 |publisher=[[ComingSoon.net]] |date=October 15, 2014}}</ref> In November, [[TheWrap]] revealed that [[Jared Leto]] was in talks for the role of [[Joker (comics)|Joker]], for which Gosling was originally sought.<ref name=LetoCast>{{cite web |last1=Sneider |first1=Jeff |title=Jared Leto Eyed to Play The Joker in WB's 'Suicide Squad' |url=http://www.thewrap.com/jared-leto-eyed-to-play-the-joker-in-wbs-suicide-squad-exclusive/ |accessdate=November 8, 2014 |website=[[TheWrap]] |date=November 7, 2014}}</ref> The main cast was announced by Warner Brothers in December 2014 with Smith, Hardy, Leto, Robbie, [[Jai Courtney]], and [[Cara Delevingne]] as Deadshot, [[Rick Flag]], Joker, Harley Quinn, Captain Boomerang, and [[Enchantress (DC Comics)|Enchantress]], respectively.<ref name=DecemberConfirmed>{{cite news |last1=Sneider |first1=Jeff |title=Will Smith, Tom Hardy, Jared Leto, Margot Robbie Set for 'Suicide Squad' |url=http://www.thewrap.com/will-smith-tom-hardy-jared-leto-margot-robbie-set-for-suicide-squad/ |accessdate=February 19, 2015 |publisher=thewrap.com |date=December 2, 2014}}</ref> The studio was also considering [[Viola Davis]], [[Octavia Spencer]], and [[Oprah Winfrey]] for the role of [[Amanda Waller]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kroll |first1=Justin |title='Suicide Squad' Cast Revealed: Jared Leto to Play the Joker, Will Smith is Deadshot |url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/suicide-squad-cast-revealed-jared-leto-to-play-the-joker-will-smith-is-deadshot-1201368867/ |accessdate=February 19, 2015 |work=Variety |date=December 2, 2014}}</ref> Following the announcement of the cast, comic book writer [[John Ostrander]] (creator of the modern incarnation of the [[Suicide Squad#Suicide Squad (vol. 1)|Suicide Squad]]) talked with ''[[Comic Book Resources]]'' about the casting, saying, \"I have no problem with the casting... what I am really impressed by with all of the casting is that they are getting some very good actors to play these parts.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Suicide Squad\" Creator Weighs In on Film Casting, Concept |url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=57562 |last=Renaud |first=Jeffrey |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231202915/http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=57562 |archivedate=December 31, 2014 |accessdate=December 9, 2014 |website=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=December 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, Davis expressed interest in playing Amanda Waller during an interview, saying \"I'm fascinated by [Waller].\"<ref name=\"CastWaller2\"/> Meanwhile, Tom Hardy had to drop out as Rick Flag because of scheduling issues with his film ''[[The Revenant (2015 film)|The Revenant]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/01/15/tom-hardy-drops-out-of-suicide-squad |title=Tom Hardy Drops Out of Suicide Squad |date=January 15, 2015 |last=Collura |first=Scott |work=IGN}}</ref> [[Jake Gyllenhaal]], who worked with Ayer on ''[[End of Watch]]'', was then given an offer to replace Hardy as Flag, but he declined.<ref>{{cite web |first=Justin |last=Kroll |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/jake-gyllenhaal-suicide-squad-rick-flag-1201411414/ |title='Suicide Squad': Jake Gyllenhaal Passes on Rick Flag Role |work=Variety |date=January 21, 2015 |accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> The studio was then looking at [[Joel Edgerton]], [[Jon Bernthal]], and [[Joel Kinnaman]] to play the role.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/jake-gyllenhaal-suicide-squad-rick-flag-1201411414/ |title=Jake Gyllenhaal Passes on 'Suicide Squad' |date=January 21, 2015 |last=Kroll |first=Justin |work=Variety |accessdate=January 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.quirkybyte.com/blog/2017/02/actor-directing-suicide-squad-2/ |title=Will This Controversial Actor Actually Be Directing Suicide Squad 2? |publisher=QuirkyByte |last=Fanai |first=Amy |date=February 17, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=KinnamanTalks>{{cite web |url=http://www.thewrap.com/joel-kinnaman-eyed-to-replace-tom-hardy-in-wbs-suicide-squad/ |title=Joel Kinnaman to Replace Tom Hardy as Rick Flag in WB's 'Suicide Squad' |publisher=The Wrap |last1=Sneider |first1=Jeff |last2=Ge |first2=Linda |date=February 13, 2015}}</ref> In February, [[Jay Hernandez]] joined the cast and Kinnaman was also confirmed to play Flag.<ref name=HernandezKinnamanCast>{{cite news |last1=Sneider |first1=Jeff |title=Jay Hernandez Joining Will Smith, Jared Leto in WB's 'Suicide Squad' (Exclusive) |url=http://www.thewrap.com/jay-hernandez-joining-will-smith-jared-leto-in-wbs-suicide-squad-exclusive/ |accessdate=February 19, 2015 |publisher=thewrap.com |date=February 18, 2015}}</ref> At the [[87th Academy Awards]], it was revealed that Davis had been cast as Amanda Waller.<ref name=DavisCast>{{cite tweet |title=VIDEO - @violadavis confirms to @BenMulroney she'll play Amanda Waller in #SuicideSquad shooting in Toronto! #etalk |number=570296573751648256 |author=etalk |authorlink=etalk |user=etalkCTV |date=February 24, 2015 |accessdate=March 2, 2015}}</ref> In March 2015, boxer Raymond Olubawale was reported to have an unspecified role in the film,<ref name=OlubowaleCast>{{cite web |last1=Buffery |first1=Steve |title=Olubowale's back and ready to rumble with Ruddock |url=http://www.torontosun.com/2015/03/26/olubowales-back-and-ready-to-rumble-with-ruddock |website=Toronto Sun |accessdate=March 30, 2015|date=March 27, 2015 }}</ref> and [[Scott Eastwood]] announced that he had been cast.<ref name=EastwoodCast>{{cite tweet |title=#Breaking - @ScottEastwood confirms to #etalk he's been in Toronto working on #SuicideSquad. More to come tomorrow. |number=582213320326926336 |author=etalk |user=etalkCTV |date=March 29, 2015 |accessdate=March 30, 2015}}</ref> Later that month, it was confirmed that [[Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje]] and Karen Fukuhara had been cast as [[Killer Croc]] and [[Katana (comics)|Katana]], respectively.<ref name=\"CastCroc\"/> [[Adam Beach]], [[Ike Barinholtz]], and [[Jim Parrack]] were added to the cast in April 2015.<ref name=CastVarietyMisc/> In January 2016, [[Ben Affleck]] was confirmed to reprise his role as [[Batman]] from ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]''.<ref name=\"Batman-Suicide-Squad-confirmed\" />\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Suicide Squad filming in Toronto 11.jpg|thumb|Filming of a [[Car chase|chase sequence]] on [[Yonge Street]] in Downtown [[Toronto]], May 2015]]\n\nFilming began on April 13, 2015 in Toronto.<ref>{{cite news |title=Suicide Squad Will Officially Start Filming April 13th |url=http://dccomicsmovie.com/suicide-squad-will-officially-start-filming-april-13th/ |accessdate=April 8, 2015 |work=DC Comics Movie |date=March 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |title=Day 1 #SuicideSquad |user=DavidAyerMovies |number=587710878100893696 |author=Ayer, David |authorlink=David Ayer |accessdate=April 13, 2015 |date=April 13, 2015}}</ref> On April 26 and 27, filming took place at Hy's Steakhouse.<ref>{{cite news |title='Suicide Squad' filming locations in Toronto on April 26 & 27 |url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2015/04/24/suicide-squad-filming-locations-in-toronto-on-april-26-27/ |accessdate=April 26, 2015 |work=On Location Vacations |author=Christine |date=April 24, 2015}}</ref> A \"snowstorm\" scene was filmed on April 29 on Adelaide St. and in Ching Lane.<ref>{{cite news |title='Suicide Squad' is filming a \"snowstorm\" scene in Toronto tonight |url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2015/04/29/suicide-squad-is-filming-a-snowstorm-scene-in-toronto-tonight/ |accessdate=May 2, 2015 |author=Christine |work=On Location Vacations |date=April 29, 2015}}</ref> On May 5, a few major scenes were filmed in downtown Toronto next to Yonge and Dundas Square.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.news1130.com/2015/05/06/entertainment-city-suicide-squad/ |title=Entertainment City: 'Suicide Squad' |publisher=News1130 |date=May 6, 2015 |accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> Principal photography [[wrap (filmmaking)|wrapped]] in August 2015 after additional filming took place in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/475391-production-wraps-on-suicide-squad-movie#/slide/1 |title=Production Wraps on Suicide Squad Movie |publisher=ComingSoon.net |last=Perry |first=Spencer |date=August 24, 2015 |accessdate=November 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=DavidAyerMovies |number=637280237806465024 |title=It's a wrap folks! #SuicideSquad #WarnerBros #DCcomics |author=Ayer, David |date=August 28, 2015 |accessdate=November 16, 2015}}</ref> Additional filming ensued in 2016 following Warner's desire to make a more lighthearted and comedic tone akin to the trailers, especially as ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]'' was criticized for being too somber; it was reported the reshoots cost as much as $22 million (more than the typical $6\u201310 million that additional filming costs).<ref name=cinemascore/> It was also confirmed that [[Zack Snyder]] filmed a scene with the Flash while shooting ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]'' in London, while Ayer was in post-production on ''Suicide Squad''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/suicide-squad-justice-league-cameo-scene-2016-8 |title=Suicide Squad 'Justice League' Cameo Scene |date=August 7, 2016 |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> Ayer confirmed that the film was completed on June 24, 2016.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=DavidAyerMovies |number=746361454970834944 |title=Squad is completed! Finished final mix and coloring. Now it's off to the lab and then the world. Nothing like it out there. It.Is.a.Beast. |author=Ayer, David |date=June 24, 2016}}</ref> Despite the involvement of multiple editors in the process, only [[John Gilroy (film editor)|John Gilroy]] is named in the main credit sequence.<ref name=thr/> It was later revealed that many of Jared Leto's scenes were omitted from the final cut.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/suicide-squad-jared-leto-joker-scenes-cut-deleted-1201831587/ |title='Suicide Squad': Jared Leto Addresses How Many Joker Scenes Were Cut |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |first=Lamarco |last=McClendon |date=August 5, 2016 |accessdate=August 31, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/suicide-squad-jared-leto-says-917290 |title='Suicide Squad': Jared Leto Teases Joker Scenes That Were Cut From the Movie |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |first=Eli |last=Flesch |date=August 4, 2016 |accessdate=August 31, 2016}}</ref> An interview with Leto revealed that he was upset over the removal of his work.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Osborn |first1=Alex |title=Joker Actor Jared Leto Reportedly Feels He Was \"Tricked\" Into Suicide Squad |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/08/16/joker-actor-jared-leto-reportedly-feels-he-was-tricked-into-suicide-squad |website=IGN |accessdate=January 3, 2017 |date=August 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Porter |first1=Matt |title=Suicide Squad: Jared Leto Says He Shot Enough Joker Material for a Whole Movie, Lobbied for R Rating |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/08/08/suicide-squad-jared-leto-says-he-shot-enough-joker-material-for-a-whole-movie-lobbied-for-r-rating |website=IGN |accessdate=January 3, 2017 |date=August 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{main|Suicide Squad (soundtrack)}}\n[[Academy Award]]-winning composer [[Steven Price (composer)|Steven Price]], who previously worked with Ayer on ''[[Fury (2014 film)|Fury]]'', composed the score for ''Suicide Squad''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Behind The Scenes Look At Suicide Squad Scoring Session |url=https://comicbook.com/dc/2016/05/29/behind-the-scenes-look-at-suicide-squad-scoring-session/ |publisher=comicbook.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160530154324/http://comicbook.com/dc/2016/05/29/behind-the-scenes-look-at-suicide-squad-scoring-session/ |archivedate=May 30, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ''Suicide Squad: Original Motion Picture Score'' was announced for a release date of August 8, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://comicbook.com/2016/07/16/suicide-squad-official-score-tracklist-revealed/ |title=Suicide Squad Official Score Tracklist Revealed |first=Russ |last=Burlingame |publisher=Comicbook.com |date=July 16, 2016 |accessdate=July 19, 2016}}</ref> A soundtrack album for the film, titled ''Suicide Squad: The Album'', was announced in June 2016, and released on August 5, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jay |last=Jayson |url=http://comicbook.com/dc/2016/06/16/suicide-squad-movie-soundtrack-revealed/ |title=Suicide Squad Movie Soundtrack Revealed |publisher=Comicbook.com |date=June 16, 2016 |accessdate=June 28, 2016}}</ref> The album's first single, \"[[Heathens (song)|Heathens]]\" by [[Twenty One Pilots]], was released on June 20, 2016.<ref name=\"Suicide Soundtrack\">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7408822/suicide-squad-soundtrack-eminem-skrillex-lil-wayne-twenty-one-pilots |title='Suicide Squad' Soundtrack: Skrillex & Rick Ross, Panic! at the Disco Cover 'Bohemian Rhapsody' & More |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |first=Gil |last=Kaufman |date=June 17, 2016 |accessdate=June 22, 2016}}</ref> A music video for the song, set in a prison and featuring footage from the film, was released on June 21.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.idolator.com/7637725/twenty-one-pilots-suicide-squad-heathens-video |title=Twenty One Pilots Hang In A Prison For \"Heathens\" Video: Watch |publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |first=Rachel |last=Sonis |date=June 22, 2016 |accessdate=June 22, 2016}}</ref> \"[[Sucker for Pain]]\" was released as the second single on June 24.<ref name=\"Suicide Soundtrack\"/> The album's third single, \"[[Purple Lamborghini]]\" by [[Skrillex]] and [[Rick Ross]], was released on July 22.<ref name='Skrillex teases \"Purple Lamborghini\" music video'>{{cite web |title=Skrillex teases 'Purple Lamborghini' music video |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BG29c4SyaD7/ |publisher=Instagram}}</ref> \"Gangsta\" by [[Kehlani]]; \"Standing in the Rain\" by [[Action Bronson]], [[Mark Ronson]], and [[Dan Auerbach]] of [[The Black Keys]]; \"Medieval Warfare\" by [[Grimes (musician)|Grimes]]; and a cover of [[Queen (band)|Queen]]'s \"[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\" performed by [[Panic! at the Disco]] were released as four promotional singles on August 2, August 3, and August 4, 2016 respectively, with \"Medieval Warfare\" and \"Bohemian Rhapsody\" being released on the same day.<ref>{{cite web |title=Suicide Squad: The Album |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/suicide-squad-the-album/id1125281254 |publisher=iTunes Store |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804050749/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/suicide-squad-the-album/id1125281254 |archivedate=August 4, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Visual effects===\nThe visual effects are provided by [[Moving Picture Company]], [[Sony Imageworks]], Mammal Studios and Ollin VFX and Supervised by Robert Winter, Mark Breakspaer, Gregory D. Liegey, Charlie Iturriaga and [[Jerome Chen (special effects artist)|Jerome Chen]] as the Production Supervisor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.artofvfx.com/suicide-squad/|title=SUICIDE SQUAD - The Art of VFX|website=www.artofvfx.com|date=June 24, 2016 |accessdate=July 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Suicide Squad'' premiered at the [[Beacon Theatre (New York City)|Beacon Theatre]] in New York City on August 1, 2016. The subsequent London premiere took place on August 3, 2016.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.ikonlondonmagazine.com/will-smith-and-margot-robbie-on-the-red-carpet-at-the-london-premiere-of-suicide-squad/ | title= Will Smith And Margot Robbie On The Red Carpet At The London Premiere Of Suicide Squad | publisher= Ikon London Magazine | date= 4 August 2016 | accessdate=23 February 2018}}</ref> It was theatrically released in the United States and in the UK on August 5, 2016, in 2D, 3D and IMAX 3D.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slashfilm.com/dc-movie-slate-revealed/ |title=DC Comics Movies Announced: 'Suicide Squad,' 'Wonder Woman,' 'Justice League,' 'The Flash,' 'Aquaman' |last=Fischer |first=Russ |publisher=[[/Film]] |date=October 15, 2014 |accessdate=October 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\n''Suicide Squad'' held a panel at the 2015 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]], with stars Smith, Robbie, Courtney, Davis, and Kinnaman among those who appeared. A trailer intended to be exclusive to the event premiered, but was leaked online, with Warner Bros. responding by stating they would not release an official version.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2015/07/comic-con-suicide-squad-deadpool-pirated-footage-leaks-1201474871/ |title=Will Comic Con Leaks Of 'Suicide Squad' And 'Deadpool' Stop Studios From Showing Exclusive Footage? |last=Fleming, Jr. |first=Mike |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=July 12, 2015 |accessdate=July 19, 2015}}</ref> However, the following day, Warner Bros. released an official version, stating: \"Warner Bros. Pictures and our anti-piracy team have worked tirelessly over the last 48 hours to contain the ''Suicide Squad'' footage that was pirated from Hall H on Saturday. We have been unable to achieve that goal. Today we will release the same footage that has been illegally circulating on the web, in the form it was created and high quality with which it was intended to be enjoyed. We regret this decision as it was our intention to keep the footage as a unique experience for the Comic-Con crowd, but we cannot continue to allow the film to be represented by the poor quality of the pirated footage stolen from our presentation.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2015/07/suicide-squad-official-movie-footage-exclusive-1201475371/ |title=Warner Bros Releases 'Suicide Squad' Footage After Being Frustrated By Comic Con Pirates |last=Fleming, Jr. |first=Mike |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=July 13, 2015 |accessdate=July 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Suicide Squad'' was released on Digital HD on November 15, 2016, and on Blu-ray, 4K Ultra-HD Blu-Ray, Blu-Ray 3D, and DVD on December 13, 2016. An [[Director's cut#Extended cuts and special editions|extended cut]] of the film is included in the home entertainment release, containing roughly thirteen minutes of footage absent from the theatrical version.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=SuicideSquadWB |number=783685958034034689 |date=October 5, 2016 |title=#SuicideSquad Extended Cut. Spread the word. |access-date=May 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/suicide-squad-extended-cut-be-935299 |title='Suicide Squad' Extended Cut to Be Released After All |first=Aaron |last=Couch |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=October 5, 2016 |accessdate=October 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/10/05/suicide-squad-extended-cut-coming-to-blu-ray |title=SUICIDE SQUAD EXTENDED CUT COMING TO BLU-RAY |first=Nicole |last=Carpenter |work=[[IGN]] |date=October 5, 2016 |accessdate=October 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n''Suicide Squad'' was a box office success,<ref name=\"HT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2016/09/26/suicide-squad-warner-bros-did-everything-right-except-make-a-good-movie/ |title='Suicide Squad': Warner Bros. Did Everything Right Except Make A Good Movie |author=Scott Mendelson |work=[[Forbes]] |date=September 26, 2016 |accessdate=September 26, 2016}}</ref> grossing $325.1 million in the United States and Canada and $421.7 million in other territories for a worldwide total of $746.8 million, against a production budget of $175 million ($325 million including advertising and promotion costs).<ref name=BOM /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mobile.nytimes.com/2016/08/08/movies/making-suicide-squad-a-smash-despite-withering-reviews.html |title=Making 'Suicide Squad' a Smash, Despite Withering Reviews |author=Brooks Barnes |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 7, 2016 |accessdate=August 9, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/08/suicide-squad-crosses-500-million-worldwide-box-office-1201805484/ |title='Suicide Squad' Shoots Past $500M At Worldwide Box Office |last=Tartaglione |first=Nancy |date=August 18, 2016|access-date=August 19, 2016}}</ref> ''Suicide Squad'' was highly anticipated by audiences worldwide, despite the negative critical reception and lower-than-expected box office performance of ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]'' in March.<ref name=\"LATimes\"/> It recorded a worldwide opening of $267.1 million from 59 countries and IMAX global debut of $18.2 million, both set new records for the month of August.<ref name=\"FORBES\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2016/08/07/box-office-suicide-squad-nabs-huge-267m-global-debut/ |title=Box Office: 'Suicide Squad' Nabs Huge $267M Global Debut |author=Scott Mendelson |work=[[Forbes]] |date=August 7, 2016 |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> That is also the second-best debut worldwide for a DC property after ''Dawn of Justice '' ($422.5 million) and the seventh best for a superhero title.<ref name=\"DEADD\"/> ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' highlighted that ''Dawn of Justice'' had an advantage of receiving a coveted day-and-date release with China, while ''Suicide Squad'' did not secure a release date in the country.<ref name=\"THR3\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-suicide-squad-opens-917863 |title=Box Office: 'Suicide Squad' Opens to Big $135M But Drops Sharply Saturday |author=Pamela McClintock |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 7, 2016 |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Forbes]]'' pointed out that had the film secured a release in China, it may well have matched or topped the $773 million total of ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]'' and the $782 million gross of ''[[Deadpool (film)|Deadpool]]''.<ref name=\"HT\"/> ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' calculated the net profit of the film to be $158.45 million, when factoring together all expenses and revenues for the film, making it the 10th most profitable release of 2016.<ref name=profit>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2017/03/suicide-squad-box-office-profit-2016-1202052792/ |title=No. 10 'Suicide Squad' Box Office Profits \u2013 2016 Most Valuable Movie Blockbuster Tournament |last=Fleming Jr |first=Mike |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=March 27, 2017 |accessdate=March 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====North America====\nProjections for its opening weekend in the United States and Canada were being continuously revised upwards starting from $100 million to as high as $150 million.<ref name=\"preview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/box-office-suicide-squad-tracking-911029 |title=Box Office: 'Suicide Squad' Tracking for Enormous $125M U.S. Debut |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=July 14, 2016 |accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"preview2\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/07/suicide-squad-will-smith-august-opening-box-office-record-1201786609/ |title='Suicide Squad' Gunning For August & Will Smith Opening Records \u2013 Box Office |website=Deadline Hollywood|date=July 14, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/07/jason-bourne-bad-moms-nerve-opening-weekend-box-office-results-1201795475/ |title='Bourne' Gets His $60M; 'Moms' Purses Mid-$20M; 'Nerve' Steady \u2013 Box Office Sunday AM |first=Anita |last=Busch |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=July 31, 2016 |accessdate=July 31, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=4211&p=.htm |title='Jason Bourne' Tops Weekend with $60M; 'Star Trek Beyond' Suffers Big Second Weekend Drop |first=Brad |last=Brevet |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |date=July 31, 2016 |accessdate=August 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/box-office-suicide-squad-headed-916471 |title=Box-Office Preview: Can 'Suicide Squad' Best 'Deadpool' in U.S. Debut? |first=Pamela |last=McClintock |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 2, 2016 |accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref> The film opened across 4,255 theaters, the widest for the month of August. Of that, 382 theaters were in IMAX, over 490 large-format screens locations, 270+ drive-ins, 180+ [[D-Box]] locations and over 200 dine-in/luxury theaters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=4213 |title='Suicide Squad' Set for August Opening Record Despite Negative Reviews |author=Brad Brevet |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |date=August 4, 2016 |accessdate=August 5, 2016}}</ref> It opened Friday, August 5, 2016, on about 11,000 screens and earned $65.1 million, marking the biggest August opening and single day, and the third biggest opening day gross of 2016. Of that, $5.8 million came from IMAX theaters, also a new August record.<ref name=\"FORBES1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2016/08/06/box-office-suicide-squad-scores-insane-65m-friday/ |title=Box Office: 'Suicide Squad' Scores Insane $65M Friday |author=Scott Mendelson |work=[[Forbes]] |date=August 6, 2016 |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> This includes $20.5 million it earned from Thursday previews, which began at 6:00 pm, setting the record for biggest-ever preview of August and the second biggest for a non-sequel film (behind ''[[Man of Steel (film)|Man of Steel]]''). IMAX comprised $2.4 million (12%) of that figure.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-suicide-squad-rockets-917376 |title=Box Office: 'Suicide Squad' Rockets to $20.5M Thursday Night |author=Pamela McClintock and Rebecca Ford |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 5, 2016 |accessdate=August 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2016/08/05/box-office-suicide-squad-breaks-first-record-with-20-5m-thursday/ |title='Suicide Squad' Breaks First Box Office Record With $20.5M Thursday |author=Scott Mendelson |work=[[Forbes]] |date=August 5, 2016 |accessdate=August 5, 2016}}</ref> Much like ''Batman v Superman'' and ''[[The Dark Knight Rises]]'', however, the film saw a steep Friday-to-Saturday decline, grossing $38.8 million (a drop of 41%).<ref name=\"DEADD\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/08/suicide-squad-weekend-box-office-opening-will-smith-margot-robbie-1201799046/ |title='Suicide Squad' Opening Weekend Now At $135.1M \u2013 Early Sunday AM Update |author=Anthony D'Alessandro |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 7, 2016 |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"FORBES3\"/> In total, it earned $133.7 million in its opening weekend, setting records for the month of August (previously held by ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]'') and for [[Will Smith]]'s career (''[[I Am Legend (film)|I Am Legend]]'').<ref name=\"DEADD\"/> It is also the second-biggest debut for a non-sequel, behind ''[[The Hunger Games (film)|The Hunger Games]]'' ($152 million), the fourth biggest of the year and the fifth biggest for Warner Bros.<ref name=\"DEADD\"/><ref name=\"FORBES3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2016/08/07/suicide-squad-box-office-a-record-breaking-but-front-loaded-135m-weekend/ |title=Box Office: 'Suicide Squad' Scores Record-Crushing, But Front-Loaded, $135M Weekend |author=Scott Mendelson |work=[[Forbes]] |date=August 7, 2016 |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> IMAX made up $11 million of the opening numbers from 382 theaters, $200,000 shy of breaking ''Guardians of the Galaxy''{{'}}s record. Nevertheless, it did beat ''Guardians of the Galaxy''{{'}}s $7.6 million in terms of premium large format screens which comprised $13 million. For Cinemark XD screens, which made $3.2 million, the sixth-highest opening.<ref name=\"DEADD\"/>\n\nThe opening numbers helped [[Warner Bros.]] push past the $1 billion mark in North America for the sixteenth year in a row. The film also helped the total weekend tickets sales to an unprecedented $221.3 million in August. Previously, August has not exceeded $200 million at the box office in a single weekend in North America.<ref name=\"DEADD\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=4214&p=.htm |title='Suicide Squad' Shoots Down August Record with $135 Million Opening |author=Brad Brevet |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |date=August 7, 2016 |accessdate=August 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/?view=wknd&wknd=32&sort=year&order=DESC&p=.htm |title=Weekend Index \u2013 Aug 5 - 7, 2016 |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=August 8, 2016}}</ref> ''Suicide Squad'' scored a massive debut primarily on the backs of the under-35 set which made up 76% of the opening weekend.<ref name=\"F4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2016/08/11/suicide-squad-4-reasons-its-box-office-blowout-is-good-news/ |title='Suicide Squad': 4 Reasons Its Box Office Blowout Is Good News |author=Scott Mendelson |work=[[Forbes]] |date=August 11, 2016 |accessdate=August 12, 2016}}</ref> Audiences were also diverse, with [[African-American]]s and [[Hispanic Americans]] making up 41% of the patrons.<ref name=\"F4\"/>\n\nFollowing its record breaking opening weekend, it posted the biggest August Monday gross with $13.1 million, a drop of 56.5% from its Sunday gross. This broke ''Guardians of the Galaxy''{{'}}s previous record of $11.7 million,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/08/suicide-squad-box-office-second-weekend-sausage-party-seth-rogen-petes-dragon-florence-foster-jenkins-1201800933/ |title='Suicide Squad' Secures Record Monday Haul For August, Eyes $51M-$54M In 2nd Weekend \u2013 B.O. Preview |author=Anthony D'Alessandro |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 9, 2016 |accessdate=August 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2016/08/09/box-office-suicide-squad-earns-13-million-monday-for-146m-cume/ |title=Box Office: 'Suicide Squad' Scores Solid $13M Monday For $146M In Total Earnings |author=Scott Mendelson |work=[[Forbes]] |date=August 9, 2016 |accessdate=August 10, 2016}}</ref> and also the biggest August Tuesday with $14.3 million, up 9% from its Monday take.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/08/suicide-squad-tuesday-august-box-office-record-captain-american-civil-war-batman-v-superman-1201801379/ |title='Suicide Squad' Super Tuesday Not Only An August Record, But Also Beats 'Civil War' |author=Anthony D'Alessandro |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 10, 2016 |accessdate=August 10, 2016}}</ref> The film has earned the biggest Friday, Saturday, Sunday, Monday and Tuesday in August history.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2016/08/10/box-office-suicide-squad-tops-x-men-apocalypse-in-five-days/ |title=Box Office 'Suicide Squad' Tops 'X-Men: Apocalypse' In Five Days |author=Scott Mendelson |work=[[Forbes]] |date=August 10, 2016 |accessdate=August 10, 2016}}</ref> It made $179.1 million in its first week of release, the fourth biggest of the year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2016/08/12/box-office-suicide-squad-ends-first-week-with-179-1m/ |title=Box Office: 'Suicide Squad' Ends First Week With $179.1M In Cumulative Earnings |author=|accessdate=August 13, 2016}}</ref> Despite earning $13.4 million on its second Friday, the film dropped 79%, slightly less than ''Batman v Superman''{{'}}s 81% drop.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2016/08/13/friday-box-office-suicide-squad-plunges-79-holding-no-better-than-batman-v-superman/ |title=Friday Box Office: 'Suicide Squad' Plunges 79%, Holding No Better Than 'Batman V Superman' |author=Scott Mendelson |work=[[Forbes]] |date=August 13, 2016 |accessdate=August 13, 2016}}</ref> Following a first-place finish in its first weekend of release, the film faced a steep decline of 67.2% in its [[Second weekend in box office performance|second weekend]], earning an estimated $43.8 million to score the biggest August second weekend gross. It also passed the $200 million mark in ten days and was able to hold the top spot for the second time in a row despite competition from the comedy ''[[Sausage Party]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2016/08/14/box-office-suicide-squad-tumbles-67-for-43-77m-weekend/ |title=Box Office: 'Suicide Squad' Tumbles 67% For $43.77M Weekend |author=Scott Mendelson |work=[[Forbes]] |date=August 14, 2016 |accessdate=August 14, 2016}}</ref> However, the drop is one of the biggest declines for a studio superhero film, and for Warner Bros., which ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' called it \"deja vu all over again\" after ''Batman v Superman'' tumbled 69% in its second weekend earlier in the year. The second weekend decline is the second biggest in summer history, behind ''[[Warcraft (film)|Warcraft]]''{{'}}s historic 70% drop in June of the same year. The site also highlighted possible reasons for the significantly steep drop: dismal reviews, general apathy among moviegoers, altering movie-going habits and competition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/weekend-box-office-sausage-party-919379 |title=Weekend Box Office: 'Sausage Party' Feasts on $33.6M; 'Pete's Dragon' Flounders |author=Pamela McClintock |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 14, 2016 |accessdate=August 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-analysis-suicide-squad-919425 |title=Box-Office Analysis: 'Suicide Squad' and the Summer of Steep Second-Week Drops |author=Pamela McClintock |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 15, 2016 |accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter three weeks of holding the top spot, it was overtaken by ''[[Don't Breathe]]'' on its fourth weekend.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/weekend-box-office-dont-breathe-923578 |title=Weekend Box Office: 'Don't Breathe' Terrorizes Rivals With Winning $26.1M Debut |author=Pamela McClintock |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 28, 2016 |accessdate=August 28, 2016}}</ref> It maintained the second spot in its fifth weekend and registered its best hold with a -20% decline while also passing the $300 million threshold<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2016/09/04/box-office-dont-breathe-tops-suicide-squad-near-300m-star-trek-beyond-nabs-30m-in-china/ |title=Box Office: 'Don't Breathe' Tops, 'Suicide Squad' Near $300M, 'Star Trek Beyond' Nabs $30M In China |author=Scott Mendelson |work=[[Forbes]] |date=September 4, 2016 |accessdate=September 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/09/dont-breathe-light-between-oceans-morgan-labor-day-weekend-box-office-1201812978/ |title='Don't Breathe' Still Has Oxygen, 'Suicide Squad' Seizes $300M+, 'Morgan' D.O.A. : Labor Day Weekend B.O. \u2013 Sunday Update |author=Anthony D'Alessandro |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=September 4, 2016 |accessdate=September 4, 2016}}</ref> on its thirty-second day of release.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2016/09/05/box-office-deadpool-created-unrealistic-expectations-for-suicide-squad-batman-v-superman/ |title=Box Office: How 'Deadpool' Created Pie-In-The-Sky Expectations For 'Suicide Squad' |author=Scott Mendelson |work=[[Forbes]] |date=September 5, 2016 |accessdate=September 6, 2016}}</ref> It remained in the top ten for eight weekends until falling off in its ninth weekend.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2016/10/02/box-office-sully-tops-100m-suicide-squad-exits-top-ten-magnificent-seven-stumbles/ |title=Box Office: 'Sully' Tops $100M, 'Suicide Squad' Exits Top Ten, 'Magnificent Seven' Stumbles |author=Scott Mendelson |work=[[Forbes]] |date=October 2, 2016 |accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Other territories====\nInternationally, ''Suicide Squad'' secured a release in approximately 62 countries.<ref name=\"Overseas40thOpening\"/> It was released in 57 countries (70% of the marketplace) in conjuncture with its North American debut, including France, South Korea, Australia, Russia and the [[Commonwealth of Independent States|CIS]], Brazil, the United Kingdom, Republic of Ireland, Spain and Mexico beginning from Wednesday, August 3. According to trackings, the film was projected to have an opening anywhere between $85 million to $120 million, which would be a new August international debut record.<ref name=\"DEADproj\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/08/suicide-squad-nine-lives-box-office-preview-1201796523/ |title='Suicide Squad' Will Rock August As 'Nine Lives' Cozies Up To Family Audience \u2013 Box Office Preview |first1=Anita |last1=Busch |first2=Nancy |last2=Tartaglione |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 2, 2016 |accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/box-office-suicide-squad-reviews-will-smith-1201828678/ |title=Box Office: Can 'Suicide Squad' Survive Bad Reviews for Record-Breaking Weekend? |first=Brent |last=Lang |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=August 2, 2016 |accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' pointed out that although the film is a lesser known property, similar to ''Guardians of the Galaxy'', stars such as [[Will Smith]] are better known internationally, which could potentially aid the film's performance.<ref name=\"DEADproj\"/> It opened Wednesday, August 3, 2016, in 7 countries, earning $8.1 million.<ref name=\"Overseas1\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/08/suicide-squad-opening-international-box-office-results-1201798378/ |title='Suicide Squad' Pummels $29.6M In Two Days Overseas \u2013 International Box Office |author=Nancy Tartaglione |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 4, 2016 |accessdate=August 4, 2016}}</ref> It opened in 50 more countries on August 4 and 5, earning $53.8 million for a three-day total of $64.6 million from 57 countries.<ref name=\"Overseas1\"/> Through Sunday, August 7, it delivered a five-day opening of $133.3 million from 57 countries on 17,630 screens, nearly double the previous August record held by ''Guardians of the Galaxy''. It also set IMAX opening record with $7 million.<ref name=\"Overseas33rdOpening\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/08/suicide-squad-secret-life-of-pets-time-raiders-jason-bourne-international-box-office-weekend-results-1201799726/ |title='Suicide Squad's Offshore Bow Rises To $133.3M Topping 'Deadpool' Comp \u2013 Intl Box Office Hot Actuals |author=Nancy Tartaglione |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 8, 2016 |accessdate=August 9, 2016}}</ref> It added $58.7 million on its second weekend, a drop of 57% on 15,600 screens in 62 territories.<ref name=\"Overseas35thOpening\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/08/suicide-squad-secret-life-of-pets-sausage-party-petes-dragon-foreign-weekend-results-international-box-office-1201803323/ |title='Suicide Squad' Rounds Up $243M Overseas & $465M Global Cumes; 'Pets' Prancing To $600M WW \u2013 Intl Box Office |author=Nancy Tartaglione |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 14, 2016 |accessdate=August 14, 2016}}</ref> After two straight wins, it was overtaken by the animated ''[[The Secret Life of Pets]]'' in its third weekend.<ref name=\"Overseas36thOpening\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/08/suicide-squad-secret-life-of-pets-ben-hur-war-dogs-weekend-results-foreign-international-box-office-1201806587/ |title=Universal Pictures 'Pets' Collars $674M WW; 'Suicide Squad' Necks $575M Through Sunday \u2013 Intl B.O. Final |author=Nancy Tartaglione |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 22, 2016 |accessdate=August 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIt recorded the biggest opening day of all time for Warner Bros. in Russia ($3.9 million), the biggest August opening day in the United Kingdom ($6.2 million), Brazil ($3 million), South Korea ($2.9 million, also the second biggest Warner Bros. opening day), France ($2.7 million), Sweden ($564,000) and Holland ($517,000, also the biggest opening of the year).<ref name=\"Overseas1\"/> Mexico and Spain opened with $3.9 million and $1.4 million respectively.<ref name=\"Overseas1\"/> In terms of opening weekend, the film recorded the biggest Warner Bros. opening of all time in Russia ($11.4 million). In Brazil, despite playing amidst the [[2016 Summer Olympics]], it managed to open with $11.75 million, marking the biggest August opening weekend of all time, the biggest Will Smith opening, and the fourth biggest opening for a superhero film. Its opening numbers alone made it the second biggest film for the studio there.<ref name=\"Overseas33rdOpening\"/> In South Korea, although the film was off to a strong start, however, it was eventually overtaken by ''[[The Last Princess (film)|The Last Princess]]'' and ''[[Operation Chromite (film)|Operation Chromite]]'' debuting at No. 3. It made $10.8 million in five days (Wednesday to Sunday).<ref name=\"Overseas33rdOpening\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/asia/korea-box-office-princess-reigns-over-weekend-squad-opens-third-1201832502/ |title=Korea Box Office: 'Princess' Reigns Over Weekend, 'Squad' Opens Third |author=Sonia Kil |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=August 7, 2016|access-date=August 8, 2016}}</ref> The U.K. and Ireland posted the biggest opening market for the film with \u00a311.25 million ($14.8 million) from 573 theaters.{{citation needed|reason=no source given|date=January 2018}} Discounting previews, it delivered the third-biggest UK opening of the year, behind ''Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice'' (\u00a314.62 million) and ''Captain America: Civil War'' (\u00a314.47 million). It also became the first new released film of August since 2014 to debut above \u00a33 million.<ref name=\"Overseas33rdOpening\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/aug/09/suicide-squad-tops-uk-box-office-finding-dory-jason-bourne |title=Crime pays: DC's Suicide Squad tops UK box office with \u00a311.25m |author=Charles Gant |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=August 9, 2016|access-date=August 9, 2016}}</ref> Elsewhere, it scored the biggest August opening in Australia ($10.5 million), Mexico ($10.4 million) and Argentina ($2.5 million), while in Spain, it recorded the biggest DC opening with $3.4 million, where it was behind ''[[The Secret Life of Pets]]'' for the weekend and France a $7.9 million opening.<ref name=\"Overseas33rdOpening\"/> It opened in first place in India for a non-local film with $1.8 million from 462 screens, despite facing competition from ''[[Jason Bourne (film)|Jason Bourne]]'' ($1.1 million from 1,027 screens) which also opened on the same weekend. Despite the later film occupying twice the screen number of the former, ''Suicide Squad'' managed to take the top spot.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dongroves/2016/08/07/indian-box-office-dishoom-stays-strong-while-suicide-squad-and-jason-bourne-under-perform/ |title=Indian Box Office: 'Dishoom' Stays Strong As 'Suicide Squad' Takes Top Spot Ahead Of 'Jason Bourne' |author=Don Groves |work=[[Forbes]] |date=August 7, 2016 |accessdate=August 8, 2016}}</ref> Italy opened with an estimated $2.2 million in two days, that's the biggest opening for Smith there.<ref name=\"Overseas35thOpening\"/> It opened in first place in Germany with $6.9 million.<ref name=\"Overseas36thOpening\"/> It opened in Japan \u2013 the film's last market \u2013 on September 9 where it debuted with $3.8 million.<ref name=\"Overseas39thOpening\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/09/sully-mil-jeong-suicide-squad-international-box-office-1201817102/ |title='Sully' Flies Higher In Offshore Debut; 'Suicide Squad' Squashes $700M WW \u2013 International Box Office Final |author=Anita Busch |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=September 13, 2016|access-date=September 14, 2016}}</ref> It finished in second spot (and first among new releases) behind local anime ''[[Your Name]]''. With such a robust opening, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' projected that the film would end its run there around $20 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/asia/japan-box-office-your-name-hit-1201858071/ |title=Japan Box Office: 'Your Name' Heads for Huge Success |author=Mark Schilling |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=September 12, 2016|access-date=September 14, 2016}}</ref> It has so far grossed $9.4 million there.<ref name=\"Overseas40thOpening\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/09/bridget-jones-baby-suicide-squad-chinese-odyssey-sully-overseas-weekend-results-international-box-office-1201821739/ |title='Bridget Jones's Baby' Bows To $30M; 'Suicide Squad' Powers Past $400M \u2013 Intl Box Office |author=Nancy Tartaglione |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=September 18, 2016|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn terms of total earnings, its biggest market outside of North America is the UK ($43.3 million), followed by Brazil ($35.1 million) and Mexico ($27.1 million).<ref name=\"Overseas39thOpening\"/> In two weeks, it became the second-highest-grossing Warner Bros. film of all time in Brazil behind ''Dawn of Justice''.<ref name=\"FI2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2016/08/14/box-office-suicide-squad-tops-465-million-worldwide/ |title=Box Office: 'Suicide Squad' Tops $465 Million Worldwide |author=Scott Mendelson |work=[[Forbes]] |date=August 14, 2016|access-date=August 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n[[File:David Ayer by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Several months after the film's release, writer and director [[David Ayer]] stated that he would have done some elements of ''Suicide Squad'' differently.<ref name=\"collider.com\">{{cite web |last=Cabin |first=Chris |url= http://collider.com/david-ayer-suicide-squad-joker/ |title=David Ayer Pens Message About 'Suicide Squad' Reception & The Joker's Role |publisher=[[Collider.com|Collider]] |date=January 22, 2017 |access-date=May 5, 2017}}</ref>]]\n''Suicide Squad'' received mixed to negative reviews from critics.<ref name=\"varietyc\">{{cite news |last1=Khatchatourian |first1=Maane |title='Suicide Squad' Director Responds to Negative Reviews |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/suicide-squad-bad-reviews-director-responds-1201829629/ |accessdate=January 3, 2017 |work=Variety |date=August 3, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"reviews3\">{{cite news |title='Suicide Squad' Cast Responds to Negative Reviews: \"Critics Have Been Absolutely Horrific\" |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/suicide-squad-cast-respond-negative-917386 |accessdate=August 5, 2016 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 4, 2016}}</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 27% based on 367 reviews, with an average rating of 4.8/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''Suicide Squad'' boasts a talented cast and a little more humor than previous [[DC Extended Universe|DCEU]] efforts, but they aren't enough to save the disappointing end result from a muddled plot, thinly written characters, and choppy directing.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/suicide_squad_2016/|title=''Suicide Squad'' (2016)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media|Fandango]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 1, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a [[weighted mean|weighted average]] of 40 out of 100, based on 53 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/suicide-squad |title=''Suicide Squad'' Reviews |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |work=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=August 5, 2016}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B+\" on an A+ to F scale, while [[PostTrak]] reported filmgoers gave it a 73% overall positive score.<ref name=cinemascore>{{cite web |title='Suicide Squad' $133.6M Opening Breaks August Record To Push Warner Bros. Past $1B Domestic \u2013 Monday Final |url=http://deadline.com/2016/08/suicide-squad-weekend-box-office-opening-will-smith-margot-robbie-1201799046/ |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=August 8, 2016 |access-date=August 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s [[Peter Travers]] wrote, \"[[DC Comics]] tries something different with ''Suicide Squad'', an all-star collection of crime fighting villains\u2014and the result is anything but super.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/suicide-squad-movie-review-w432204 |title='Suicide Squad' Review: DC Bad Guys' Movie is Anything but Super |first=Peter |last=Travers |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=August 2, 2016}}</ref> Richard Lawson of ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' said, \"''Suicide Squad'' is just bad. It's ugly and boring, a toxic combination that means the film's highly fetishized violence doesn't even have the exciting tingle of the wicked or the taboo.\"<ref name=vanity>{{cite web |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/08/suicide-squad-review |title=''Suicide Squad'' Isn't Even the Good Kind of Bad |first=Richard |last=Lawson |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> Writing for ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', [[Joe Morgenstern]] heavily criticized the film saying, \"In a word, ''Suicide Squad'' is trash. In two words, it's ugly trash.\" He further said, it \"amounts to an all-out attack on the whole idea of entertainment,\" and called the film a product of \"shameless pandering\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/suicide-squad-review-weapon-of-mass-depression-1470342658 |title='Suicide Squad' Review: Weapon of Mass Depression - A team of DC Comics bad guys takes on worse guys in this summer extravaganza |first=Joe |last=Morgenstern |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=August 4, 2016 |access-date=August 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nChris Nashawaty of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film B\u2212 saying, \"''Suicide Squad'' kicks off with fizzy, punk-rock ferocity before turning flat and spiraling into familiar formulas,\" and called [[Jared Leto]]'s \"scene-stealing\" Joker \"wasted\" and \"stranded in the periphery\". He concluded by saying, \"For DC, ''Suicide Squad'' is a small step forward. But it could have been a giant leap.\"<ref name=\"ew\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/08/02/suicide-squad-ew-review |title=Suicide Squad: EW review |first=Chris |last=Nashawaty |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> [[IGN]] gave the film 5.9/10, saying: \"''Suicide Squad'' is a decidedly different flavor than ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice|Batman v Superman]]''. It goes for subversive, funny and stylish, and it succeeds wildly during the first act. But then the movie turns into something predictable and unexciting.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/08/02/suicide-squad-review |last=Yehl |first=Joshua |title=The DCEU strikes out with Task Force Meh. |website=[[IGN]] |date=August 2, 2016 |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref> Drew McWeeny from ''[[HitFix]]'' gave it a positive review, writing \"''Suicide Squad'' is not the darkest mainstream superhero comic book movie ever made, nor is it even the darkest live-action film featuring Batman ever made. However, it is gleefully nihilistic, and it takes a different approach to what has become a fairly familiar story form at this point, right at the moment when it feels like superhero movies either have to evolve or die.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=McWeeny |first1=Drew |title=Review: 'Suicide Squad' won't save the world, but it just might save DC |url=http://www.hitfix.com/motion-captured/review-suicide-squad-wont-save-the-world-but-it-just-might-save-dc |website=HitFix |accessdate=August 3, 2016 |date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> Brian Truitt from ''[[USA Today]]'' wrote, \"Compared to its ilk, ''Suicide Squad'' is an excellently quirky, proudly raised middle finger to the staid superhero-movie establishment.\"<ref>{{cite news |date=August 2, 2016|last1=Truitt |first1=Brian |title=Review: 'Suicide Squad' finds sincerity in insanity |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2016/08/02/review-suicide-squad-movie/87915762/ |work=USA Today |access-date=August 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n[[Margot Robbie]]'s performance as [[Harley Quinn]] was better received, with many critics eager to see more of the character in future films.<ref name=\"varietyc\"/><ref name=\"ew\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://wtop.com/entertainment/2016/08/review-harley-quinns-star-born-amid-sloppy-suicide-squad/ |title=Review: Harley Quinn's star is born amid sloppy 'Suicide Squad' |date=August 5, 2016|access-date=August 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.providencejournal.com/entertainmentlife/20160804/harley-quinn-could-be-2016s-most-popular-movie-character |title=Harley Quinn could be 2016's most popular movie character |last=Post |first=David Betancourt The Washington |access-date=August 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clickondetroit.com/entertainment/harley-quinn-steps-up-to-plate-in-suicide-squad |title=Harley Quinn steps up to plate in 'Suicide Squad' |date=August 4, 2016 |access-date=August 5, 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160805215255/http://www.clickondetroit.com/entertainment/harley-quinn-steps-up-to-plate-in-suicide-squad |archive-date=August 5, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In January 2017, David Ayer said he wished he had done certain things differently in the film including story elements, as well as giving more screen time to the Joker.<ref name=\"collider.com\"/>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{main|List of accolades received by Suicide Squad}}\n''Suicide Squad'' was nominated for various awards, winning several. The film was nominated for three [[Grammy Awards]] as well as one [[Critics' Choice Movie Awards]] (winning one), seven [[People's Choice Awards]] (winning one) and received multiple [[Teen Choice Awards]] nominations, including \"Choice AnTEENcipated Movie\", \"Choice Movie Actor: AnTEENcipated\" for Will Smith and Scott Eastwood, and \"Choice Movie Actress: AnTEENcipated\" for Margot Robbie and Cara Delevingne.<ref name=\"TeenChoice\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/767635/teen-choice-awards-2016-nominations-announced-see-the-first-wave-of-potential-winners |title=Teen Choice Awards 2016 Nominations Announced: See the \"First Wave\" of Potential Winners |last=Vulpo |first=Mike |publisher=[[E!]] |date=May 24, 2016 |accessdate=May 25, 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6hm3YMtx8 |archivedate=May 25, 2016 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> It won in both the former and latter categories.<ref name=\"Results\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/07/31/teen-choice-awards-2016-winners-list|title=Teen Choice Awards 2016: See the full list of winners|last=Goodman|first=Jessica|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=July 31, 2016|accessdate=August 4, 2016}}</ref> The film won an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Makeup and Hairstyling|Best Makeup and Hairstyling]] at [[89th Academy Awards]], making it the first film in the [[DC Extended Universe]] to win an Academy Award.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2017 |title=THE 89TH ACADEMY AWARDS 2017 |publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] |date=February 26, 2017 |accessdate=February 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Future==\n{{See also|DC Extended Universe}}\n\nThe film's mid-credit scene leads to the 2017 film ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]''. After the release and financial success of ''Suicide Squad'', Warner Bros. and DC Films announced multiple films being developed featuring Margot Robbie reprising her role as Harley Quinn, including: ''Suicide Squad 2'', ''Gotham City Sirens'', ''[[Birds of Prey (2020 film)|Birds of Prey]]'', and an untitled film centered around Quinn and the Joker.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kroll |first=Justin |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/will-smith-david-ayer-bright-suicide-squad-1201696226/ |title=Will Smith, David Ayer Reteaming on Max Landis Spec 'Bright' |work=Variety |date=March 2, 2016 |accessdate=May 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160929144638/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/will-smith-david-ayer-bright-suicide-squad-1201696226/ |archive-date=2016-09-29 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"DC-THR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/gotham-city-sirens-movie-david-ayer-margot-robbie-reteam-all-female-dc-villains-project- |title=David Ayer, Margot Robbie Reteam for All-Female DC Villains Movie 'Gotham City Sirens' (Exclusive) |work=The Hollywood Reporter |last=Kit |first=Borys |date=December 13, 2016 |accessdate=May 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713013607/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/gotham-city-sirens-movie-david-ayer-margot-robbie-reteam-all-female-dc-villains-project- |archive-date=2017-07-13 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/harley-quinn-vs-joker-movie-spinoff/|title=Warner Bros. is Developing Harley Quinn vs The Joker Spinoff|date=July 21, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=October 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625033753/https://screenrant.com/harley-quinn-vs-joker-movie-spinoff/|archive-date=2018-06-25|url-status=live|df=}}</ref> Various sources report that the studios plan on featuring the anti-heroine in a trilogy of films for the character's first story-arc.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2465419/harley-quinn-rumored-to-be-getting-her-own-dc-trilogy|title=Harley Quinn Rumored To Be Getting Her Own DC Trilogy|author=|date=January 18, 2019|website=CINEMABLEND|accessdate=March 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thegww.com/rumor-warner-bros-exploring-harley-quinn-trilogy-birds-of-prey-gotham-city-sirens-birds-of-prey-v-gotham-city-sirens/|title=Rumor: Warner Bros Exploring 'Harley Quinn' Trilogy: 'Birds Of Prey'; 'Gotham City Sirens'; 'Birds Of Prey v Gotham City Sirens'|author=|date=January 17, 2019|website=thegww.com|accessdate=March 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/dc/2019/01/18/harley-quinn-trilogy-rumored-in-works/|title=Harley Quinn Trilogy Rumored To Be In The Works|author=|date=|website=DC|accessdate=March 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Sequel===\n''[[The Suicide Squad (film)|The Suicide Squad]]'' was announced with intention that David Ayer would return as director from the first film. Ayer left the project to work on ''Gotham City Sirens'' instead.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/1683869/why-david-ayer-is-directing-gotham-city-sirens-instead-of-suicide-squad-2 |title=Why David Ayer Is Directing Gotham City Sirens Instead Of Suicide Squad 2 |access-date=2019-05-02 |website=Cinemablend}}</ref> This followed with [[Gavin O'Connor (filmmaker)|Gavin O'Connor]] hired as co-screenwriter-director, while production was originally slated to begin October 2018, though the script's similarities to ''Birds of Prey'' led to [[principal photography]] delays. [[James Gunn]] was later hired to re-write the screenplay.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://collider.com/suicide-squad-2-gavin-oconnor-not-directing/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-12-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121004151/http://collider.com/suicide-squad-2-gavin-oconnor-not-directing/ |archive-date=2018-11-21 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://discussingfilm.wordpress.com/2018/09/15/todd-stashwick-talks-12-monkeys-kim-possible-suicide-squad-2-more-exclusive/|title=Todd Stashwick Talks '12 Monkeys', 'Kim Possible', 'Suicide Squad 2 & More. (EXCLUSIVE)|date=September 15, 2018|publisher=|access-date=October 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920081353/https://discussingfilm.wordpress.com/2018/09/15/todd-stashwick-talks-12-monkeys-kim-possible-suicide-squad-2-more-exclusive/|archive-date=2018-09-20|url-status=live|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Sandy Schaefer |url=https://screenrant.com/suicide-squad-2-production-start-2018/ |title=Suicide Squad 2 Production Start Set for 2018 |website=Screen Rant |date=December 11, 2017 |access-date=December 16, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171218120627/https://screenrant.com/suicide-squad-2-production-start-2018/ |archive-date=2017-12-18 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Marc |first=Christopher |url=https://thegww.com/update-will-smith-sets-production-schedules-for-bad-boys-for-life-and-bright-2-as-suicide-squad-2-is-delayed/ |title=UPDATE: WILL SMITH SETS PRODUCTION SCHEDULES FOR ''BAD BOYS FOR LIFE'' AND ''BRIGHT 2'' AS ''SUICIDE SQUAD 2'' IS DELAYED |date=August 18, 2018 |work=OmegaUnderground |publisher=TheGWW |access-date=August 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gonzalez|first=Umberto|last2=Verhoeven|first2=Beatrice|url=https://www.thewrap.com/james-gunn-suicide-squad-2-for-dc/|title=James Gunn in Talks to Write ''Suicide Squad 2'' for DC, Eyed to Direct (Exclusive)|date=October 9, 2018|work=TheWrap|access-date=October 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009184648/https://www.thewrap.com/james-gunn-suicide-squad-2-for-dc/|archive-date=2018-10-09|url-status=live|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Prasad|first=R.A|url=https://pursuenews.com/suicide-squad-2-director-zack-snyder-geoff-johns-reportedly-on-producer-team/|title=''Suicide Squad 2'': Director Zack Snyder & Geoff Johns Reportedly On Producer Team|date=October 11, 2018|work=PursueNews|access-date=October 11, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025155323/https://pursuenews.com/suicide-squad-2-director-zack-snyder-geoff-johns-reportedly-on-producer-team/|archive-date=2018-10-25|url-status=live|df=}}</ref> It is scheduled to be released on August 6, 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/warner-bros-release-dates-galore-doctor-sleep-checks-in-this-november-the-witches-oct-2020-the-suicide-squad-returns-in-2021-1202546092/|title=Warner Bros. Release Dates Galore: 'Doctor Sleep' Checks In This November, 'The Witches' Oct. 2020; 'The Suicide Squad' Returns In 2021|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=January 30, 2019|access-date=January 30, 2019}}</ref> It was also announced that Gunn will direct the film.\n\nIn February 2019, [[Margot Robbie]] was confirmed to reprise her role as Harleen Quinzel / Harley Quinn.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/markhughes/2019/02/13/why-the-future-of-dceu-movies-looks-brighter-than-ever/#38ef45cc676d|title=Why The Future Of DCEU Movies Looks Brighter Than Ever (Updated)|last=Hughes|first=Mark|work=[[Forbes]]|date=February 13, 2019|access-date=February 28, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/76W7UDMLd|archivedate=February 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2019, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' announced that [[Idris Elba]] was cast as Deadshot, replacing [[Will Smith]] who dropped out due to scheduling conflicts.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/idris-elba-replacing-will-smith-suicide-squad-sequel-1191349|title=Idris Elba in Talks to Replace Will Smith in 'Suicide Squad' Sequel (Exclusive)|first=David|last=Pountain|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 6, 2019|access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> [[Peter Safran]], who produced ''[[Aquaman (film)|Aquaman]]'' and ''[[Shazam! (film)|Shazam!]]'', stated that the film will be more of a [[Reboot (fiction)|soft reboot]] than a sequel with mostly new characters in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.joblo.com/movie-news/ex-shazam-producer-talks-james-gunn-on-both-the-suicide-squad-gotgv3|title=Ex. Shazam! producer talks James Gunn on both The Suicide Squad & GOTGv3|last=Shirey|first=Paul|publisher=[[JoBlo]]|date=March 16, 2019|access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref> Production is scheduled to begin later that year in September in [[Atlanta, Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/suicide-squad-2-will-smith-not-returning-1202566772/|title=Will Smith Will Not Return As Deadshot In James Gunn's 'Suicide Squad 2'|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=February 27, 2019|access-date=February 27, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/76W0nKBs7|archivedate=February 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/will-smith-the-suicide-squad-sequel-exits-1203151442/|title=Will Smith Exits 'Suicide Squad' Sequel (Exclusive)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=February 27, 2019|access-date=February 27, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/76W0xOD6t|archivedate=February 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/viola-davis-returning-james-gunns-suicide-squad-sequel/|title=Viola Davis Returning For James Gunn's Suicide Squad Sequel|first=David|last=Pountain|work=We Got This Covered|date=February 28, 2019|access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n''The Suicide Squad'' is scheduled to be released on August 6, 2021.<ref name=\"THR Jan 2019 dates\">{{cite web|last1=Couch|first1=Aaron|last2=McClintock|first2=Pamela|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/batman-suicide-squad-sequel-set-2021-release-dates-1181432|title='The Batman,' 'The Suicide Squad' Set 2021 Release Dates|date=January 30, 2019|accessdate=January 30, 2019|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/james-gunn-suicide-squad-2-director/|title=James Gunn to Direct 'Suicide Squad 2\u2032 for Warner Bros.|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|last=Mancuso|first=Vinnie|date=January 30, 2019|accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> On March 29, 2019, it was reported that [[Jai Courtney]] will reprise his role as George \"Digger\" Harkness / Captain Boomerang,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Guerrasio |first1=Jason |title=Jai Courtney says he will be back playing Captain Boomerang in the James Gunn 'Suicide Squad' movie |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/jai-courtney-is-captain-boomerang-in-james-gunn-suicide-squad-movie-2019-3 |website=[[Business Insider]] |accessdate=March 29, 2019 |date=March 29, 2019}}</ref> while on April 5, it was reported that the character of Deadshot was removed from the film and that Elba would be playing a different character instead in order to leave an opportunity for Smith to return in the future.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/suicide-squad-sequel-idris-elba-new-character-1203181518/|title='The Suicide Squad': Deadshot Removed from Sequel as Idris Elba Moves to New Character (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|last2=Kroll|first2=Justin|date=2019-04-05|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref> That same day, it was also reported that both [[Viola Davis]] and [[Joel Kinnaman]] will reprise their roles as Amanda Waller and Rick Flag.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/viola-davis-amanda-waller-the-suicide-squad/|title=Viola Davis to Return as Amanda Waller in James Gunn's 'The Suicide Squad' (Exclusive)|last=Gonzalez|first=Umberto|date=2019-04-05|website=The Wrap|language=en|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://discussingfilm.net/2019/04/05/viola-davis-set-to-reprise-her-role-in-james-gunns-the-suicide-squad-exclusive/|title=Joel Kinnaman Set To Reprise His Role In James Gunn's 'The Suicide Squad' (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Fisher|first=Jacob|date=2019-04-05|website=Discussing Film|language=en|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref> By April 2019, [[David Dastmalchian]] and [[Daniela Melchior]] were cast as [[List of minor DC Comics characters#Polka-Dot Man|Polka-Dot Man]] and [[Ratcatcher (comics)|Ratcatcher]], while [[John Cena]] was in talks for the role of [[Peacemaker (comics)|Peacemaker]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/the-suicide-squad-polka-dot-man-david-dastmalchian/|title='The Suicide Squad' Casts David Dastmalchian as Outlandish Villain|website=Collider|last=Goldberg|first=Matt|date=April 29, 2019|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/daniela-melchior-ratcatcher-suicide-squad-sequel-1203201879/|title=Newcomer Daniela Melchior Eyed For Ratcatcher Role in 'Suicide Squad' Sequel (EXCLUSIVE)|website=Variety|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=April 30, 2019|accessdate=April 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/john-cena-suicide-squad-2-1203191618/|title=John Cena Eyed for 'Suicide Squad' Sequel (EXCLUSIVE)|website=Variety|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=April 17, 2019|accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref> In May 2019, [[Benicio del Toro]] was reported to be in talks to play the film's villain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/michael-rooker-king-shark-suicide-squad/|title=Michael Rooker in Talks to Play King Shark in 'The Suicide Squad' (Exclusive)|website=The Wrap|last=Gonzalez|first=Umberto|date=May 9, 2019|accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thegww.com/exclusive-benico-del-toro-eyed-for-villain-role-in-the-suicide-squad/|title=EXCLUSIVE: BENICIO DEL TORO EYED FOR VILLAIN ROLE IN 'THE SUICIDE SQUAD'|website=Geeks WorldWide|last=Polito|first=Thomas|date=May 10, 2019|accessdate=May 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn July 10, 2019, ''The Hollywood Reporter'' announced that [[Storm Reid]] will play Idris Elba's character's daughter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/storm-reid-joins-james-gunns-suicide-squad-1223553|title=Storm Reid Joins Idris Elba in James Gunn's 'The Suicide Squad'|website=The Hollywood Reporter|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=July 10, 2019}}</ref> On August 19, 2019, [[Flula Borg]] joined the cast.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pearson|first=Ben|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/the-suicide-squad-cast-flula-borg/|title=\u2018The Suicide Squad\u2019 Adds \u2018Pitch Perfect 2\u2019 Actor Flula Borg|website=/Film|date=August 19, 2019}}</ref> On August 24, 2019, Deadline reported that [[Steve Agee]] would voice King Shark.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/suicide-squad-james-gunn-casts-steve-agee-king-shark-1202703447/|title=Comedian Steve Agee Joining James Gunn's 'Suicide Squad' Gang|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|work=Deadline|date=August 24, 2019|access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref> The next day, Deadline reported [[Nathan Fillion]] had joined the cast.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/suicide-squad-nathan-fillion-rookie-star-joins-cast-james-gunn-movie-1202702610/|title=Nathan Fillion Boarding James Gunn's 'The Suicide Squad'|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|work=Deadline|date=August 25, 2019|access-date=August 25, 2019}}</ref> The day after that, it was revealed that [[Taika Waititi]] was cast in an undisclosed role.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/suicide-squad-taika-waititi-in-talks-to-star-james-gunn-dc-film-cast-1202704115/|title=Taika Waititi In Talks For Role In James Gunn\u2019s \u2018Suicide Squad\u2019|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|work=Deadline|date=August 27, 2019|access-date=September 3, 2019}}</ref> On September 3, 2019, Deadline reported that [[Peter Capaldi]] was cast in a role and [[Pete Davidson]] is in talks for a role.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/suicide-squad-snl-pete-davidson-peter-capaldi-cast-james-gunn-dc-movie-1202709645/|title=\u2018Doctor Who\u2019s Peter Capaldi Joining James Gunn\u2019s \u2018The Suicide Squad\u2019; Is \u2018SNL\u2019s Pete Davidson Next?|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|work=Deadline|date=September 3, 2019|access-date=September 3, 2019}}</ref> On September 13, 2019, Gunn released the full cast list for the film, confirming Cena's and Davidson's involvement as well as announcing that [[Michael Rooker]], who was previously rumored to appear in the film as King Shark before said rumors were debunked, would be appearing alongside Julio Ruiz, Jennifer Holland, [[Alice Braga]], Tinahe Kajese, [[Sean Gunn]], [[Juan Diego Botto]], Mayling Ng and [[Joaqu\u00edn Cos\u00edo]] in undisclosed roles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/suicide-squad-2-movie-cast-list-confirmed-james-gunn/|title=Full Suicide Squad 2 Cast Confirmed (But James Gunn Teases He\u2019ll Kill Some Off)|date=2019-09-13|website=ScreenRant|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2471678/looks-like-michael-rooker-will-not-play-king-shark-in-suicide-squad-2-yall|title=Looks Like Michael Rooker Will Not Play King Shark In Suicide Squad 2, Y'all|date=2019-05-13|website=CINEMABLEND|access-date=2019-09-14}}</ref>\n\n===Spin-offs===\n*'''''[[Birds of Prey (2020 film)|Birds of Prey]]''''': Announced to be in development with a script by [[Christina Hodson]]. The film featured Quinn, after leaving the Joker, teaming up with other [[antihero]]es to protect [[Cassandra Cain]] from [[Gotham City]] crime boss [[Black Mask (comics)|Roman Sionis / Black Mask]]. [[Cathy Yan]] serves as director, with [[principal photography]] lasting from January through April 2019.<ref name=\"RobbieBirds\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/margot-robbies-harley-quinn-movie-894486 |title=Harley Quinn Movie in the Works at Warner Bros. With Margot Robbie (Exclusive) |work=The Hollywood Reporter |last=Kit |first=Borys |date=May 16, 2016 |access-date=2018-06-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517095106/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/margot-robbies-harley-quinn-movie-894486# |archive-date=2016-05-17 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/margot-robbies-harley-quinn-movie-894549 |title=Which DC Heroes Could Join Harley Quinn in a Spinoff Movie? |work=The Hollywood Reporter |last=McMillan |first=Graeme |date=May 16, 2016 |access-date=2018-06-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615093627/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/margot-robbies-harley-quinn-movie-894549# |archive-date=2018-06-15 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> The film was released on February 7, 2020 to positive reviews from critics.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/birds-of-prey-harley-quinn-review-roundup |title= Critics say Birds of Prey is a stylized, Deadpool-esque romp that mostly hits its mark |author=Josh Weiss|website=[[SyFy|SyFy Wire]] |date=February 5, 2020 |accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref> It is the first film in the DCEU to receive an R rating from the [[Motion Picture Association of America]].\n* '''''Gotham City Sirens''''': ''Gotham City Sirens'' will be directed by David Ayer, with a script from [[Geneva Robertson-Dworet]].<ref name=\"DC-THR\" /> The project was originally scheduled to begin production mid-2017, though the film was delayed due to the production team's busy schedules on other projects,<ref name=\"DC-THR\" /> and in favor of ''Birds of Prey''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/markhughesfilms/status/811995249887289344|title=Mark Hughes on Twitter|publisher=|accessdate=October 4, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/harley-quinn-movie-r-rated-margot-robbie/#cathy-yan|title=The Harley Quinn Spinoff Might Be an \"R-Rated Girl Gang Film,\" Says Margot Robbie|date=May 8, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=October 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180611151645/http://collider.com/harley-quinn-movie-r-rated-margot-robbie/#cathy-yan#cathy-yan|archive-date=2018-06-11|url-status=live|df=}}</ref> Despite the project's delay, Ayer has continued to work on developing the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christianpost.com/news/director-david-ayer-debunks-rumors-suggesting-gotham-city-sirens-is-dead-211369/|title=Director David Ayer Debunks Rumors Suggesting 'Gotham City Sirens' Is Dead|publisher=|accessdate=October 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929000508/https://www.christianpost.com/news/director-david-ayer-debunks-rumors-suggesting-gotham-city-sirens-is-dead-211369/|archive-date=2018-09-29|url-status=live|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/suicide-squad-david-ayer-gotham-city-sirens-paul-dini/|title=Suicide Squad Director Meets With Gotham City Sirens Creator|date=August 2, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=October 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929000505/https://screenrant.com/suicide-squad-david-ayer-gotham-city-sirens-paul-dini/|archive-date=2018-09-29|url-status=live|df=}}</ref>\n* '''''Deadshot''''': In December 2016, a film centered around Floyd Lawton / Deadshot was announced in development.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/dc/amp/2016/12/13/suicide-squad-deadshot-spinoff-in-the-works-at-warner-brothers/|title=Suicide Squad Deadshot Spinoff In The Works At Warner Brothers|website=comicbook.com|date=December 13, 2016}}</ref>\n*'''Untitled Harley Quinn and the Joker film''': The untitled Harley Quinn and the Joker film was announced, with filmmaking duo [[Glenn Ficarra]] and [[John Requa]] attached as co-writers/-directors/-producers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/margot-robbie-praises-joker-harley-quinn-movie-directors/ |title=Margot Robbie Praises Joker & Harley Quinn Movie Directors |last=Stowe |first=Dusty |date=September 19, 2017 |website=ScreenRant |access-date=October 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012085519/https://screenrant.com/margot-robbie-praises-joker-harley-quinn-movie-directors/ |archive-date=2018-10-12 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> By October 2018 the script was completed, and though the project was originally intended to begin production immediately after ''The Suicide Squad'', the filmmakers have since stated that production would begin once filming on ''Birds of Prey'' has wrapped.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/joker-harley-quinn-movie-scores-crazy-stupid-love-filmmakers-write-direct-1032210|title=Joker and Harley Quinn Movie Coming from 'Crazy Stupid Love' Filmmakers (Exclusive)|publisher=|accessdate=October 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008035212/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/joker-harley-quinn-movie-scores-crazy-stupid-love-filmmakers-write-direct-1032210|archive-date=2018-10-08|url-status=live|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metro.us/entertainment/movies/the-joker-and-harley-quinn-spin-off-update|title=The Joker and Harley Quinn spin-off's writers talk us through their 'deranged' mash-up of 'Bad Santa' and 'This Is Us'|date=September 20, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=October 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926014038/https://www.metro.us/entertainment/movies/the-joker-and-harley-quinn